{"title_page": "Kristang language", "text_new": "{{Infobox language\n|name        = Papia Kristang\n|altname     = Malaccan Creole Portuguese\n|nativename  = ''Kristang''\n|states      = [[Malaysia]]\n|speakers    = {{sigfig|2150|2}}\n|date        = 2007\n|ref         = e18\n|familycolor = Creole\n|fam1        = [[Portuguese Creole]]\n|fam2        = Malayo-Portuguese Creole\n|iso3        = mcm\n|glotto=none\n|glotto2=mala1533\n|glottoname2=Malacca\u2013Batavia Creole\n|glottorefname2=Malacca\u2013Batavia Portuguese Creole\n|lingua      = 51-AAC-aha\n|notice      = IPA\n}}\n\n'''''Papia Kristang''''' (\"speak kristang\"), or just '''''Kristang''''', is a [[creole language]]. It is spoken by the [[Kristang people|Kristang]], a community of people of mixed Portuguese and Asian ancestry of the [[Malays (ethnic group)|Malay]] race, chiefly in [[Malacca]] ([[Malaysia]]).\n\nThe language is also called '''''Crist\u00e3o''''' or '''''Cristan''''' (\"Christian\"), '''''Portugues di Melaka''''' (\"Malacca Portuguese\"), '''''Linggu Mai''''' (\"Mother Tongue\") or simply '''''Papia'''''. Papia means speak. However, locals and most of the Kristang community refer to the language as \"[[Portugis language|Portugis]]\".\n\nIn ''[[Atlas of the World's Languages in Danger]]'' (2010; formerly the ''Red Book of Endangered Languages'') published by [[UNESCO]], Kristang is classified as a \u201cseverely endangered\u201d<ref>{{cite book |last= Moseley|first= Christopher|author-link= |date= 2012 |title= The UNESCO atlas of the world's languages in danger|url= |location= |publisher=World Oral Literature Project |page= |isbn=978-92-3-104096-2}}</ref> language, with only about 2,000 people who speak it.\n\n== History ==\n\nThe Kristang language originated after the conquest of [[Sultanate of Malacca|Malacca]] (Malaysia) in 1511 by the [[Portuguese Empire]]. The community of speakers descends mainly from [[interracial relationship]]s between Portuguese men and local women, as well as a number of migrants from [[Portuguese India]], themselves of mixed [[Luso-Indian|Indo-Portuguese]] ancestry.\n\nKristang had a substantial influence on [[Macanese language|Macanese]], the creole language spoken in [[Macau]], due to substantial migration from Malacca after its takeover by the [[Dutch Empire|Dutch]].\n\nEven after Portugal lost Malacca and almost all contact in 1641, the Kristang community largely preserved its language. The language is not taught at school, although there are still some Church services in Kristang.\n\nHowever, Papia Kristang is facing a decrease in language use within the community.<ref>{{cite journal |last1= Baxter |first1= Alan.N |date= 1996|title= Portuguese and Creole Portuguese in the Pacific and Western Pacific rim|doi= 10.1515/9783110819724.2.299 |access-date=}}</ref> There is a language shift to [[English_language|English]] and [[Malay_language|Bahasa Malaysia]] due to prestige and accessibility that eventually led to a decline in Kristang language use.\n\n== Distribution ==\n\nThe language has about 750 speakers in Malacca<ref>{{harvp|Baxter|2005|page=16}}</ref> and another 100 in Singapore.<ref name=\"Wong 2016\">{{cite web|last1=Wong|first1=Kevin Martens|title=Kodrah Kristang Kaminyu di Kodramintu: Kinyang Ngua (The Kristang Language Revitalization Plan, Phase One)|url=https://kodrahkristang.files.wordpress.com/2016/07/kaminyu-di-kodramintu-v1.pdf|website=Kodrah Kristang|accessdate=August 12, 2016|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161013200854/https://kodrahkristang.files.wordpress.com/2016/07/kaminyu-di-kodramintu-v1.pdf|archivedate=October 13, 2016}}</ref> A small number of speakers also live in other Portuguese Eurasian communities in [[Kuala Lumpur]] and [[Penang]] in Malaysia, and in diaspora communities in [[Perth]], [[Canada]], the [[United Kingdom]] and elsewhere.<ref name=\"Baxter1988\">{{Cite book |url=http://sealang.net/archives/pl/pdf/PL-B95.pdf |title=A Grammar of Kristang (Malacca Creole Portuguese) |last=Baxter |first=Alan N. |publisher=Pacific Linguistics |year=1988 |isbn=0-85883-375-1  |series=Pacific Linguistics Series B - No. 95 |location=Canberra |doi=10.15144/pl-b95 |hdl=1885/145643 |hdl-access=free |ref=harv}}</ref>\n\n===Revitalisation efforts===\nThe language is currently in steep decline, although efforts to revive it have begun in recent years in both the Portuguese Settlement in Malacca and Singapore.\n\n====Singapore====\nThe revitalisation of Papia Kristang in Singapore can be largely attributed to the [https://kodrah.kristang.com Kodrah Kristang]('Awaken, Kristang') initiative led by Kevin Martens Wong<ref name=\"Wong 2016\"/>. This long-term revitalisation initiative seeks to revitalize the language by teaching it to a new generation of learners through complementary classes and the provision of online materials.\n\nIn 2017, they held the first Kristang Language Festival which was attended by more than 1,400 people, including the Portuguese-Eurasian community in Singapore and Singapore\u2019s Deputy Prime Minister [[Teo Chee Hean]].<ref>{{cite web|url= https://kodrah.kristang.com/1st-kristang-language-festival/|title= 1st Kristang Language Festival|accessdate=March 14, 2020}}</ref>\n\nA Kristang Online Dictionary was also launched at the first Kristang Language Festival. The project, ''Pinchah Kristang: A Dictionary of Kristang''<ref>{{cite web|url= https://www.luismc.com/pinchah_kristang/|title= Pinchah Kristang: A Dictionary of Kristang|accessdate=April 15, 2020}}</ref>, is led and developed by Lu\u00eds Morgado da Costa based on the WordNet system developed at the [[Nanyang_Technological_University|Nanyang Technological University]].\n\nThis dictionary also supports another initiative known as ''Jardinggu, or Kristang Lexical Incubator''<ref>{{cite web|url= https://kodrahkristang.wordpress.com/jardinggu/|title= Jardinggu: The Kristang Lexical Incubator|accessdate=April 15, 2020}}</ref>. Initiated in April 2017, the Jardinggu provides a space for the discussion and accelerated addition of new words into the Kristang lexicon. Through this initiative, around 320 new lexemes for concepts that were previously represented by English loans have been suggested by the Kodrah community.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://cpb-us-w2.wpmucdn.com/blog.nus.edu.sg/dist/0/11221/files/2019/12/Wong-special-session.pdf|title=New word development in Singapore Kristang and its implications for variation |publisher= |access-date=15 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n====Malacca====\nThe Kristang-speaking community located at the Portuguese Settlement, or Padri sa Chang (\u201cThe Priest\u2019s Land\u201d) was able to undertake more sustained revitalisation efforts and publicise itself to non-Eurasian Malaysians, and the language. Notably with texts, stories and phrasebooks in Kristang produced by [[Joan Margaret Marbeck]] and through investments and interest from individuals and organisations outside the community. Joan Marbeck has produced three publications: ''Ungu Adanza'' (An Inheritance), ''Linggu Mai'' (Mother Tongue) and the Kristang Phrasebook. She is also credited with writing probably the only play in Kristang, called ''Seng Marianne'' (Without Marianne) and was also instrumental in staging a musical in Kristang - ''Kazamintu no Praiya'' which translates to 'Wedding on the beach'.<ref>{{cite paper|author = HAJA MOHIDEEN BIN MOHAMED ALI|title = THE MAINTENANCE OF MALAYSIA\u2019S MINORITY LANGUAGES| publisher = | date = 2010|url = http://irep.iium.edu.my/9829/4/ICMM2010_p27.pdf|format = PDF|pages = |accessdate=April 15, 2020}}</ref>\n\nWithin the community, there were efforts made together with the help of academics to promote their culture and the Kristang language. In 1988, Alan Baxter published ''A grammar of Kristang'' based on his fieldwork within the community.<ref name=\"Baxter1988\"/>\n\nThere are also supports from the Lisbon-based Calouste Gulbenkian Foundation, which funded and published Marbeck\u2019s Kristang texts<ref>Joan Margaret Marbeck. ''Ungua Adanza'' (Heritage). Lisbon: Calouste Gulbenkian Foundation, 1995</ref>, and the University of Malaya and linguists like Dr. Stefanie Pillai, who have produced a CD of Kristang hymns, and in plans of developing Kristang textbook for beginners.<ref>{{cite web|url= https://unravellingmag.com/articles/revitalising-kristang/|title= Revitalising Kristang: An interview with Stefanie Pillai|accessdate=March 15, 2020}}</ref> \n\nAlong with Malacca Portuguese-Eurasian Association (MPEA) president Michael Gerald Singho, they published a textbook, ''Beng Prende Portugues Malak\u00e1 (Papi\u00e1 Cristang)'', also known as Come, Let's Learn Portugues Malak\u00e1 (Papi\u00e1 Cristang) for people who want to learn Kristang.\n\n==Phonology==\nThe acoustic and articulatory properties of Kristang have not been extensively studied. However, Hancock (1969<ref name=\"Hancock1969\">{{Cite book |last=Hancock |first=Ian F. |date=1969 |title=A Glossary of Papia Kristang Or Malacca Creole Portuguese}}</ref>, 1973<ref name=\"Hancock1973\">{{Cite journal |last=Hancock |first=Ian F. |date=1973 |title=Malacca Creole Portuguese: Asian, African or European? |journal=Anthropological Linguistics|volume=17 |issue=5 |pages=211\u2013238}}</ref>), Batalha (1981)<ref name=\"Batalha1981\">{{Cite journal |last=Bathalha |first=G. N. |date=1981 |title=O Inqu\u00e9rito Lingu\u00edstico Bol\u00e9o em Malaca |journal=Biblos (Coimbra)}}</ref>, and most recently, Baxter (1988)<ref name=\"Baxter1988\"/> have outlined brief descriptions of its sound system.\n\n<br />\n\n===Consonants===\nThe inventory of Kristang's consonant phonemes show a significant parallel to the consonants of Standard Malay in [[Malay phonology]].\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|-\n|+Consonant phonemes of Kristang<ref name=\"Baxter1988\" /><ref name=\"Hancock1969\" />\n! colspan=2 |\n! style=\"width: 5em;\" | [[Bilabial consonant|Bilabial]]\n! style=\"width: 5em;\" | [[Labiodental consonant|Labio-dental]]\n! style=\"width: 5em;\" | [[Dental consonant|Alveo-dental]]\n! style=\"width: 5em;\" | [[Alveolar consonant|Alveolar]]\n! style=\"width: 5em;\" | [[Palatal consonant|Palato-alveolar]]\n! style=\"width: 5em;\" | [[Velar consonant|Velar]]\n|-\n!rowspan=2| [[Stop consonant|Stop]]\n! {{small|[[voicelessness|voiceless]]}}\n| {{IPA link|p}}\n| \n| {{IPA link|t}}\n| \n| \n| {{IPA link|k}}\n|-\n! {{small|[[voice (phonetics)|voiced]]}}\n| {{IPA link|b}}\n| \n| {{IPA link|d}}\n| \n| \n| {{IPA link|\u0261}}\n|-\n!rowspan=2| [[Affricate consonant|Affricate]]\n! {{small|[[voicelessness|voiceless]]}}\n|\n|\n|\n| \n| {{IPA link|c}} {{efn|name=c|Described as ''/ch/'' in the inventory by Hancock (1973).}}\n|\n|-\n! {{small|[[voice (phonetics)|voiced]]}}\n|\n| \n|\n| \n| {{IPA link|j}} \n|\n|-\n!rowspan=2| [[Fricative consonant|Fricative]]\n! {{small|[[voicelessness|voiceless]]}}\n|\n| {{IPA link|f}}\n| {{IPA link|s}}\n|\n|\n| \n|-\n! {{small|[[voice (phonetics)|voiced]]}}\n|\n| {{IPA link|v}}{{efn|name=v|The phoneme {{IPA link|v}} is highly infrequent and restricted in distribution. It is also excluded from Hancock (1975)'s inventory<ref name=\"Hancock1973\"/>.}}\n| {{IPA link|z}}\n|\n|\n|\n|-\n!colspan=2| [[Nasal consonant|Nasal]]\n| {{IPA link|m}}\n| \n| {{IPA link|n}}\n| \n| {{IPA link|\u0272}}{{efn|name=\u0272|/\u00f1/ by Baxter (1988)<ref name=\"Baxter1988\"/> and /ny/ by Hancock<ref name=\"Hancock1973\"/> .}}\n| {{IPA link|\u014b}}{{efn|name=\u014b|/ng/ by Baxter (1988)<ref name=\"Baxter1988\"/>.}}\n|-\n!colspan=2| [[Tap consonant|Tap]]/[[Trill consonant|Trill]]\n|\n| \n|\n| {{IPA link|r}}\n|\n|\n|-\n!colspan=2| [[Lateral consonant|Lateral]]\n|\n| \n| {{IPA link|l}}\n| \n|\n|\n|}\n\n{{notelist}}\n\n====Phonological contrasts====\n\nBaxter (1988)<ref name=\"Baxter1988\" /> established the phonemic inventory of Kristang based on the phonological contrasts in its consonant system. This is summarised and illustrated below with examples of minimal pairs. \n\n*'''Stops''': contrast in the '''initial''' and '''medial''' positions.\n\n{| class=\"mw-collapsible mw-collapsed\" style=\"margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto; border: none;\"\n|+''Examples:''\n! colspan=\"2\" style=\"width: 14em; text-align:center;\"|[[Bilabial consonant|Bilabial]]\n!\n! colspan=\"2\" style=\"width: 14em; text-align:center;\"|[[Dental consonant|Alveodental]]\n!\n! colspan=\"2\" style=\"width: 14em; text-align:center;\"|[[Velar consonant|Velar]]\n|-\n|style=\"width: 7em; text-align:center;\"|<small><u>initial</u></small>\n|style=\"width: 7em; text-align:center;\"|<small><u>medial</u></small>\n|\n|style=\"width: 7em; text-align:center;\"|<small><u>initial</u></small>\n|style=\"width: 7em; text-align:center;\"|<small><u>medial</u></small>\n|\n|style=\"width: 7em; text-align:center;\"|<small><u>initial</u></small>\n|style=\"width: 7em; text-align:center;\"|<small><u>medial</u></small>\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|'''p'''ai\n\n''<small>(father)</small>''\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|ka'''p'''a\n\n''<small>(castrate)</small>''\n|\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|'''t'''eng\n\n''<small>(have, be)</small>''\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|a'''t'''i\n\n''<small>(until)</small>''\n|\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|'''k'''aba\n''<small>(finish)</small>''\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|sa'''k'''u\n''<small>(sack, pocket)</small>''\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|'''b'''ai\n''<small>(go)</small>''\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|ka'''b'''a\n<small>''(finish)''</small>\n|\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|'''d'''eng\n''<small>(dried stingray)</small>''\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|a'''d'''i\n<small>''(duck)''</small>\n|\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|'''g'''aba\n''<small>(praise)</small>''\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|sa'''g'''u\n''<small>(sago)</small>''\n|}\n\n*'''Affricates:''' contrast in the '''initial''' and '''medial''' positions.\n\n{| class=\"mw-collapsible mw-collapsed\" style=\"margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto; border: none;\"\n|+''Examples:''\n! colspan=\"2\" style=\"width: 14em; text-align:center;\"|[[Palato-alveolar consonant|Palato-alveolar]]\n|-\n|style=\"width: 7em; text-align:center;\"|<small><u>initial</u></small>\n|style=\"width: 7em; text-align:center;\"|<small><u>medial</u></small>\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|'''c'''eru\n\n''<small>(smell)</small>''\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|in'''c'''hidu\n\n''<small>(full)</small>''\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|'''j'''eru\n''<small>(son-in-law)</small>''\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|jin'''j'''ibri\n<small>''(ginger, gums)''</small>\n|}\n\n*'''Fricatives''': contrasts in the '''medial''' positions. No clear distinctions between voiced-voiceless pairs and all fricative counterparts can be drawn as:\n**/v/ is highly infrequent and restricted in distribution.\n**Initial /z/ has fallen into disuse.\n\n{| class=\"mw-collapsible mw-collapsed\" style=\"margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto; border: none;\"\n|+''Examples:''\n| colspan=\"2\" style=\"width: 14em; text-align:center;\" |/{{IPA link|f}}/ vs /{{IPA link|s}}/\n!\n|style=\"text-align:center;\" |/{{IPA link|f}}/ vs /{{IPA link|z}}/\n|\n|style=\"text-align:center;\" |/{{IPA link|f}}/ vs /{{IPA link|s}}/\n|-\n| style=\"width: 7em; text-align:center;\" |<small><u>initial</u></small>\n| style=\"width: 7em; text-align:center;\" |<small><u>medial</u></small>\n|\n| style=\"width: 7em; text-align:center;\" |<small><u>medial</u></small>\n|\n| style=\"width: 7em; text-align:center;\" |<small><u>medial</u></small>\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" |'''f'''ai\n\n''<small>(pretend/do)</small>''\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" |ko'''f'''i\n\n''<small>(coffee)</small>''\n|\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" |ba'''f'''a\n\n''<small>(steam)</small>''\n|\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" |ba'''f'''u\n''<small>(breath)</small>''\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" |'''s'''ai\n\n''<small>(go out)</small>''\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" |ko'''s'''i\n\n''<small>(kick)</small>''\n|\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" |ba'''z'''a\n<small>''(pour)''</small>\n|\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" |ba'''s'''u\n''<small>(under)</small>''\n|}\n\n*'''Nasals'''\n**'''Initial position''': only /{{IPA link|m}}/, /{{IPA link|n}}/ and /{{IPA link|\u0272}}/ contrast.\n**'''Medial position''': all nasals /{{IPA link|m}}, {{IPA link|n}}, {{IPA link|\u0272}}, {{IPA link|\u014b}}/ contrast.\n**'''Final position''': no contrasts have been found in identical environments.\n**It is also of note that nasals do not contrast before a consonant.\n*'''Flap/Trill''': contrasts in '''initial,''' '''medial''' and '''final''' positions.\n*'''Lateral liquid''': contrasts in '''initial,''' '''medial''' and '''final''' positions.\n\n== Features ==\n\nIts grammatical structure is similar to that of the [[Malay language]].\n\nBecause of its largely Portuguese vocabulary, and perhaps also as a result of migrations and cultural exchange along trade routes, Kristang has much in common with other Portuguese-based creoles, including the near-extinct creoles of [[Indonesia]] and [[East Timor]].\n\n== Grammar ==\n\nThe usage of verbs is one of the grammatical features of Kristang that is similar to Malay. While Portuguese verbs mainly use morphology, or suffixes, to change a verb\u2019s tense or for it to match with the person and number of its subject, Malay does not change the form of the verb itself. Instead, it makes use of pre-verbal words to convey tense and does not indicate the person or number of the subject in the form of the verb. Kristang\u2019s structure is practically identical to Malay, although the choice of words comes from Portuguese. \n\nTo indicate verb tenses, the following appositions are used: ''jah'' (i.e. from the Portuguese ''j\u00e1'', meaning \"already\", or controversially a corruption of Malay ''dah'', shortened version of ''sudah'', also \"already\") for past tenses; ''ta'' (from ''est\u00e1'', which means \"is\") for present continuous tenses and ''logu'' or ''lo'' (from ''logo'', which means \"soon\") for the future tense. These simplified forms correspond with their equivalents in Malay ''sudah'', ''sedang'', and ''akan'', respectively.\n\n{|class=wikitable\n!English\n!Portuguese\n!Malay\n!Kristang\n|-\n|I eat \n|Eu como\n|Saya makan\n|Yo kumih\n|-\n|I ate/have eaten \n|Eu comi\n|Saya sudah makan\n|Yo ja kumih\n|-\n|I will eat \n|Eu comerei\n|Saya akan makan\n|Yo logu kumih\n|-\n|He eats\n|Ele come\n|Dia makan\n|Eli kumih\n|-\n<sup></sup> \n|}\n\nPluralisation is also the same in Malay as in Kristang. For example in English and Portuguese, an \u2018\u2013s\u2019 is added to make cats or gatos, whereas in Kristang and Malay, the entire word is duplicated , such as gatu-gatu in Kristang, and kucing-kucing in Malay.\n\nAdversity Passive, which is used to talk about situations where a negative action happens to something, but the person or originator of the negative action is not mentioned something, is also present both in Kristang and Malay. The Adversity Passive is signaled by kena (Malay), and by tokah (Kristang). \n\n{|class=wikitable\n!Colloquial Malay \n!Kristang\n!Colloquial English near-equivalent\n|-\n|Ikan kena makan\n|Pesi tokah kumih\n|The fish got eaten\n|-\n<sup></sup> \n|}\n\n= Vocabulary =\n\nA peculiarity of the language is the pronoun ''yo'' (meaning \"I\") which is used in [[northern Portuguese  dialects|Northern Portuguese]]  (pronounced as ''yeu'') as well as Spanish and Italian/Sicilian.\n\nThe Kristang lexicon borrowed heavily from Portuguese, but often with drastic truncation; for example, Portuguese ''padrinho'' and ''madrinha'' (\"godfather\" and \"godmother\") became ''inyu'' and ''inya'' in Kristang. As it is primarily a Creole language, much of its vocabulary is derived from Chinese, Indian and Malay languages to varying degrees.\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|+<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Mohideen, S & Mohideen, S|first=|date=2008|title=Survival of the Minority Kristang Language in Malaysia|url=http://search.proquest.com/docview/85673255/|journal=Language in India|volume=8(7)|pages=1-18|via=}}</ref>\n!Meaning\n!Kristang Word\n!Origin Word\n!Origin Word Language\n|-\n|Shrimp Paste\n|blacan\n|belacan\n| rowspan=\"4\" |Malay\n|-\n|Walking Stick\n|tongkah\n|tongkat\n|-\n|Hoe\n|changkol\n|cangkul\n|-\n|Jellyfish\n|ampeh\n|ampai\n|-\n|Loincloth\n|kachu\n|katchu\n| rowspan=\"3\" |Tamil\n|-\n|Lime\n|churutu\n|surutu\n|-\n|Grandfather\n|tata\n|thatha\n|-\n|Spatula\n|chengsi\n|chiensi\n| rowspan=\"2\" |Hokkien\n|-\n|Lantern\n|aloleng\n|leng tsu\n|-\n|Open-air restaurant\n|kolau\n|kou lau\n|Cantonese\n|-\n|Convent\n|konventu\n|convent\n| rowspan=\"2\" |English\n|-\n|Hospital\n|ospital\n|hospital\n|-\n|Toilet\n|kakus\n|kakhuis\n| rowspan=\"2\" |Dutch\n|-\n|Tombstone\n|kelda\n|kelder\n|}\n[[Metathesis (linguistics)|Metathesis]] was common: for example, Portuguese ''gordo'' \"fat\" gave Kristang ''godru''.  The Portuguese diphthong ''oi'' (or archaic ''ou'') was reduced to ''o'', e.g. ''dois''/''dous'' \"two\" \u2192 ''dos'',  ''\u00e0 noite''/''\u00e0 noute'' \"tonight\" \u2192 ''anoti''/''anuti''.\n \nMany Portuguese words that began with ''ch'', pronounced {{IPA|[\u0283]}} (\"sh\") in modern Portuguese, have the pronunciation {{IPA|[t\u0283]}} (\"ch\" as in \"cheese\") in Kristang. So, for example, Portuguese ''chegar'' \"to arrive\" and ''chuva'' \"rain\" produced Kristang ''chegak'' and ''chua'' (pronounced with {{IPA|[t\u0283]}}). This could have been due to [[Malay language|Malay]] influence, or it could be that Kristang preserved the original pronunciation  {{IPA|[t\u0283]}} of Old Portuguese. (Note that Portuguese \"ch\" pronounced {{IPA|[t\u0283]}} occurs in Northern Portugal.)\n\nThe chief resource for individuals to pick up Kristang is a Kristang-English dictionary compiled by Baxter and de Silva<ref>{{Cite journal|last=N Baxter|first=Alan|date=2004|title=A dictionary of Kristang (Malacca Creole Portuguese) with an English-Kristang finderlist|url=https://openresearch-repository.anu.edu.au/bitstream/1885/146269/1/PL-564|journal=Pacific Linguistics|volume=|pages=|via=Pacific Linguistics}}</ref>\n\n== Writing system ==\n\nKristang was and is largely an oral language and has never been taught officially in schools. The first proposal<ref name=\"Baxter1988\"/> for a standard orthography was made in the late 1980s, with the publication of a thesis, \u201cA Grammar of Kristang\u201d by Alan N. Baxter, in which he emphasizes the use of the [[Malay alphabet|Malay orthography]].\n\nAs in most [[Portuguese dialects]], the vowel ''e'' is usually pronounced {{IPA|[i]}} when followed by a syllable with {{IPA|/i/}}; so, for example, ''penitensia'' (\"penitence\") is pronounced {{IPA|[pini\u02c8te\u0272sia]}}.\n\nIn the 1990s, [[Joan Margaret Marbeck]]'s book ''Ungua Andanza'' was published, with the orthography written in a Luso-Malay context.<ref>Joan Margaret Marbeck. ''Ungua Adanza'' (Heritage). Lisbon: Calouste Gulbenkian Foundation, 1995</ref>\n\n== Examples ==\n\n===Numbers===\nMuch of the lexicon for Kristang numbers draws influence from Portuguese, a [[Romance language]]. However, unlike Portuguese, which distinguishes between the masculine and feminine forms of \u201cone\u201d (''um/uma'') and \u201ctwo\u201d (''dois/duas''), numbers in Kristang do not inflect for gender.\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n!English\n!Kristang\n!Portuguese\n!Malay\n|-\n|one\n|ungua/ngua \n|um (''masc.'') / uma (''fem.'')\n|satu\n|-\n|two\n|dos\n|dois (''masc.'') / duas (''fem.'')\n|dua\n|-\n|three\n|tres\n|tr\u00eas\n|tiga\n|-\n|four\n|katru\n|quatro\n|empat\n|-\n|five\n|singku\n|cinco\n|lima\n|-\n|six\n|sez\n|seis\n|enam\n|-\n|seven\n|seti\n|sete\n|tujuh\n|-\n|eight\n|oitu\n|oito\n|lapan\n|-\n|nine\n|nubi\n|nove\n|sembilan\n|-\n|ten\n|des\n|dez\n|sepuluh\n|-\n|}\n\n===Pronouns===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n!English\n!Kristang\n!Portuguese\n!Malay\n|-\n|Me\n|yo\n|eu\n|saya (''formal'') / aku (''casual'')\n|-\n|You (singular)\n|bos\n|v\u00f3s\n|Awak/Kamu\n|-\n|You (plural)\n|bolotudu/bolotu\n|v\u00f3s todos\n|Awak semua/Kamu semua\n|-\n|We\n|nus\n|n\u00f3s\n|kami\n|-\n|He/she/it\n|eli\n|ele, ela, isto\n|dia\n|-\n|They\n|olotu\n|eles\n|mereka\n|-\n|}\n\n===Common phrases===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n!English\n!Kristang\n!Portuguese\n!Malay\n|-\n|Thank You\n|Mutu Merseh\n|Muitas merc\u00eas\n|Terima Kasih\n|-\n|How Are You?\n|Teng Bong?\n|Est\u00e1s bom?/T\u00eam bom?\n|Awak apa khabar?\n|-\n|What's your name?\n|Ki bos sa numi?\n|Qual \u00e9 o seu nome?/Qual \u00e9 o seu nome?\n|Siapa nama awak?\n|-\n|Good Morning\n|Bong Pamiang\n|Boa Manh\u00e3\n|Selamat Pagi\n|-\n|Good Afternoon\n|Bong Midia\n|Bom Meio-dia\n|Selamat Petang\n|-\n|Good Evening\n|Bong Atadi\n|Boa Tarde\n|Selamat Malam\n|-\n|Good Night\n|Bong Anuti\n|Boa Noite\n|Selamat Malam/Tidur\n|-\n|Mother\n|mai\n|m\u00e3e\n|Emak/Ibu/Bonda/Ummi/Mama\n|-\n|Father\n|pai\n|pai\n|Bapa/Ayah/Abah/Abi\n|-\n|Wife\n|muleh\n|mulher\n|Isteri\n|-\n|Husband\n|maridu\n|marido\n|Suami\n|-\n|Old Woman\n|bela\n|velha\n|Wanita Tua\n|-\n|Old Man\n|belu\n|velho\n|Lelaki Tua\n|-\n|Little one\n|Quenino/Keninu\n|Pequenino\n|Si Kecil\n|-\n|Mouth\n|boka\n|boca\n|Mulut\n|-\n|Fat\n|godru\n|gordo\n|Gemuk\n|-\n|Beautiful\n|bonitu\n|bonito\n|Cantik\n|-\n|Party\n|festa\n|festa\n|Pesta\n|-\n|Yes\n|seng\n|sim\n|Ya\n|-\n|No\n|ngka\n|n\u00e3o\n|Tidak\n|-\n|Who\n|keng\n|quem\n|Siapa\n|-\n|What\n|ki\n|que\n|Apa\n|-\n|When\n|kiora\n|quando (\"que hora\")\n|Bila\n|-\n|Where\n|ondi\n|onde\n|Mana\n|-\n|Why\n|kifoi \n|porque (\"que foi\")\n|Mengapa\n|-\n|How\n|klai\n|como\n|Bagaimana\n|-\n|}\n\n===Poem of Malacca===\n:''Keng teng fortuna fikah na Malaka,''\n:''Nang kereh partih bai otru tera.''\n:''Pra ki tudu jenti teng amizadi,''\n:''Kontu partih logu fikah saudadi.''\n\n:''Oh Malaka, tera di San Francisku,''\n:''Nteh otru tera ki yo kereh.''\n:''Oh Malaka undi teng sempri fresku,''\n:''Yo kereh fikah ateh mureh.''\n\n\nPortuguese translation:\n:''Quem tem fortuna fica em Malaca,''\n:''N\u00e3o quer partir para outra terra.''\n:''Por aqui toda a gente tem amizade,''\n:''Quando tu partes logo fica a saudade.''\n\n:''\u00d3 Malaca, terra de S\u00e3o Francisco,''\n:''N\u00e3o tem outra terra que eu queira.''\n:''\u00d3 Malaca, onde tem sempre frescura,''\n:''Eu quero ficar at\u00e9 morrer.''\n\n\nEnglish translation:\n:Who is lucky stays in Malacca,\n:Doesn't want to go to another land.\n:In here everyone has friendship,\n:When one leaves soon has ''[[saudade]]''.\n\n:Oh Malacca, land of Saint Francis,\n:There is no other land that I want.\n:Oh Malacca, where there's always freshness,\n:I want to stay here until I die.\n\n\nMalay translation:\n\n:Siapa beruntung tinggal di Melaka,\n:Tidak mahu ke tanah berbeza.\n:Di sini semua bersahabat,\n:Bila seorang pergi terasa rindu.\n\n:Oh Melaka, tanah Saint Francis,\n:Tiada tanah lain yang ku mahu.\n:Oh Melaka, dimana adanya kesegaran,\n:Aku mahu tinggal di sini hingga ke akhir nyawa.\n\n== See also ==\n*[[Kristang_people|Kristang people]]\n*[[Eurasians in Singapore]]\n*[[Chavacano language]], a similar though [[Spanish language|Spanish]]-derived [[Malayo-Polynesian languages|Malayo-Polynesian]] creole\n*[[Batavia, Dutch East Indies]], as Kristang is also called Malacca\u2013Batavia Creole\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== References ==\n{{refbegin}}\n* {{Cite book |url=http://sealang.net/archives/pl/pdf/PL-B95.pdf |title=A Grammar of Kristang (Malacca Creole Portuguese) |last=Baxter |first=Alan N. |publisher=Pacific Linguistics |year=1988 |isbn=0-85883-375-1  |series=Pacific Linguistics Series B - No. 95 |location=Canberra |doi=10.15144/pl-b95 |hdl=1885/145643 |hdl-access=free |ref=harv}}\n* {{Cite book |url=http://sealang.net/archives/pl/pdf/PL-564.pdf |title=A Dictionary of Kristang (Malacca Creole Portuguese) English |last=Baxter |first=Alan N. |last2=De Silva |first2=Patrick |publisher=Pacific Linguistics |year=2004 |isbn=0-85883-552-5 |location=Canberra |doi=10.15144/pl-564 |series=Pacific Linguistics 564 |hdl=1885/146269 |hdl-access=free |ref=harv}}\n* {{Cite journal |last=Baxter |first=Alan N. |date=2005 |title=Kristang (Malacca Creole Portuguese) \u2013a long-time survivor seriously endangered |url=https://pdfs.semanticscholar.org/871c/1bbde940e1a64a27505a04630ff4e3b1e2ce.pdf |journal=Estudios de Socioling\u00fc\u00edstica |volume=6 |issue=1 |pages=1-37 |ref=harv}}\n{{refend}}\n\n== External links ==\n*[http://kodrah.kristang.com Kodrah Kristang: Kristang in Singapore Revitalization Project and Classes]\n*[http://www.lusotopie.sciencespobordeaux.fr/fernandis.pdf Papia, Relijang e Tradisang, The Portuguese Eurasians in Malaysia]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20091027034428/http://geocities.com/TheTropics/Paradise/9221/ Malacca Portuguese Eurasian Association]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20050409201057/http://www.malaccacom.net/malaccaportuguese/ Malacca Portuguese Settlement]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20050728002511/http://www.eurasians.org/culture_kristang.html  Singapore Eurasian Association Kristang Page]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20130422061132/http://joanmarbeck.com/ Joan Marbeck's homepage]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20041122225051/http://www.geocities.com/jingkli_nona/ Jingkli Nona - a Kristang viewpoint]\n*[http://www.theseira.net/tphoto.html The Theseira family]\n*[https://www.webcitation.org/query?url=http://www.geocities.com/kevinshepherdson/intro_quest.html&date=2009-10-26+01:20:29 The Shepherdson family]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20050828185504/http://www.peranakan.org.sg/index.html The Peranakan Association Singapore]\n*[http://hub.dataline.net.au/~tfoen/eurasiansvc.htm The Eurasian Company of the Singapore Volunteer Corps]\n*[http://www.pasarmalambesar.nl/english/eng.htm/ Pasar Malam Besar festival in the Netherlands]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20091027034428/http://geocities.com/TheTropics/Paradise/9221/ Malaysian Eurasian food]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20120717012748/http://portuguese.meetup.com/members/?localeId=864%2F All Portuguese Language Meetup Groups]\n*[http://www.soton.ac.uk/~psp/ Portuguese people speaking society]\n*[http://www.sil.org/sociolx/ndg-lg-home.html/ Endangered Languages]\n\n{{Languages of Malaysia}}\n{{Languages of Singapore}}\n{{Portuguese Creoles}}\n\n[[Category:Languages of Malaysia]]\n[[Category:Languages of Singapore]]\n[[Category:Portuguese-based pidgins and creoles]]\n[[Category:Endangered pidgins and creoles]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox language\n|name        = Papia Kristang\n|altname     = Malaccan Creole Portuguese\n|nativename  = ''Kristang''\n|states      = [[Malaysia]]\n|speakers    = {{sigfig|2150|2}}\n|date        = 2007\n|ref         = e18\n|familycolor = Creole\n|fam1        = [[Portuguese Creole]]\n|fam2        = Malayo-Portuguese Creole\n|iso3        = mcm\n|glotto=none\n|glotto2=mala1533\n|glottoname2=Malacca\u2013Batavia Creole\n|glottorefname2=Malacca\u2013Batavia Portuguese Creole\n|lingua      = 51-AAC-aha\n|notice      = IPA\n}}\n\n'''''Papia Kristang''''' (\"speak kristang\"), or just '''''Kristang''''', is a [[creole language]]. It is spoken by the [[Kristang people|Kristang]], a community of people of mixed Portuguese and Asian ancestry of the [[Malays (ethnic group)|Malay]] race, chiefly in [[Malacca]] ([[Malaysia]]).\n\nThe language is also called '''''Crist\u00e3o''''' or '''''Cristan''''' (\"Christian\"), '''''Portugues di Melaka''''' (\"Malacca Portuguese\"), '''''Linggu Mai''''' (\"Mother Tongue\") or simply '''''Papia'''''. Papia means speak. However, locals and most of the Kristang community refer to the language as \"[[Portugis language|Portugis]]\".\n\nIn ''[[Atlas of the World's Languages in Danger]]'' (2010; formerly the ''Red Book of Endangered Languages'') published by [[UNESCO]], Kristang is classified as a \u201cseverely endangered\u201d<ref>{{cite book |last= Moseley|first= Christopher|author-link= |date= 2012 |title= The UNESCO atlas of the world's languages in danger|url= |location= |publisher=World Oral Literature Project |page= |isbn=978-92-3-104096-2}}</ref> language, with only about 2,000 people who speak it.\n\n== History ==\n\nThe Kristang language originated after the conquest of [[Sultanate of Malacca|Malacca]] (Malaysia) in 1511 by the [[Portuguese Empire]]. The community of speakers descends mainly from [[interracial relationship]]s between Portuguese men and local women, as well as a number of migrants from [[Portuguese India]], themselves of mixed [[Luso-Indian|Indo-Portuguese]] ancestry.\n\nKristang had a substantial influence on [[Macanese language|Macanese]], the creole language spoken in [[Macau]], due to substantial migration from Malacca after its takeover by the [[Dutch Empire|Dutch]].\n\nEven after Portugal lost Malacca and almost all contact in 1641, the Kristang community largely preserved its language. The language is not taught at school, although there are still some Church services in Kristang.\n\nHowever, Papia Kristang is facing a decrease in language use within the community.<ref>{{cite journal |last1= Baxter |first1= Alan.N |date= 1996|title= Portuguese and Creole Portuguese in the Pacific and Western Pacific rim|doi= 10.1515/9783110819724.2.299 |access-date=}}</ref> There is a language shift to [[English_language|English]] and [[Malay_language|Bahasa Malaysia]] due to prestige and accessibility that eventually led to a decline in Kristang language use.\n\n== Distribution ==\n\nThe language has about 750 speakers in Malacca<ref>{{harvp|Baxter|2005|page=16}}</ref> and another 100 in Singapore.<ref name=\"Wong 2016\">{{cite web|last1=Wong|first1=Kevin Martens|title=Kodrah Kristang Kaminyu di Kodramintu: Kinyang Ngua (The Kristang Language Revitalization Plan, Phase One)|url=https://kodrahkristang.files.wordpress.com/2016/07/kaminyu-di-kodramintu-v1.pdf|website=Kodrah Kristang|accessdate=August 12, 2016|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161013200854/https://kodrahkristang.files.wordpress.com/2016/07/kaminyu-di-kodramintu-v1.pdf|archivedate=October 13, 2016}}</ref> A small number of speakers also live in other Portuguese Eurasian communities in [[Kuala Lumpur]] and [[Penang]] in Malaysia, and in diaspora communities in [[Perth]], [[Canada]], the [[United Kingdom]] and elsewhere.<ref name=\"Baxter1988\">{{Cite book |url=http://sealang.net/archives/pl/pdf/PL-B95.pdf |title=A Grammar of Kristang (Malacca Creole Portuguese) |last=Baxter |first=Alan N. |publisher=Pacific Linguistics |year=1988 |isbn=0-85883-375-1  |series=Pacific Linguistics Series B - No. 95 |location=Canberra |doi=10.15144/pl-b95 |hdl=1885/145643 |hdl-access=free |ref=harv}}</ref>\n\n===Revitalisation efforts===\nThe language is currently in steep decline, although efforts to revive it have begun in recent years in both the Portuguese Settlement in Malacca and Singapore.\n\n====Singapore====\nThe revitalisation of Papia Kristang in Singapore can be largely attributed to the [https://kodrah.kristang.com Kodrah Kristang]('Awaken, Kristang') initiative led by Kevin Martens Wong<ref name=\"Wong 2016\"/>. This long-term revitalisation initiative seeks to revitalize the language by teaching it to a new generation of learners through complementary classes and the provision of online materials.\n\nIn 2017, they held the first Kristang Language Festival which was attended by more than 1,400 people, including the Portuguese-Eurasian community in Singapore and Singapore\u2019s Deputy Prime Minister [[Teo Chee Hean]].<ref>{{cite web|url= https://kodrah.kristang.com/1st-kristang-language-festival/|title= 1st Kristang Language Festival|accessdate=March 14, 2020}}</ref>\n\nA Kristang Online Dictionary was also launched at the first Kristang Language Festival. The project, ''Pinchah Kristang: A Dictionary of Kristang''<ref>{{cite web|url= https://www.luismc.com/pinchah_kristang/|title= Pinchah Kristang: A Dictionary of Kristang|accessdate=April 15, 2020}}</ref>, is led and developed by Lu\u00eds Morgado da Costa based on the WordNet system developed at the [[Nanyang_Technological_University|Nanyang Technological University]].\n\nThis dictionary also supports another initiative known as ''Jardinggu, or Kristang Lexical Incubator''<ref>{{cite web|url= https://kodrahkristang.wordpress.com/jardinggu/|title= Jardinggu: The Kristang Lexical Incubator|accessdate=April 15, 2020}}</ref>. Initiated in April 2017, the Jardinggu provides a space for the discussion and accelerated addition of new words into the Kristang lexicon. Through this initiative, around 320 new lexemes for concepts that were previously represented by English loans have been suggested by the Kodrah community.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://cpb-us-w2.wpmucdn.com/blog.nus.edu.sg/dist/0/11221/files/2019/12/Wong-special-session.pdf|title=New word development in Singapore Kristang and its implications for variation |publisher= |access-date=15 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n====Malacca====\nThe Kristang-speaking community located at the Portuguese Settlement, or Padri sa Chang (\u201cThe Priest\u2019s Land\u201d) was able to undertake more sustained revitalisation efforts and publicise itself to non-Eurasian Malaysians, and the language. Notably with texts, stories and phrasebooks in Kristang produced by [[Joan Margaret Marbeck]] and through investments and interest from individuals and organisations outside the community. Joan Marbeck has produced three publications: ''Ungu Adanza'' (An Inheritance), ''Linggu Mai'' (Mother Tongue) and the Kristang Phrasebook. She is also credited with writing probably the only play in Kristang, called ''Seng Marianne'' (Without Marianne) and was also instrumental in staging a musical in Kristang - ''Kazamintu no Praiya'' which translates to 'Wedding on the beach'.<ref>{{cite paper|author = HAJA MOHIDEEN BIN MOHAMED ALI|title = THE MAINTENANCE OF MALAYSIA\u2019S MINORITY LANGUAGES| publisher = | date = 2010|url = http://irep.iium.edu.my/9829/4/ICMM2010_p27.pdf|format = PDF|pages = |accessdate=April 15, 2020}}</ref>\n\nWithin the community, there were efforts made together with the help of academics to promote their culture and the Kristang language. In 1988, Alan Baxter published ''A grammar of Kristang'' based on his fieldwork within the community.<ref name=\"Baxter1988\"/>\n\nThere are also supports from the Lisbon-based Calouste Gulbenkian Foundation, which funded and published Marbeck\u2019s Kristang texts<ref>Joan Margaret Marbeck. ''Ungua Adanza'' (Heritage). Lisbon: Calouste Gulbenkian Foundation, 1995</ref>, and the University of Malaya and linguists like Dr. Stefanie Pillai, who have produced a CD of Kristang hymns, and in plans of developing Kristang textbook for beginners.<ref>{{cite web|url= https://unravellingmag.com/articles/revitalising-kristang/|title= Revitalising Kristang: An interview with Stefanie Pillai|accessdate=March 15, 2020}}</ref> \n\nAlong with Malacca Portuguese-Eurasian Association (MPEA) president Michael Gerald Singho, they published a textbook, ''Beng Prende Portugues Malak\u00e1 (Papi\u00e1 Cristang)'', also known as Come, Let's Learn Portugues Malak\u00e1 (Papi\u00e1 Cristang) for people who want to learn Kristang.\n\n==Phonology==\nThe acoustic and articulatory properties of Kristang have not been extensively studied. However, Hancock (1969<ref name=\"Hancock1969\">{{Cite book |last=Hancock |first=Ian F. |date=1969 |title=A Glossary of Papia Kristang Or Malacca Creole Portuguese}}</ref>, 1973<ref name=\"Hancock1973\">{{Cite journal |last=Hancock |first=Ian F. |date=1973 |title=Malacca Creole Portuguese: Asian, African or European? |journal=Anthropological Linguistics|volume=17 |issue=5 |pages=211\u2013238}}</ref>), Batalha (1981)<ref name=\"Batalha1981\">{{Cite journal |last=Bathalha |first=G. N. |date=1981 |title=O Inqu\u00e9rito Lingu\u00edstico Bol\u00e9o em Malaca |journal=Biblos (Coimbra)}}</ref>, and most recently, Baxter (1988)<ref name=\"Baxter1988\"/> have outlined brief descriptions of its sound system.\n\n===Consonants===\nThe inventory of Kristang's consonant phonemes show a significant parallel to the consonants of Standard Malay in [[Malay phonology]].\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|-\n|+Consonant phonemes of Kristang<ref name=\"Baxter1988\" /><ref name=\"Hancock1969\" />\n! colspan=2 |\n! style=\"width: 5em;\" | [[Bilabial consonant|Bilabial]]\n! style=\"width: 5em;\" | [[Labiodental consonant|Labio-dental]]\n! style=\"width: 5em;\" | [[Dental consonant|Alveo-dental]]\n! style=\"width: 5em;\" | [[Alveolar consonant|Alveolar]]\n! style=\"width: 5em;\" | [[Palatal consonant|Palato-alveolar]]\n! style=\"width: 5em;\" | [[Velar consonant|Velar]]\n|-\n!rowspan=2| [[Stop consonant|Stop]]\n! {{small|[[voicelessness|voiceless]]}}\n| {{IPA link|p}}\n| \n| {{IPA link|t}}\n| \n| \n| {{IPA link|k}}\n|-\n! {{small|[[voice (phonetics)|voiced]]}}\n| {{IPA link|b}}\n| \n| {{IPA link|d}}\n| \n| \n| {{IPA link|\u0261}}\n|-\n!rowspan=2| [[Affricate consonant|Affricate]]\n! {{small|[[voicelessness|voiceless]]}}\n|\n|\n|\n| \n| {{IPA link|c}} {{efn|name=c|Described as ''/ch/'' in the inventory by Hancock (1973).}}\n|\n|-\n! {{small|[[voice (phonetics)|voiced]]}}\n|\n| \n|\n| \n| {{IPA link|j}} \n|\n|-\n!rowspan=2| [[Fricative consonant|Fricative]]\n! {{small|[[voicelessness|voiceless]]}}\n|\n| {{IPA link|f}}\n| {{IPA link|s}}\n|\n|\n| \n|-\n! {{small|[[voice (phonetics)|voiced]]}}\n|\n| {{IPA link|v}}{{efn|name=v|The phoneme {{IPA link|v}} is highly infrequent and restricted in distribution. It is also excluded from Hancock (1975)'s inventory<ref name=\"Hancock1973\"/>.}}\n| {{IPA link|z}}\n|\n|\n|\n|-\n!colspan=2| [[Nasal consonant|Nasal]]\n| {{IPA link|m}}\n| \n| {{IPA link|n}}\n| \n| {{IPA link|\u0272}}{{efn|name=\u0272|/\u00f1/ by Baxter (1988)<ref name=\"Baxter1988\"/> and /ny/ by Hancock<ref name=\"Hancock1973\"/> .}}\n| {{IPA link|\u014b}}{{efn|name=\u014b|/ng/ by Baxter (1988)<ref name=\"Baxter1988\"/>.}}\n|-\n!colspan=2| [[Tap consonant|Tap]]/[[Trill consonant|Trill]]\n|\n| \n|\n| {{IPA link|r}}\n|\n|\n|-\n!colspan=2| [[Lateral consonant|Lateral]]\n|\n| \n| {{IPA link|l}}\n| \n|\n|\n|}\n\n{{notelist}}\n\n====Phonological contrasts====\n\nBaxter (1988)<ref name=\"Baxter1988\" /> established the phonemic inventory of Kristang based on the phonological contrasts in its consonant system. This is summarised and illustrated below with examples of minimal pairs. \n\n*'''Stops''': contrast in the '''initial''' and '''medial''' positions.\n\n{| class=\"mw-collapsible mw-collapsed\" style=\"margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto; border: none;\"\n|+''Examples:''\n! colspan=\"2\" style=\"width: 14em; text-align:center;\"|[[Bilabial consonant|Bilabial]]\n!\n! colspan=\"2\" style=\"width: 14em; text-align:center;\"|[[Dental consonant|Alveodental]]\n!\n! colspan=\"2\" style=\"width: 14em; text-align:center;\"|[[Velar consonant|Velar]]\n|-\n|style=\"width: 7em; text-align:center;\"|<small><u>initial</u></small>\n|style=\"width: 7em; text-align:center;\"|<small><u>medial</u></small>\n|\n|style=\"width: 7em; text-align:center;\"|<small><u>initial</u></small>\n|style=\"width: 7em; text-align:center;\"|<small><u>medial</u></small>\n|\n|style=\"width: 7em; text-align:center;\"|<small><u>initial</u></small>\n|style=\"width: 7em; text-align:center;\"|<small><u>medial</u></small>\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|'''p'''ai\n\n''<small>(father)</small>''\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|ka'''p'''a\n\n''<small>(castrate)</small>''\n|\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|'''t'''eng\n\n''<small>(have, be)</small>''\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|a'''t'''i\n\n''<small>(until)</small>''\n|\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|'''k'''aba\n''<small>(finish)</small>''\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|sa'''k'''u\n''<small>(sack, pocket)</small>''\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|'''b'''ai\n''<small>(go)</small>''\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|ka'''b'''a\n<small>''(finish)''</small>\n|\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|'''d'''eng\n''<small>(dried stingray)</small>''\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|a'''d'''i\n<small>''(duck)''</small>\n|\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|'''g'''aba\n''<small>(praise)</small>''\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|sa'''g'''u\n''<small>(sago)</small>''\n|}\n\n*'''Affricates:''' contrast in the '''initial''' and '''medial''' positions.\n\n{| class=\"mw-collapsible mw-collapsed\" style=\"margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto; border: none;\"\n|+''Examples:''\n! colspan=\"2\" style=\"width: 14em; text-align:center;\"|[[Palato-alveolar consonant|Palato-alveolar]]\n|-\n|style=\"width: 7em; text-align:center;\"|<small><u>initial</u></small>\n|style=\"width: 7em; text-align:center;\"|<small><u>medial</u></small>\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|'''c'''eru\n\n''<small>(smell)</small>''\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|in'''c'''hidu\n\n''<small>(full)</small>''\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|'''j'''eru\n''<small>(son-in-law)</small>''\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|jin'''j'''ibri\n<small>''(ginger, gums)''</small>\n|}\n\n*'''Fricatives''': contrasts in the '''medial''' positions. No clear distinctions between voiced-voiceless pairs and all fricative counterparts can be drawn as:\n**/v/ is highly infrequent and restricted in distribution.\n**Initial /z/ has fallen into disuse.\n\n{| class=\"mw-collapsible mw-collapsed\" style=\"margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto; border: none;\"\n|+''Examples:''\n| colspan=\"2\" style=\"width: 14em; text-align:center;\" |/{{IPA link|f}}/ vs /{{IPA link|s}}/\n!\n|style=\"text-align:center;\" |/{{IPA link|f}}/ vs /{{IPA link|z}}/\n|\n|style=\"text-align:center;\" |/{{IPA link|f}}/ vs /{{IPA link|s}}/\n|-\n| style=\"width: 7em; text-align:center;\" |<small><u>initial</u></small>\n| style=\"width: 7em; text-align:center;\" |<small><u>medial</u></small>\n|\n| style=\"width: 7em; text-align:center;\" |<small><u>medial</u></small>\n|\n| style=\"width: 7em; text-align:center;\" |<small><u>medial</u></small>\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" |'''f'''ai\n\n''<small>(pretend/do)</small>''\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" |ko'''f'''i\n\n''<small>(coffee)</small>''\n|\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" |ba'''f'''a\n\n''<small>(steam)</small>''\n|\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" |ba'''f'''u\n''<small>(breath)</small>''\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" |'''s'''ai\n\n''<small>(go out)</small>''\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" |ko'''s'''i\n\n''<small>(kick)</small>''\n|\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" |ba'''z'''a\n<small>''(pour)''</small>\n|\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" |ba'''s'''u\n''<small>(under)</small>''\n|}\n\n*'''Nasals'''\n**'''Initial position''': only /{{IPA link|m}}/, /{{IPA link|n}}/ and /{{IPA link|\u0272}}/ contrast.\n**'''Medial position''': all nasals /{{IPA link|m}}, {{IPA link|n}}, {{IPA link|\u0272}}, {{IPA link|\u014b}}/ contrast.\n**'''Final position''': no contrasts have been found in identical environments.\n**It is also of note that nasals do not contrast before a consonant.\n*'''Flap/Trill''': contrasts in '''initial,''' '''medial''' and '''final''' positions.\n*'''Lateral liquid''': contrasts in '''initial,''' '''medial''' and '''final''' positions.\n\n== Features ==\n\nIts grammatical structure is similar to that of the [[Malay language]].\n\nBecause of its largely Portuguese vocabulary, and perhaps also as a result of migrations and cultural exchange along trade routes, Kristang has much in common with other Portuguese-based creoles, including the near-extinct creoles of [[Indonesia]] and [[East Timor]].\n\n== Grammar ==\n\nThe usage of verbs is one of the grammatical features of Kristang that is similar to Malay. While Portuguese verbs mainly use morphology, or suffixes, to change a verb\u2019s tense or for it to match with the person and number of its subject, Malay does not change the form of the verb itself. Instead, it makes use of pre-verbal words to convey tense and does not indicate the person or number of the subject in the form of the verb. Kristang\u2019s structure is practically identical to Malay, although the choice of words comes from Portuguese. \n\nTo indicate verb tenses, the following appositions are used: ''jah'' (i.e. from the Portuguese ''j\u00e1'', meaning \"already\", or controversially a corruption of Malay ''dah'', shortened version of ''sudah'', also \"already\") for past tenses; ''ta'' (from ''est\u00e1'', which means \"is\") for present continuous tenses and ''logu'' or ''lo'' (from ''logo'', which means \"soon\") for the future tense. These simplified forms correspond with their equivalents in Malay ''sudah'', ''sedang'', and ''akan'', respectively.\n\n{|class=wikitable\n!English\n!Portuguese\n!Malay\n!Kristang\n|-\n|I eat \n|Eu como\n|Saya makan\n|Yo kumih\n|-\n|I ate/have eaten \n|Eu comi\n|Saya sudah makan\n|Yo ja kumih\n|-\n|I will eat \n|Eu comerei\n|Saya akan makan\n|Yo logu kumih\n|-\n|He eats\n|Ele come\n|Dia makan\n|Eli kumih\n|-\n<sup></sup> \n|}\n\nPluralisation is also the same in Malay as in Kristang. For example in English and Portuguese, an \u2018\u2013s\u2019 is added to make cats or gatos, whereas in Kristang and Malay, the entire word is duplicated , such as gatu-gatu in Kristang, and kucing-kucing in Malay.\n\nAdversity Passive, which is used to talk about situations where a negative action happens to something, but the person or originator of the negative action is not mentioned something, is also present both in Kristang and Malay. The Adversity Passive is signaled by kena (Malay), and by tokah (Kristang). \n\n{|class=wikitable\n!Colloquial Malay \n!Kristang\n!Colloquial English near-equivalent\n|-\n|Ikan kena makan\n|Pesi tokah kumih\n|The fish got eaten\n|-\n<sup></sup> \n|}\n\n= Vocabulary =\n\nA peculiarity of the language is the pronoun ''yo'' (meaning \"I\") which is used in [[northern Portuguese  dialects|Northern Portuguese]]  (pronounced as ''yeu'') as well as Spanish and Italian/Sicilian.\n\nThe Kristang lexicon borrowed heavily from Portuguese, but often with drastic truncation; for example, Portuguese ''padrinho'' and ''madrinha'' (\"godfather\" and \"godmother\") became ''inyu'' and ''inya'' in Kristang.\n\n[[Metathesis (linguistics)|Metathesis]] was common: for example, Portuguese ''gordo'' \"fat\" gave Kristang ''godru''.  The Portuguese diphthong ''oi'' (or archaic ''ou'') was reduced to ''o'', e.g. ''dois''/''dous'' \"two\" \u2192 ''dos'',  ''\u00e0 noite''/''\u00e0 noute'' \"tonight\" \u2192 ''anoti''/''anuti''.\n \nMany Portuguese words that began with ''ch'', pronounced {{IPA|[\u0283]}} (\"sh\") in modern Portuguese, have the pronunciation {{IPA|[t\u0283]}} (\"ch\" as in \"cheese\") in Kristang. So, for example, Portuguese ''chegar'' \"to arrive\" and ''chuva'' \"rain\" produced Kristang ''chegak'' and ''chua'' (pronounced with {{IPA|[t\u0283]}}). This could have been due to [[Malay language|Malay]] influence, or it could be that Kristang preserved the original pronunciation  {{IPA|[t\u0283]}} of Old Portuguese. (Note that Portuguese \"ch\" pronounced {{IPA|[t\u0283]}} occurs in Northern Portugal.)\n\n== Writing system ==\n\nKristang was and is largely an oral language and has never been taught officially in schools. The first proposal<ref name=\"Baxter1988\"/> for a standard orthography was made in the late 1980s, with the publication of a thesis, \u201cA Grammar of Kristang\u201d by Alan N. Baxter, in which he emphasizes the use of the [[Malay alphabet|Malay orthography]].\n\nAs in most [[Portuguese dialects]], the vowel ''e'' is usually pronounced {{IPA|[i]}} when followed by a syllable with {{IPA|/i/}}; so, for example, ''penitensia'' (\"penitence\") is pronounced {{IPA|[pini\u02c8te\u0272sia]}}.\n\nIn the 1990s, [[Joan Margaret Marbeck]]'s book ''Ungua Andanza'' was published, with the orthography written in a Luso-Malay context.<ref>Joan Margaret Marbeck. ''Ungua Adanza'' (Heritage). Lisbon: Calouste Gulbenkian Foundation, 1995</ref>\n\n== Examples ==\n\n===Numbers===\nMuch of the lexicon for Kristang numbers draws influence from Portuguese, a [[Romance language]]. However, unlike Portuguese, which distinguishes between the masculine and feminine forms of \u201cone\u201d (''um/uma'') and \u201ctwo\u201d (''dois/duas''), numbers in Kristang do not inflect for gender.\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n!English\n!Kristang\n!Portuguese\n!Malay\n|-\n|one\n|ungua/ngua \n|um (''masc.'') / uma (''fem.'')\n|satu\n|-\n|two\n|dos\n|dois (''masc.'') / duas (''fem.'')\n|dua\n|-\n|three\n|tres\n|tr\u00eas\n|tiga\n|-\n|four\n|katru\n|quatro\n|empat\n|-\n|five\n|singku\n|cinco\n|lima\n|-\n|six\n|sez\n|seis\n|enam\n|-\n|seven\n|seti\n|sete\n|tujuh\n|-\n|eight\n|oitu\n|oito\n|lapan\n|-\n|nine\n|nubi\n|nove\n|sembilan\n|-\n|ten\n|des\n|dez\n|sepuluh\n|-\n|}\n\n===Pronouns===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n!English\n!Kristang\n!Portuguese\n!Malay\n|-\n|Me\n|yo\n|eu\n|saya (''formal'') / aku (''casual'')\n|-\n|You (singular)\n|bos\n|v\u00f3s\n|Awak/Kamu\n|-\n|You (plural)\n|bolotudu/bolotu\n|v\u00f3s todos\n|Awak semua/Kamu semua\n|-\n|We\n|nus\n|n\u00f3s\n|kami\n|-\n|He/she/it\n|eli\n|ele, ela, isto\n|dia\n|-\n|They\n|olotu\n|eles\n|mereka\n|-\n|}\n\n===Common phrases===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n!English\n!Kristang\n!Portuguese\n!Malay\n|-\n|Thank You\n|Mutu Merseh\n|Muitas merc\u00eas\n|Terima Kasih\n|-\n|How Are You?\n|Teng Bong?\n|Est\u00e1s bom?/T\u00eam bom?\n|Awak apa khabar?\n|-\n|What's your name?\n|Ki bos sa numi?\n|Qual \u00e9 o seu nome?/Qual \u00e9 o seu nome?\n|Siapa nama awak?\n|-\n|Good Morning\n|Bong Pamiang\n|Boa Manh\u00e3\n|Selamat Pagi\n|-\n|Good Afternoon\n|Bong Midia\n|Bom Meio-dia\n|Selamat Petang\n|-\n|Good Evening\n|Bong Atadi\n|Boa Tarde\n|Selamat Malam\n|-\n|Good Night\n|Bong Anuti\n|Boa Noite\n|Selamat Malam/Tidur\n|-\n|Mother\n|mai\n|m\u00e3e\n|Emak/Ibu/Bonda/Ummi/Mama\n|-\n|Father\n|pai\n|pai\n|Bapa/Ayah/Abah/Abi\n|-\n|Wife\n|muleh\n|mulher\n|Isteri\n|-\n|Husband\n|maridu\n|marido\n|Suami\n|-\n|Old Woman\n|bela\n|velha\n|Wanita Tua\n|-\n|Old Man\n|belu\n|velho\n|Lelaki Tua\n|-\n|Little one\n|Quenino/Keninu\n|Pequenino\n|Si Kecil\n|-\n|Mouth\n|boka\n|boca\n|Mulut\n|-\n|Fat\n|godru\n|gordo\n|Gemuk\n|-\n|Beautiful\n|bonitu\n|bonito\n|Cantik\n|-\n|Party\n|festa\n|festa\n|Pesta\n|-\n|Yes\n|seng\n|sim\n|Ya\n|-\n|No\n|ngka\n|n\u00e3o\n|Tidak\n|-\n|Who\n|keng\n|quem\n|Siapa\n|-\n|What\n|ki\n|que\n|Apa\n|-\n|When\n|kiora\n|quando (\"que hora\")\n|Bila\n|-\n|Where\n|ondi\n|onde\n|Mana\n|-\n|Why\n|kifoi \n|porque (\"que foi\")\n|Mengapa\n|-\n|How\n|klai\n|como\n|Bagaimana\n|-\n|}\n\n===Poem of Malacca===\n:''Keng teng fortuna fikah na Malaka,''\n:''Nang kereh partih bai otru tera.''\n:''Pra ki tudu jenti teng amizadi,''\n:''Kontu partih logu fikah saudadi.''\n\n:''Oh Malaka, tera di San Francisku,''\n:''Nteh otru tera ki yo kereh.''\n:''Oh Malaka undi teng sempri fresku,''\n:''Yo kereh fikah ateh mureh.''\n\n\nPortuguese translation:\n:''Quem tem fortuna fica em Malaca,''\n:''N\u00e3o quer partir para outra terra.''\n:''Por aqui toda a gente tem amizade,''\n:''Quando tu partes logo fica a saudade.''\n\n:''\u00d3 Malaca, terra de S\u00e3o Francisco,''\n:''N\u00e3o tem outra terra que eu queira.''\n:''\u00d3 Malaca, onde tem sempre frescura,''\n:''Eu quero ficar at\u00e9 morrer.''\n\n\nEnglish translation:\n:Who is lucky stays in Malacca,\n:Doesn't want to go to another land.\n:In here everyone has friendship,\n:When one leaves soon has ''[[saudade]]''.\n\n:Oh Malacca, land of Saint Francis,\n:There is no other land that I want.\n:Oh Malacca, where there's always freshness,\n:I want to stay here until I die.\n\n\nMalay translation:\n\n:Siapa beruntung tinggal di Melaka,\n:Tidak mahu ke tanah berbeza.\n:Di sini semua bersahabat,\n:Bila seorang pergi terasa rindu.\n\n:Oh Melaka, tanah Saint Francis,\n:Tiada tanah lain yang ku mahu.\n:Oh Melaka, dimana adanya kesegaran,\n:Aku mahu tinggal di sini hingga ke akhir nyawa.\n\n== See also ==\n*[[Kristang_people|Kristang people]]\n*[[Eurasians in Singapore]]\n*[[Chavacano language]], a similar though [[Spanish language|Spanish]]-derived [[Malayo-Polynesian languages|Malayo-Polynesian]] creole\n*[[Batavia, Dutch East Indies]], as Kristang is also called Malacca\u2013Batavia Creole\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== References ==\n{{refbegin}}\n* {{Cite book |url=http://sealang.net/archives/pl/pdf/PL-B95.pdf |title=A Grammar of Kristang (Malacca Creole Portuguese) |last=Baxter |first=Alan N. |publisher=Pacific Linguistics |year=1988 |isbn=0-85883-375-1  |series=Pacific Linguistics Series B - No. 95 |location=Canberra |doi=10.15144/pl-b95 |hdl=1885/145643 |hdl-access=free |ref=harv}}\n* {{Cite book |url=http://sealang.net/archives/pl/pdf/PL-564.pdf |title=A Dictionary of Kristang (Malacca Creole Portuguese) English |last=Baxter |first=Alan N. |last2=De Silva |first2=Patrick |publisher=Pacific Linguistics |year=2004 |isbn=0-85883-552-5 |location=Canberra |doi=10.15144/pl-564 |series=Pacific Linguistics 564 |hdl=1885/146269 |hdl-access=free |ref=harv}}\n* {{Cite journal |last=Baxter |first=Alan N. |date=2005 |title=Kristang (Malacca Creole Portuguese) \u2013a long-time survivor seriously endangered |url=https://pdfs.semanticscholar.org/871c/1bbde940e1a64a27505a04630ff4e3b1e2ce.pdf |journal=Estudios de Socioling\u00fc\u00edstica |volume=6 |issue=1 |pages=1-37 |ref=harv}}\n{{refend}}\n\n== External links ==\n*[http://kodrah.kristang.com Kodrah Kristang: Kristang in Singapore Revitalization Project and Classes]\n*[http://www.lusotopie.sciencespobordeaux.fr/fernandis.pdf Papia, Relijang e Tradisang, The Portuguese Eurasians in Malaysia]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20091027034428/http://geocities.com/TheTropics/Paradise/9221/ Malacca Portuguese Eurasian Association]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20050409201057/http://www.malaccacom.net/malaccaportuguese/ Malacca Portuguese Settlement]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20050728002511/http://www.eurasians.org/culture_kristang.html  Singapore Eurasian Association Kristang Page]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20130422061132/http://joanmarbeck.com/ Joan Marbeck's homepage]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20041122225051/http://www.geocities.com/jingkli_nona/ Jingkli Nona - a Kristang viewpoint]\n*[http://www.theseira.net/tphoto.html The Theseira family]\n*[https://www.webcitation.org/query?url=http://www.geocities.com/kevinshepherdson/intro_quest.html&date=2009-10-26+01:20:29 The Shepherdson family]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20050828185504/http://www.peranakan.org.sg/index.html The Peranakan Association Singapore]\n*[http://hub.dataline.net.au/~tfoen/eurasiansvc.htm The Eurasian Company of the Singapore Volunteer Corps]\n*[http://www.pasarmalambesar.nl/english/eng.htm/ Pasar Malam Besar festival in the Netherlands]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20091027034428/http://geocities.com/TheTropics/Paradise/9221/ Malaysian Eurasian food]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20120717012748/http://portuguese.meetup.com/members/?localeId=864%2F All Portuguese Language Meetup Groups]\n*[http://www.soton.ac.uk/~psp/ Portuguese people speaking society]\n*[http://www.sil.org/sociolx/ndg-lg-home.html/ Endangered Languages]\n\n{{Languages of Malaysia}}\n{{Languages of Singapore}}\n{{Portuguese Creoles}}\n\n[[Category:Languages of Malaysia]]\n[[Category:Languages of Singapore]]\n[[Category:Portuguese-based pidgins and creoles]]\n[[Category:Endangered pidgins and creoles]]\n", "name_user": "Defamatory123", "label": "safe", "comment": "Added parts to vocabulary", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Kristang_language"}
{"title_page": "Paratha", "text_new": "{{short description|Flatbread originating in the Indian subcontinent}}\n{{for|the similar South Indian flatbread|Parotta}}\n{{Infobox prepared food\n| name             = Paratha\n| image            = Alooparatha.jpg\n| image_size       = 250px\n| caption          = Potato paratha (aloo paratha)\n| alternate_name   = Paratha, paraunthi, palata, porota, forota, farata, parontay, prontha\n| country          = [[India]]\n| region           = Indian subcontinent<ref name=\"Banerji2008\"/> and [[Southeast Asia]]<ref name=\"Cummings\"/>\n| national_cuisine = [[Indian cuisine|India]], [[Bangladeshi cuisine|Bangladesh]], [[Pakistani cuisine|Pakistan]], [[Nepali cuisine|Nepal]], [[Sri Lankan cuisine|Sri Lanka]], [[Maldivian cuisine|Maldives]], [[Burmese cuisine|Myanmar]]<ref name=\"Cummings\">{{cite book|author=Joe Cummings|title=Myanmar (Burma).|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=L0UuAQAAIAAJ|publisher=Lonely Planet}}</ref>\n| creator          =\n| course           =\n| served           =\n| main_ingredient  = [[Atta flour|Atta]], [[Maida flour|maida]], [[ghee]]/[[butter]]/[[cooking oil]] and various [[stuffing]]s\n| variations       =\n| calories         =\n| other            =\n}}\nA '''paratha''' ({{IAST|par\u0101\u1e47\u1e6dh\u0101}}) is a flatbread native to the [[Indian subcontinent]],<ref name=\"Banerji2008\">{{cite book|author=Chitrita Banerji|title=Eating India: An Odyssey into the Food and Culture of the Land of Spices|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=XfjOQfPtmw0C&pg=PA119|date=10 December 2008|publisher=Bloomsbury Publishing|isbn=978-1-59691-712-5|pages=119\u2013}}</ref> prevalent throughout the modern-day nations of India, Sri Lanka, Pakistan, Nepal, Bangladesh, Maldives, and Myanmar,<ref name=\"Cummings\"/> where wheat is the traditional staple. ''Paratha'' is an amalgamation of the words ''parat'' and ''[[Atta flour|atta]]'', which literally means layers of cooked [[dough]].<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=Rim1x7fHjZgC&pg=PA87&dq=paratha+indian+cuisine+popular|title=Mughlai Cook Book|first=Neera|last=Verma|publisher=Diamond Pocket Books (P) Ltd.|via=Google Books|isbn=9788171825479}}</ref> Alternative spellings and names include ''parantha'', ''parauntha'', ''prontha'', ''parontay'' \n([[Punjabi language|Punjabi]]), ''porota'' (in [[Odia language|Odia]], [[Bengali language|Bengali]], [[Malayalam language|Malayalam]]), ''palata'' ({{IPA-my|p\u0259l\u00e0t\u00e0|pron}}; in Burma),<ref name=\"Cummings\"/> ''porotha'' (in [[Assamese language|Assamese]]), ''forota'' (in [[Sylheti language|Sylheti]]) and ''farata'' (in [[Mauritius]], [[Sri Lanka]] and the [[Maldives]]).\n\n== History ==\nThe [[Hindustani language|Hindustani]] word ''paratha'' is derived from Sanskrit (S. \u092a\u0930, or \u092a\u0930\u093e+\u0938\u094d\u0925\u0903, or \u0938\u094d\u0925\u093f\u0924\u0903).<ref>{{cite web |url= http://dsalsrv02.uchicago.edu/cgi-bin/philologic/search3advanced?dbname=platts&query=paratha&matchtype=exact&display=utf8|title= A dictionary of Urdu, classical Hindi, and English|last= Platts |first= John |date= 1884|website= A dictionary of Urdu, classical Hindi, and English|publisher= W. H. Allen & Co.|access-date= 2017-03-19|quote= \"par\u0101\u1e6dh\u0101 [S. \u092a\u0930, or \u092a\u0930\u093e+\u0938\u094d\u0925\u0903, or \u0938\u094d\u0925\u093f\u0924\u0903], s.m. A cake made with butter or gh\u012b, and of several layers, like pie-crust.\"}}</ref> Recipes for various stuffed wheat puranpolis (which Achaya (2003) describes as parathas) are mentioned in ''[[Manasollasa]]'', a 12th-century Sanskrit encyclopedia compiled by [[Someshvara III]], who ruled from present-day [[Karnataka]].<ref>{{cite book |author=K.T. Achaya |title=The Story of Our Food |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=bk9RHRCqZOkC&pg=PA85 |year=2003 |publisher=Universities Press |isbn=978-81-7371-293-7 |page=85 }}</ref> However,  [[Puran poli]] is a separate bread. Earlier references to paratha have been mentioned by Nijjar (1968), in his book Panj\u0101b under the sult\u0101ns, 1000-1526 A.D. when he writes that parauthas were common with the nobility and aristocracy in the Punjab.<ref>Nijjer, Bakhshish Singh (1968) Panj\u0101b under the sult\u0101ns, 1000-1526 A.D. Sterling Publishers [https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=QaU5AQAAIAAJ&dq=panjab+parautha&focus=searchwithinvolume&q=+parautha]</ref>\n\nAccording to Banerji (2010), parathas are associated with Punjabi and North Indian cooking. The Punjabi method is to stuff parathas with a variety of stuffings. However, Banerji states, Mughals were also fond of parathas which gave raise to the Dhakai paratha, multilayered and flaky, taking its name from [[Dhaka]] in [[Bangladesh]].<ref>Banerji, Chitrita \n (2010) Eating India: Exploring the Food and Culture of the Land of Spices, Bloomsbury Publishing [https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=c9lJnCpfEDoC&pg=PT77&dq=punjabi+paratha+associate&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwju8IPZwu7gAhWOUBUIHQj8CxYQ6AEIKDAA#v=onepage&q=punjabi%20paratha%20associate&f=false]</ref> O'Brien (2003) suggests that it is not correct to state that the Punjabi paratha was popularised in Delhi after the 1947 [[partition of India]], as the Punjabi item was prevalent in Delhi before then.<ref>O'Brien, Charmaine (2003) Penguin UK [https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=xeSXAAAAQBAJ&pg=PT129&dq=punjabi+parantha&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjpn9SxxO7gAhUWSRUIHezqBsIQ6AEINDAC#v=onepage&q&f=falseFlavours Of Delhi: A Food Lover's Guide] </ref>\n\n==Plain and stuffed varieties==\n\n{{nutritionalvalue\n| name=Paratha, whole wheat, commercially prepared, Frozen\n| kCal=327\n| protein=6.36 g\n| fat=13.20 g\n| carbs=45.36 g\n| fiber=9.6 g\n| water=33.5 g\n| sugars=4.15\n| calcium_mg=25\n| iron_mg=1.61\n| magnesium_mg=37\n| phosphorus_mg=120\n| potassium_mg=139\n| sodium_mg=452\n| zinc_mg=0.82\n| manganese_mg=\n| thiamin_mg=0.11\n| riboflavin_mg=0.076\n| niacin_mg=1.830\n| pantothenic_mg=0\n| vitB6_mg=0.08\n| folate_ug=0\n| vitE_mg=1.35\n| vitK_ug=3.4\n| source_usda=1\n| note=[http://ndb.nal.usda.gov/ndb/search/list?qlookup=28286&format=Full Link to USDA Database entry]\n}}\n\nParathas are one of the most popular [[leavening agent|unleavened]] flatbreads in the [[Indian Subcontinent]], made by baking or cooking [[Whole grain|whole wheat]] dough on a [[tava]], and finishing off with [[pan frying|shallow frying]].<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=Wgtdzu2GXh8C&pg=PA130&dq=paratha+indian+cuisine+popular|title=Climbing the Mango Trees: A Memoir of a Childhood in India|first=Madhur|last=Jaffrey|date=18 December 2008|publisher=Knopf Doubleday Publishing Group|via=Google Books|isbn=9780307517692}}</ref> Parathas are thicker and more substantial than [[chapati]]s/[[roti]]s and this is either because, in the case of a ''plain paratha'', they have been layered by coating with [[ghee]] or oil and folding repeatedly (much like the method used for [[puff pastry]] or some types of Turkish [[b\u00f6rek]]) using a [[laminated dough]] technique; or else because food ingredients such as mixed vegetables have been mixed in with the dough, such as potato or cauliflower, green beans, and carrots. A Rajasthani mung bean paratha uses both the layering technique together with mung dal mixed into the dough. Some so-called ''stuffed parathas'' resemble a filled pie squashed flat and shallow fried, using two discs of dough sealed around the edges. Then by alternatively using a single disc of dough to encase a ball of filling and sealed with a series of pleats pinched into the dough around the top, gently flattened with the palm against the working surface before being rolled into a circle. Most stuffed parathas are not layered.\n\nParathas can be eaten as a breakfast dish or as a tea-time ([[tiffin]]) snack. The flour used is finely ground wholemeal ([[atta flour|atta]]) and the dough is shallow fried.\n\nPerhaps the most common stuffing for parathas is mashed, spiced potatoes (''aloo ka parantha'') followed perhaps by dal (lentils). Many other alternatives exist such as [[leaf vegetable]]s, [[radish]]es, [[cauliflower]] or [[paneer]].  A paratha (especially a stuffed one) can be eaten simply with a pat of butter spread on top or with chutney, pickles, ketchup, [[Yogurt|dahi]] or a [[raita]] or with meat or vegetable curries. Some roll the paratha into a tube and eat it with tea, often dipping the paratha.\n\nTo achieve the  [[laminated dough|layered dough]] for plain parathas, a number of different traditional techniques exist. These include covering the thinly rolled out pastry with oil, folding back and forth like a paper fan and coiling the resulting strip into a round shape before rolling flat, baking on the [[tava]] and shallow frying. Another method is to cut a circle of dough from the centre to its circumference along its radius, oiling the dough and starting at the cut edge rolling so as to form a cone which is then squashed into a disc shape and rolled out. The method of oiling and repeatedly folding the dough as in western puff pastry also exists, and this is combined with folding patterns that give traditional geometrical shapes to the finished parathas.  Plain parathas can be round, heptagonal, square, or triangular.\n\n== Serving ==\n\nThe paratha is an important part of a traditional breakfast from the Indian subcontinent. Traditionally, it is made using [[ghee]] but oil is also used. Some people may even bake it in the oven for health reasons. Usually, the paratha is eaten with dollops of white butter on top of it. Side dishes which go very well with paratha are curd, fried egg, omelette, mutton kheema (ground mutton cooked with vegetables and spices), [[nihari]] (a lamb dish), jeera aloo (potatoes lightly fried with cumin seeds), daal, and [[raita]] as part of a breakfast meal. It may be stuffed with potatoes, [[paneer]], [[onion]]s, [[qeema]] or [[chili pepper]]s.\n\n== Types ==\n[[File:A Aesthetic Parota making part 1.ogv|thumb|right|200px|Video showing one method of stretching the dough.]]\n[[File:Parathas being made.jpg|thumb|right|200px|Image showing parathas being made.]]\n* Ajwain paratha (layered paratha laced with [[ajwain]])\n* [[Aloo paratha]] (stuffed with spicy boiled potato and onions mix)\n* Aloo cheese paratha\n* Anda paratha (stuffed with spiced egg)\n* Band gobi wala paratha or Patta gobhi paratha (stuffed with [[cabbage]])\n* Batuha paratha (Lamb's quarter, Chenopodium album)\n* Boondi paratha (stuffed with salty boondi & baked with ghee)\n* Ceylon paratha (from Sri Lanka)\n* Chana paratha (chick peas)\n* Channa dal paratha (stuffed with channa [[dal]])\n* Chicken paratha\n* [[Chili parotha]] or mirchi paratha (small, spicy shredded pieces)\n* Dal paratha (stuffed with boiled, spiced and mashed dal mostly available in northwestern and western India)\n* Dhakai paratha (a type of layered paratha found in Dhaka, Bangladesh)\n* Dhaniya paratha (coriander)\n* Gajar paratha (carrot)\n* [[Gobi paratha]] (stuffed with flavoured cauliflower)\n* Jaipuri paratha\n* Kerala paratha (popular version pronounced \"porotta\")\n* Lachha paratha \u2013 tandoori (Punjabi in origin. Round in shape with multiple layers traditionally prepared in a [[tandoor]])\n* Lachha paratha \u2013 tawa wali (popular in eastern India, triangular in shape with multiple layers interspaced with ghee)\n* Lasuni Paratha (Garlic flavoured)\n* Lauki paratha (bottle gourd)\n* Makka paratha (corn)<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.republicworld.com/lifestyle/food/how-to-make-sweet-corn-paratha-recipe-north-indian-dish.html|title=Sweet Corn Paratha Recipe: Learn How To Make This Delicious North Indian Dish|publisher=}}</ref>\n* Mattar paratha (stuffed with boiled, mashed and flavoured green peas)\n* Meetha paratha (stuffed with sugar)\n* Methi paratha (stuffed with fenugreek leaves)\n* Mooli paratha (radish-stuffed paratha, popular in most regions of northern India and the Punjab region of India.)\n* [[Mughlai paratha]] (a deep-fried stuffed paratha filled with egg and minced meat)\n* Murthal Paratha, deep-fried, [[Dhaba]]s of [[Haryana]] and specially at [[Murthal]] on [[Grand Trunk Road]] are famous for this<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tribuneindia.com/2004/20040327/windows/main1.htm|title=The Tribune - Magazine section - Windows|website=www.tribuneindia.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.thehindu.com/features/magazine/food-safari-in-search-of-murthal-ke-paranthe/article4364734.ece|title=Food Safari: In search of Murthal Paratha The Hindu newspaper, 2-Feb-2013|publisher=|newspaper=The Hindu|date=2013-02-02|last1=Balasubramaniam|first1=Chitra}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/chandigarh/Highway-Bites-Dhabas-Vs-food-chains/articleshow/48843912.cms|title=Highway Bites: Dhabas Vs food chains - Times of India|publisher=}}</ref>\n* Mutton paratha\n* Papeetey ka paratha (papaya stuffed paratha)\n* Mix paratha\n* Palak paratha (spinach)\n* Paneer paratha (stuffed with cottage cheese)\n* Papad parantha\n* Parton wala paratha (Lachha paratha)\n* Petai paratha (Smashed paratha)\n* Plain paratha (layered roti without any stuffing except ghee and baked with ghee \u2013 popular in most regions of India)\n* Podeena paratha (laced with dry [[Mentha|mint]])\n* Putthay taway ka paratha\n* Pyaz ka paratha (stuffed with onion)\n* Qeema paratha, (stuffed with minced meat (''keema''), usually mutton, mostly available in Punjab, Hyderabad in India, and Myanmar)\n* [[Roti prata]] (Singapore & Malaysia)\n* Sattu paratha (stuffed with spiced sattu \u2013 roasted [[Pulse (legume)|gram]] flour popular in Uttar Pradesh and Bihar)\n* Shrimp paratha\n* Sugar paratha (layered with caramelized sugar, usually after a meal or as dessert)\n* Tandoori paratha\n* Tomato paratha (stuffed with tomatoes)\n\n<gallery mode=\"packed\">\nFile:Aloo Paratha with Butter from India.jpg|[[Punjabi cuisine|Punjabi]] Aloo Paratha served with Butter, from India\nFile:Mughlai Kheema Paratha.JPG|[[Mughlai Paratha]] from [[Kolkata, India]].\nFile:Dhakai Paratha with Bengal Gram.JPG|Dhakai Paratha from West Bengal, India\nFile:Mangaloreparatha.jpg|[[Mangalore]]an-style paratha served with other [[Indian cuisine|Indian dishes]]\nFile:Alooparatha.jpg|Aloo paratha from northern India\nFile:Parotta.jpg|South Indian [[parotta]]\nFile:Teaparatha.jpg|Paratha served with tea in a Pakistani Hotel\nFile:Paranthamumbai.jpg|Stuffed [[Bengali cuisine|Bengali]]-style paratha served in a restaurant in [[Mumbai]], [[India]]\nFile:Paratharoti.jpg|[[Trinidad and Tobago|Trinidadian]]-style roti paratha\nFile:Palatha, Myanmar.jpg|In Burma, paratha is commonly eaten as a dessert, sprinkled with sugar\nFile:Smash Paratha - Howrah 2014-04-14 0217.JPG|Petai Paratha (Smashed Paratha), a West Bengal variant served with light vegetable curry\nFile:Lachha-paratha.jpg|Lachha Paratha\nFile:Kothu Parotta (Chicken) as served in Tamil Nadu, India.jpg|Kothu Parotta (Chicken) as served in Tamil Nadu, India\n</gallery>\n\n== Ready-made varieties ==\nThe process of layering the \"skins\" of dough in a paratha can make preparation a difficult process.  This, mixed with the popularity of this flatbread, has opened the market to several ranges of frozen paratha, especially in Western markets where consumers seek authenticity. Ready-to-cook paratha may also be purchased. These preparations offer one-step preparation and save time. Some of the ready-to-cook products in the market are just the stuffings for making the stuffed parathas.\n\n== See also ==\n{{div col|colwidth=15em}}\n* [[Bhatura]]\n* [[Chili parotha]]\n* [[Gali Paranthe Wali]]\n* [[C\u014dng y\u00f3u b\u01d0ng]], a similar Chinese flatbread stuffed with minced scallions\n* [[Kerala porotta]]\n* [[Kothu parotta]], the South Indian variant\n* [[Naan]]\n* [[Parotta]]\n* [[List of bread dishes]]\n* [[List of Indian breads]]\n{{div col end}}\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n[https://www.iamafoodie.in/2020/04/lockdown-recipe-1-challange-paneer.html How to make Paneer paratha (Beginners)]== External links ==\n{{commons category|Paratha}}\n\n{{Indian Dishes}}\n{{Indian bread}}\n{{Pakistani dishes}}\n{{Pakistani bread}}\n{{Burmese cuisine}}\n{{Flatbreads}}\n{{bread}}\n\n[[Category:Balochi cuisine]]\n[[Category:Bengali cuisine]]\n[[Category:Bangladeshi cuisine]]\n[[Category:Bihari cuisine]]\n[[Category:Burmese cuisine]]\n[[Category:Flatbreads]]\n[[Category:Pakistani breads]]\n[[Category:Indian breads]]\n[[Category:Indian cuisine]]\n[[Category:Kashmiri cuisine]]\n[[Category:Nepalese cuisine]]\n[[Category:Pashtun cuisine]]\n[[Category:Punjabi cuisine]]\n[[Category:Sindhi cuisine]]\n[[Category:Unleavened breads]]\n[[Category:Uttar Pradeshi cuisine]]\n[[Category:Articles containing video clips]]\n[[Category:Stuffed dishes]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Flatbread originating in the Indian subcontinent}}\n{{for|the similar South Indian flatbread|Parotta}}\n{{Infobox prepared food\n| name             = Paratha\n| image            = Alooparatha.jpg\n| image_size       = 250px\n| caption          = Potato paratha (aloo paratha)\n| alternate_name   = Paratha, paraunthi, palata, porota, forota, farata, parontay, prontha\n| country          = [[India]]\n| region           = Indian subcontinent<ref name=\"Banerji2008\"/> and [[Southeast Asia]]<ref name=\"Cummings\"/>\n| national_cuisine = [[Indian cuisine|India]], [[Bangladeshi cuisine|Bangladesh]], [[Pakistani cuisine|Pakistan]], [[Nepali cuisine|Nepal]], [[Sri Lankan cuisine|Sri Lanka]], [[Maldivian cuisine|Maldives]], [[Burmese cuisine|Myanmar]]<ref name=\"Cummings\">{{cite book|author=Joe Cummings|title=Myanmar (Burma).|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=L0UuAQAAIAAJ|publisher=Lonely Planet}}</ref>\n| creator          =\n| course           =\n| served           =\n| main_ingredient  = [[Atta flour|Atta]], [[Maida flour|maida]], [[ghee]]/[[butter]]/[[cooking oil]] and various [[stuffing]]s\n| variations       =\n| calories         =\n| other            =\n}}\nA '''paratha''' ({{IAST|par\u0101\u1e47\u1e6dh\u0101}}) is a flatbread native to the [[Indian subcontinent]],<ref name=\"Banerji2008\">{{cite book|author=Chitrita Banerji|title=Eating India: An Odyssey into the Food and Culture of the Land of Spices|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=XfjOQfPtmw0C&pg=PA119|date=10 December 2008|publisher=Bloomsbury Publishing|isbn=978-1-59691-712-5|pages=119\u2013}}</ref> prevalent throughout the modern-day nations of India, Sri Lanka, Pakistan, Nepal, Bangladesh, Maldives, and Myanmar,<ref name=\"Cummings\"/> where wheat is the traditional staple. ''Paratha'' is an amalgamation of the words ''parat'' and ''[[Atta flour|atta]]'', which literally means layers of cooked [[dough]].<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=Rim1x7fHjZgC&pg=PA87&dq=paratha+indian+cuisine+popular|title=Mughlai Cook Book|first=Neera|last=Verma|publisher=Diamond Pocket Books (P) Ltd.|via=Google Books|isbn=9788171825479}}</ref> Alternative spellings and names include ''parantha'', ''parauntha'', ''prontha'', ''parontay'' \n([[Punjabi language|Punjabi]]), ''porota'' (in [[Odia language|Odia]], [[Bengali language|Bengali]], [[Malayalam language|Malayalam]]), ''palata'' ({{IPA-my|p\u0259l\u00e0t\u00e0|pron}}; in Burma),<ref name=\"Cummings\"/> ''porotha'' (in [[Assamese language|Assamese]]), ''forota'' (in [[Sylheti language|Sylheti]]) and ''farata'' (in [[Mauritius]], [[Sri Lanka]] and the [[Maldives]]).\n\n== History ==\nThe [[Hindustani language|Hindustani]] word ''paratha'' is derived from Sanskrit (S. \u092a\u0930, or \u092a\u0930\u093e+\u0938\u094d\u0925\u0903, or \u0938\u094d\u0925\u093f\u0924\u0903).<ref>{{cite web |url= http://dsalsrv02.uchicago.edu/cgi-bin/philologic/search3advanced?dbname=platts&query=paratha&matchtype=exact&display=utf8|title= A dictionary of Urdu, classical Hindi, and English|last= Platts |first= John |date= 1884|website= A dictionary of Urdu, classical Hindi, and English|publisher= W. H. Allen & Co.|access-date= 2017-03-19|quote= \"par\u0101\u1e6dh\u0101 [S. \u092a\u0930, or \u092a\u0930\u093e+\u0938\u094d\u0925\u0903, or \u0938\u094d\u0925\u093f\u0924\u0903], s.m. A cake made with butter or gh\u012b, and of several layers, like pie-crust.\"}}</ref> Recipes for various stuffed wheat puranpolis (which Achaya (2003) describes as parathas) are mentioned in ''[[Manasollasa]]'', a 12th-century Sanskrit encyclopedia compiled by [[Someshvara III]], who ruled from present-day [[Karnataka]].<ref>{{cite book |author=K.T. Achaya |title=The Story of Our Food |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=bk9RHRCqZOkC&pg=PA85 |year=2003 |publisher=Universities Press |isbn=978-81-7371-293-7 |page=85 }}</ref> However,  [[Puran poli]] is a separate bread. Earlier references to paratha have been mentioned by Nijjar (1968), in his book Panj\u0101b under the sult\u0101ns, 1000-1526 A.D. when he writes that parauthas were common with the nobility and aristocracy in the Punjab.<ref>Nijjer, Bakhshish Singh (1968) Panj\u0101b under the sult\u0101ns, 1000-1526 A.D. Sterling Publishers [https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=QaU5AQAAIAAJ&dq=panjab+parautha&focus=searchwithinvolume&q=+parautha]</ref>\n\nAccording to Banerji (2010), parathas are associated with Punjabi and North Indian cooking. The Punjabi method is to stuff parathas with a variety of stuffings. However, Banerji states, Mughals were also fond of parathas which gave raise to the Dhakai paratha, multilayered and flaky, taking its name from [[Dhaka]] in [[Bangladesh]].<ref>Banerji, Chitrita \n (2010) Eating India: Exploring the Food and Culture of the Land of Spices, Bloomsbury Publishing [https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=c9lJnCpfEDoC&pg=PT77&dq=punjabi+paratha+associate&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwju8IPZwu7gAhWOUBUIHQj8CxYQ6AEIKDAA#v=onepage&q=punjabi%20paratha%20associate&f=false]</ref> O'Brien (2003) suggests that it is not correct to state that the Punjabi paratha was popularised in Delhi after the 1947 [[partition of India]], as the Punjabi item was prevalent in Delhi before then.<ref>O'Brien, Charmaine (2003) Penguin UK [https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=xeSXAAAAQBAJ&pg=PT129&dq=punjabi+parantha&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjpn9SxxO7gAhUWSRUIHezqBsIQ6AEINDAC#v=onepage&q&f=falseFlavours Of Delhi: A Food Lover's Guide] </ref>\n\n==Plain and stuffed varieties==\n\n{{nutritionalvalue\n| name=Paratha, whole wheat, commercially prepared, Frozen\n| kCal=327\n| protein=6.36 g\n| fat=13.20 g\n| carbs=45.36 g\n| fiber=9.6 g\n| water=33.5 g\n| sugars=4.15\n| calcium_mg=25\n| iron_mg=1.61\n| magnesium_mg=37\n| phosphorus_mg=120\n| potassium_mg=139\n| sodium_mg=452\n| zinc_mg=0.82\n| manganese_mg=\n| thiamin_mg=0.11\n| riboflavin_mg=0.076\n| niacin_mg=1.830\n| pantothenic_mg=0\n| vitB6_mg=0.08\n| folate_ug=0\n| vitE_mg=1.35\n| vitK_ug=3.4\n| source_usda=1\n| note=[http://ndb.nal.usda.gov/ndb/search/list?qlookup=28286&format=Full Link to USDA Database entry]\n}}\n\nParathas are one of the most popular [[leavening agent|unleavened]] flatbreads in the [[Indian Subcontinent]], made by baking or cooking [[Whole grain|whole wheat]] dough on a [[tava]], and finishing off with [[pan frying|shallow frying]].<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=Wgtdzu2GXh8C&pg=PA130&dq=paratha+indian+cuisine+popular|title=Climbing the Mango Trees: A Memoir of a Childhood in India|first=Madhur|last=Jaffrey|date=18 December 2008|publisher=Knopf Doubleday Publishing Group|via=Google Books|isbn=9780307517692}}</ref> Parathas are thicker and more substantial than [[chapati]]s/[[roti]]s and this is either because, in the case of a ''plain paratha'', they have been layered by coating with [[ghee]] or oil and folding repeatedly (much like the method used for [[puff pastry]] or some types of Turkish [[b\u00f6rek]]) using a [[laminated dough]] technique; or else because food ingredients such as mixed vegetables have been mixed in with the dough, such as potato or cauliflower, green beans, and carrots. A Rajasthani mung bean paratha uses both the layering technique together with mung dal mixed into the dough. Some so-called ''stuffed parathas'' resemble a filled pie squashed flat and shallow fried, using two discs of dough sealed around the edges. Then by alternatively using a single disc of dough to encase a ball of filling and sealed with a series of pleats pinched into the dough around the top, gently flattened with the palm against the working surface before being rolled into a circle. Most stuffed parathas are not layered.\n\nParathas can be eaten as a breakfast dish or as a tea-time ([[tiffin]]) snack. The flour used is finely ground wholemeal ([[atta flour|atta]]) and the dough is shallow fried.\n\nPerhaps the most common stuffing for parathas is mashed, spiced potatoes (''aloo ka parantha'') followed perhaps by dal (lentils). Many other alternatives exist such as [[leaf vegetable]]s, [[radish]]es, [[cauliflower]] or [[paneer]].  A paratha (especially a stuffed one) can be eaten simply with a pat of butter spread on top or with chutney, pickles, ketchup, [[Yogurt|dahi]] or a [[raita]] or with meat or vegetable curries. Some roll the paratha into a tube and eat it with tea, often dipping the paratha.\n\nTo achieve the  [[laminated dough|layered dough]] for plain parathas, a number of different traditional techniques exist. These include covering the thinly rolled out pastry with oil, folding back and forth like a paper fan and coiling the resulting strip into a round shape before rolling flat, baking on the [[tava]] and shallow frying. Another method is to cut a circle of dough from the centre to its circumference along its radius, oiling the dough and starting at the cut edge rolling so as to form a cone which is then squashed into a disc shape and rolled out. The method of oiling and repeatedly folding the dough as in western puff pastry also exists, and this is combined with folding patterns that give traditional geometrical shapes to the finished parathas.  Plain parathas can be round, heptagonal, square, or triangular.\n\n== Serving ==\n\nThe paratha is an important part of a traditional breakfast from the Indian subcontinent. Traditionally, it is made using [[ghee]] but oil is also used. Some people may even bake it in the oven for health reasons. Usually, the paratha is eaten with dollops of white butter on top of it. Side dishes which go very well with paratha are curd, fried egg, omelette, mutton kheema (ground mutton cooked with vegetables and spices), [[nihari]] (a lamb dish), jeera aloo (potatoes lightly fried with cumin seeds), daal, and [[raita]] as part of a breakfast meal. It may be stuffed with potatoes, [[paneer]], [[onion]]s, [[qeema]] or [[chili pepper]]s.\n\n== Types ==\n[[File:A Aesthetic Parota making part 1.ogv|thumb|right|200px|Video showing one method of stretching the dough.]]\n[[File:Parathas being made.jpg|thumb|right|200px|Image showing parathas being made.]]\n* Ajwain paratha (layered paratha laced with [[ajwain]])\n* [[Aloo paratha]] (stuffed with spicy boiled potato and onions mix)\n* Aloo cheese paratha\n* Anda paratha (stuffed with spiced egg)\n* Band gobi wala paratha or Patta gobhi paratha (stuffed with [[cabbage]])\n* Batuha paratha (Lamb's quarter, Chenopodium album)\n* Boondi paratha (stuffed with salty boondi & baked with ghee)\n* Ceylon paratha (from Sri Lanka)\n* Chana paratha (chick peas)\n* Channa dal paratha (stuffed with channa [[dal]])\n* Chicken paratha\n* [[Chili parotha]] or mirchi paratha (small, spicy shredded pieces)\n* Dal paratha (stuffed with boiled, spiced and mashed dal mostly available in northwestern and western India)\n* Dhakai paratha (a type of layered paratha found in Dhaka, Bangladesh)\n* Dhaniya paratha (coriander)\n* Gajar paratha (carrot)\n* [[Gobi paratha]] (stuffed with flavoured cauliflower)\n* Jaipuri paratha\n* Kerala paratha (popular version pronounced \"porotta\")\n* Lachha paratha \u2013 tandoori (Punjabi in origin. Round in shape with multiple layers traditionally prepared in a [[tandoor]])\n* Lachha paratha \u2013 tawa wali (popular in eastern India, triangular in shape with multiple layers interspaced with ghee)\n* Lasuni Paratha (Garlic flavoured)\n* Lauki paratha (bottle gourd)\n* Makka paratha (corn)<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.republicworld.com/lifestyle/food/how-to-make-sweet-corn-paratha-recipe-north-indian-dish.html|title=Sweet Corn Paratha Recipe: Learn How To Make This Delicious North Indian Dish|publisher=}}</ref>\n* Mattar paratha (stuffed with boiled, mashed and flavoured green peas)\n* Meetha paratha (stuffed with sugar)\n* Methi paratha (stuffed with fenugreek leaves)\n* Mooli paratha (radish-stuffed paratha, popular in most regions of northern India and the Punjab region of India.)\n* [[Mughlai paratha]] (a deep-fried stuffed paratha filled with egg and minced meat)\n* Murthal Paratha, deep-fried, [[Dhaba]]s of [[Haryana]] and specially at [[Murthal]] on [[Grand Trunk Road]] are famous for this<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tribuneindia.com/2004/20040327/windows/main1.htm|title=The Tribune - Magazine section - Windows|website=www.tribuneindia.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.thehindu.com/features/magazine/food-safari-in-search-of-murthal-ke-paranthe/article4364734.ece|title=Food Safari: In search of Murthal Paratha The Hindu newspaper, 2-Feb-2013|publisher=|newspaper=The Hindu|date=2013-02-02|last1=Balasubramaniam|first1=Chitra}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/chandigarh/Highway-Bites-Dhabas-Vs-food-chains/articleshow/48843912.cms|title=Highway Bites: Dhabas Vs food chains - Times of India|publisher=}}</ref>\n* Mutton paratha\n* Papeetey ka paratha (papaya stuffed paratha)\n* Mix paratha\n* Palak paratha (spinach)\n* Paneer paratha (stuffed with cottage cheese)\n* Papad parantha\n* Parton wala paratha (Lachha paratha)\n* Petai paratha (Smashed paratha)\n* Plain paratha (layered roti without any stuffing except ghee and baked with ghee \u2013 popular in most regions of India)\n* Podeena paratha (laced with dry [[Mentha|mint]])\n* Putthay taway ka paratha\n* Pyaz ka paratha (stuffed with onion)\n* Qeema paratha, (stuffed with minced meat (''keema''), usually mutton, mostly available in Punjab, Hyderabad in India, and Myanmar)\n* [[Roti prata]] (Singapore & Malaysia)\n* Sattu paratha (stuffed with spiced sattu \u2013 roasted [[Pulse (legume)|gram]] flour popular in Uttar Pradesh and Bihar)\n* Shrimp paratha\n* Sugar paratha (layered with caramelized sugar, usually after a meal or as dessert)\n* Tandoori paratha\n* Tomato paratha (stuffed with tomatoes)\n\n<gallery mode=\"packed\">\nFile:Aloo Paratha with Butter from India.jpg|[[Punjabi cuisine|Punjabi]] Aloo Paratha served with Butter, from India\nFile:Mughlai Kheema Paratha.JPG|[[Mughlai Paratha]] from [[Kolkata, India]].\nFile:Dhakai Paratha with Bengal Gram.JPG|Dhakai Paratha from West Bengal, India\nFile:Mangaloreparatha.jpg|[[Mangalore]]an-style paratha served with other [[Indian cuisine|Indian dishes]]\nFile:Alooparatha.jpg|Aloo paratha from northern India\nFile:Parotta.jpg|South Indian [[parotta]]\nFile:Teaparatha.jpg|Paratha served with tea in a Pakistani Hotel\nFile:Paranthamumbai.jpg|Stuffed [[Bengali cuisine|Bengali]]-style paratha served in a restaurant in [[Mumbai]], [[India]]\nFile:Paratharoti.jpg|[[Trinidad and Tobago|Trinidadian]]-style roti paratha\nFile:Palatha, Myanmar.jpg|In Burma, paratha is commonly eaten as a dessert, sprinkled with sugar\nFile:Smash Paratha - Howrah 2014-04-14 0217.JPG|Petai Paratha (Smashed Paratha), a West Bengal variant served with light vegetable curry\nFile:Lachha-paratha.jpg|Lachha Paratha\nFile:Kothu Parotta (Chicken) as served in Tamil Nadu, India.jpg|Kothu Parotta (Chicken) as served in Tamil Nadu, India\n</gallery>\n\n== Ready-made varieties ==\nThe process of layering the \"skins\" of dough in a paratha can make preparation a difficult process.  This, mixed with the popularity of this flatbread, has opened the market to several ranges of frozen paratha, especially in Western markets where consumers seek authenticity. Ready-to-cook paratha may also be purchased. These preparations offer one-step preparation and save time. Some of the ready-to-cook products in the market are just the stuffings for making the stuffed parathas.\n\n== See also ==\n{{div col|colwidth=15em}}\n* [[Bhatura]]\n* [[Chili parotha]]\n* [[Gali Paranthe Wali]]\n* [[C\u014dng y\u00f3u b\u01d0ng]], a similar Chinese flatbread stuffed with minced scallions\n* [[Kerala porotta]]\n* [[Kothu parotta]], the South Indian variant\n* [[Naan]]\n* [[Parotta]]\n* [[List of bread dishes]]\n* [[List of Indian breads]]\n{{div col end}}\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{commons category|Paratha}}\n\n{{Indian Dishes}}\n{{Indian bread}}\n{{Pakistani dishes}}\n{{Pakistani bread}}\n{{Burmese cuisine}}\n{{Flatbreads}}\n{{bread}}\n\n[[Category:Balochi cuisine]]\n[[Category:Bengali cuisine]]\n[[Category:Bangladeshi cuisine]]\n[[Category:Bihari cuisine]]\n[[Category:Burmese cuisine]]\n[[Category:Flatbreads]]\n[[Category:Pakistani breads]]\n[[Category:Indian breads]]\n[[Category:Indian cuisine]]\n[[Category:Kashmiri cuisine]]\n[[Category:Nepalese cuisine]]\n[[Category:Pashtun cuisine]]\n[[Category:Punjabi cuisine]]\n[[Category:Sindhi cuisine]]\n[[Category:Unleavened breads]]\n[[Category:Uttar Pradeshi cuisine]]\n[[Category:Articles containing video clips]]\n[[Category:Stuffed dishes]]\n", "name_user": "Samdaripa", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(\u2192\u200eExternal links)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Paratha"}
{"title_page": "The Shifting Heart", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2015}}\n{{italic title}}\n'''''The Shifting Heart''''' is a play written in 1957<ref>{{cite book|last=Milne|first=Geoffrey|title=Theatre Australia (Un)limited|year=2004|publisher=Rodopi}}</ref> in Australia by [[Richard Beynon (writer)|Richard Beynon]], it is an insight to the [[psychology]] of racism and its victims. In the background of 1950s [[Collingwood, Victoria|Collingwood]], [[Melbourne]].\n\n== Characters ==\n\n* Momma Bianchi\n* Poppa Bianchi\n* Gino Bianchi\n* Maria Bianchi (Fowler)\n* Clarry Fowler\n* Leila Pratt\n* Donny Pratt\n* Big willy boy\n\n== Setting ==\n''The Shifting Heart'' is set in 1956, Collingwood, Melbourne on Christmas Eve. At the time, Collingwood was a poor suburb populated by lower class Australian families and Italian immigrants.\n\nThe play published in 1960 by [[Angus & Robertson]] begins with two pages of stage direction. It describes the home of Italians Mr. & Mrs. Vicenzo Bianchi, the stage is their backyard. On stage left there is a large [[garbage can]] that is overfilled, the overflow is in a small household bucket. On each side of the stage is the wall of the neighbours.\n\nOn stage left is the wall between the Pratt family, Leila and Donny. The wall is a fence that relaxes in the wind and shows an air of [[dilapidation]]. The boards are able to be pushed apart enough to let the Pratts enter the Bianchis' backyard.\n\nOn stage right there is a wall described as a formidable barrier, complete with a length of [[barbed wire]] across the top. It is low enough for the woman living there to toss garbage over. In the first pages of dialog and notes in the stage direction, it is clear that there is a \"war\" going on between the family living stage right against the Bianchis because they are Italian. The Pratt family is on the side of the Bianchi family.\n\n==Productions==\n''The Shifting Heart'' premiered at the [[Elizabethan Theatre, Sydney|Elizabethan Theatre]] in Sydney in October 1957, presented by the [[Australian Elizabethan Theatre Trust]]. It toured nationally for a year, including seasons at the [[Comedy Theatre, Melbourne|Comedy Theatre]] in Melbourne and Her Majesty's Theatre in Brisbane.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ausstage.edu.au/pages/work/1348|title=AusStage \u2013 The Shifting Heart|website=www.ausstage.edu.au|access-date=2016-06-15}}</ref>\n\nThe play debuted in England in 1959 where it played a West End season at the [[Duke of York's Theatre]].<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article103127915 |title=Enthusiastic U.K. Reception For Australian Play. |newspaper=[[The Canberra Times]] |date=12 August 1959 |accessdate=24 May 2015 |page=19 |via=National Library of Australia}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article103131252 |title=\"Shifting Heart\" Well Received |newspaper=[[The Canberra Times]] |volume=34 |issue=9,396 |date=16 September 1959 |accessdate=4 April 2017 |page=3 |via=National Library of Australia}}</ref>\n\nThe ABC made a radio version of the play in 1962.  It was adapted for Australian television on the ABC in 1968.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article107066391 |title=Richard Beynon's prize-winning play 'The Shifting Heart' will be telecast on ABC-3 at 8 o'clock tonight. Virginia Gerrett interviewed the author in London recently. The 'Z-Cars' controller. |newspaper=[[The Canberra Times]] |date=7 August 1968 |accessdate=24 May 2015 |page=12 |via=National Library of Australia}}</ref>\n\nNotable revivals include those of Melbourne's [[Union Theatre Repertory Company]] in 1962, Sydney's Marian Street Theatre in 1981, Sydney's [[Phillip Street Theatre]] in 1984, and the [[State Theatre Company of South Australia]] in 1996.\n\n==1962 TV adaptation==\n{{Infobox film\n| name           = The Shifting Heart\n| image size     = \n| image\t=\t\n| caption        = \n| director       = Lionel Harris\n| producer       = \n| writer         =  David Lyons\n| based on       = play by Richard Benyon\n| starring       = \n| music          = \n| cinematography = \n| editing        = \n| distributor    = \n| studio         = Associated Television\n| released       = 18 December 1962 (UK)\n| runtime        = 90 mins<ref>http://bufvc.ac.uk/screenplays/index.php/prog/1561</ref>\n\n| country        = Australia\n| language       = English\n| budget         = \n}}\nThe play was filmed by British TV in 1962.<ref>http://ctva.biz/UK/ITV/ITV_PlayOfTheWeek_08_(1962-63).htm</ref><ref>[http://www.austlit.edu.au/austlit/page/8110109 1962 TV adaptation] at [[AustLit]]</ref>\n\nIt screened for the ''[[General Motors Hour]]'' in Australia on 1 September 1962.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hrc.org.au/files/People/1962/May%201962029%20OPT.pdf|page=7|title=Television for 1962|website=GMH People|date=May 1962}}</ref>\n\n===Cast===\n*[[June Brunell]] as Maria\n*[[Lewis Fiander|Lewis Flander]] as Gino Bianchi\n*John Lee as Det.-Sgt Lukie\n*[[Reg Lye]] as Donny Pratt\n*[[Keith Michell]] as Clarry\n*Victor Platt as Poppa Bianchi\n*[[Madge Ryan]] as Leila Pratt\n*Gillian Webb as Momma Bianchi\n\n==1968 TV adaptation==\n{{Infobox television episode\n| title        = The Shifting Heart\n| series       = [[Wednesday Theatre]]\n| image        = \n| caption      = \n| season       = 4\n| episode      = 32\n| director     = \n| teleplay     = Richard Benyon\n| producer     = \n| photographer =\n| airdate      = 7 August 1968\n| length       = 65 minutes.<ref>{{cite news|title=TV for Today|newspaper=Sydney Morning Herald|date=7 August 1968|page=20}}</ref>\n| guests       = \n| prev         = Lysistrata\n| next         = Dublin One\n}}\nThe play was filmed for TV in 1968 as part of ''[[Wednesday Theatre]]''.  It starred Anne Charleston and Tom Oliver, who later worked together on the TV series ''[[Neighbours]]''. Australian TV drama was relatively rare at the time.<ref>{{cite magazine|first=Stephen|last=Vagg|url=https://www.filmink.com.au/60-australian-tv-plays-1950s-60s/|magazine=Filmink|title=60 Australian TV Plays of the 1950s & '60s|date=February 18, 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Cast===\n*Madge Ryan as Momma\n*[[Tom Oliver]]\n*[[Anne Charleston]]\n*Syd Conabere<ref>http://www.austlit.edu.au/austlit/page/8110365</ref>\n*[[Terry Norris]]\n*Alan Bickford\n*Berys Marsh\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.ausstage.edu.au/pages/work/1348 Australian productions] at [[AusStage]]\n*[https://www-austlit-edu-au.ezproxy.sl.nsw.gov.au/austlit/page/C244588 ''The Shifting Heart''] at [[AustLit]] (subscription required)\n*[https://www-austlit-edu-au.ezproxy.sl.nsw.gov.au/austlit/page/8110365 1968 TV production] at [[AustLit]]\n{{Oscar Whitbread}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Shifting Hearts}}\n[[Category:Australian plays]]\n[[Category:1957 plays]]\n[[Category:1950s Australian plays]]\n[[Category:Fiction set in 1956]]\n[[Category:Melbourne in fiction]]\n[[Category:1968 television plays]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2015}}\n{{italic title}}\n'''''The Shifting Heart''''' is a play written in 1957<ref>{{cite book|last=Milne|first=Geoffrey|title=Theatre Australia (Un)limited|year=2004|publisher=Rodopi}}</ref> in Australia by [[Richard Beynon (writer)|Richard Beynon]], it is an insight to the [[psychology]] of racism and its victims. In the background of 1950s [[Collingwood, Victoria|Collingwood]], [[Melbourne]].\n\n== Characters ==\n\n* Momma Bianchi\n* Poppa Bianchi\n* Gino Bianchi\n* Maria Bianchi (Fowler)\n* Clarry Fowler\n* Leila Pratt\n* Donny Pratt\n* Detective-Sergeant Lukie\n\n== Setting ==\n''The Shifting Heart'' is set in 1956, Collingwood, Melbourne on Christmas Eve. At the time, Collingwood was a poor suburb populated by lower class Australian families and Italian immigrants.\n\nThe play published in 1960 by [[Angus & Robertson]] begins with two pages of stage direction. It describes the home of Italians Mr. & Mrs. Vicenzo Bianchi, the stage is their backyard. On stage left there is a large [[garbage can]] that is overfilled, the overflow is in a small household bucket. On each side of the stage is the wall of the neighbours.\n\nOn stage left is the wall between the Pratt family, Leila and Donny. The wall is a fence that relaxes in the wind and shows an air of [[dilapidation]]. The boards are able to be pushed apart enough to let the Pratts enter the Bianchis' backyard.\n\nOn stage right there is a wall described as a formidable barrier, complete with a length of [[barbed wire]] across the top. It is low enough for the woman living there to toss garbage over. In the first pages of dialog and notes in the stage direction, it is clear that there is a \"war\" going on between the family living stage right against the Bianchis because they are Italian. The Pratt family is on the side of the Bianchi family.\n\n==Productions==\n''The Shifting Heart'' premiered at the [[Elizabethan Theatre, Sydney|Elizabethan Theatre]] in Sydney in October 1957, presented by the [[Australian Elizabethan Theatre Trust]]. It toured nationally for a year, including seasons at the [[Comedy Theatre, Melbourne|Comedy Theatre]] in Melbourne and Her Majesty's Theatre in Brisbane.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ausstage.edu.au/pages/work/1348|title=AusStage \u2013 The Shifting Heart|website=www.ausstage.edu.au|access-date=2016-06-15}}</ref>\n\nThe play debuted in England in 1959 where it played a West End season at the [[Duke of York's Theatre]].<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article103127915 |title=Enthusiastic U.K. Reception For Australian Play. |newspaper=[[The Canberra Times]] |date=12 August 1959 |accessdate=24 May 2015 |page=19 |via=National Library of Australia}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article103131252 |title=\"Shifting Heart\" Well Received |newspaper=[[The Canberra Times]] |volume=34 |issue=9,396 |date=16 September 1959 |accessdate=4 April 2017 |page=3 |via=National Library of Australia}}</ref>\n\nThe ABC made a radio version of the play in 1962.  It was adapted for Australian television on the ABC in 1968.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article107066391 |title=Richard Beynon's prize-winning play 'The Shifting Heart' will be telecast on ABC-3 at 8 o'clock tonight. Virginia Gerrett interviewed the author in London recently. The 'Z-Cars' controller. |newspaper=[[The Canberra Times]] |date=7 August 1968 |accessdate=24 May 2015 |page=12 |via=National Library of Australia}}</ref>\n\nNotable revivals include those of Melbourne's [[Union Theatre Repertory Company]] in 1962, Sydney's Marian Street Theatre in 1981, Sydney's [[Phillip Street Theatre]] in 1984, and the [[State Theatre Company of South Australia]] in 1996.\n\n==1962 TV adaptation==\n{{Infobox film\n| name           = The Shifting Heart\n| image size     = \n| image\t=\t\n| caption        = \n| director       = Lionel Harris\n| producer       = \n| writer         =  David Lyons\n| based on       = play by Richard Benyon\n| starring       = \n| music          = \n| cinematography = \n| editing        = \n| distributor    = \n| studio         = Associated Television\n| released       = 18 December 1962 (UK)\n| runtime        = 90 mins<ref>http://bufvc.ac.uk/screenplays/index.php/prog/1561</ref>\n\n| country        = Australia\n| language       = English\n| budget         = \n}}\nThe play was filmed by British TV in 1962.<ref>http://ctva.biz/UK/ITV/ITV_PlayOfTheWeek_08_(1962-63).htm</ref><ref>[http://www.austlit.edu.au/austlit/page/8110109 1962 TV adaptation] at [[AustLit]]</ref>\n\nIt screened for the ''[[General Motors Hour]]'' in Australia on 1 September 1962.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hrc.org.au/files/People/1962/May%201962029%20OPT.pdf|page=7|title=Television for 1962|website=GMH People|date=May 1962}}</ref>\n\n===Cast===\n*[[June Brunell]] as Maria\n*[[Lewis Fiander|Lewis Flander]] as Gino Bianchi\n*John Lee as Det.-Sgt Lukie\n*[[Reg Lye]] as Donny Pratt\n*[[Keith Michell]] as Clarry\n*Victor Platt as Poppa Bianchi\n*[[Madge Ryan]] as Leila Pratt\n*Gillian Webb as Momma Bianchi\n\n==1968 TV adaptation==\n{{Infobox television episode\n| title        = The Shifting Heart\n| series       = [[Wednesday Theatre]]\n| image        = \n| caption      = \n| season       = 4\n| episode      = 32\n| director     = \n| teleplay     = Richard Benyon\n| producer     = \n| photographer =\n| airdate      = 7 August 1968\n| length       = 65 minutes.<ref>{{cite news|title=TV for Today|newspaper=Sydney Morning Herald|date=7 August 1968|page=20}}</ref>\n| guests       = \n| prev         = Lysistrata\n| next         = Dublin One\n}}\nThe play was filmed for TV in 1968 as part of ''[[Wednesday Theatre]]''.  It starred Anne Charleston and Tom Oliver, who later worked together on the TV series ''[[Neighbours]]''. Australian TV drama was relatively rare at the time.<ref>{{cite magazine|first=Stephen|last=Vagg|url=https://www.filmink.com.au/60-australian-tv-plays-1950s-60s/|magazine=Filmink|title=60 Australian TV Plays of the 1950s & '60s|date=February 18, 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Cast===\n*Madge Ryan as Momma\n*[[Tom Oliver]]\n*[[Anne Charleston]]\n*Syd Conabere<ref>http://www.austlit.edu.au/austlit/page/8110365</ref>\n*[[Terry Norris]]\n*Alan Bickford\n*Berys Marsh\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.ausstage.edu.au/pages/work/1348 Australian productions] at [[AusStage]]\n*[https://www-austlit-edu-au.ezproxy.sl.nsw.gov.au/austlit/page/C244588 ''The Shifting Heart''] at [[AustLit]] (subscription required)\n*[https://www-austlit-edu-au.ezproxy.sl.nsw.gov.au/austlit/page/8110365 1968 TV production] at [[AustLit]]\n{{Oscar Whitbread}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Shifting Hearts}}\n[[Category:Australian plays]]\n[[Category:1957 plays]]\n[[Category:1950s Australian plays]]\n[[Category:Fiction set in 1956]]\n[[Category:Melbourne in fiction]]\n[[Category:1968 television plays]]\n", "name_user": "2001:8003:8045:7500:b9e5:e161:94ea:2b3", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(\u2192\u200eCharacters)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Shifting_Heart"}
{"title_page": "Solange Knowles", "text_new": "{{short description|American performance artist and musician}}\n{{good article}}{{Use mdy dates|date=March 2020}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name               = Solange\n| image              = Solange (220707).jpg\n| caption            = Knowles on stage in [[Oslo]] in 2017\n| birth_name         = Solange Piaget Knowles\n| birth_date         = {{Birth date and age|1986|6|24}}<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2012/06/22/solange-knowles-birthday-_n_1619787.html|title=Solange' Birthday: As Star Turns 26, A Look At Fabulous Celebrity Sisters (PHOTOS)|work=The Huffington Post|date=June 24, 2012}}</ref>\n| birth_place        = [[Houston]], [[Texas]], U.S.<!--As per WP:LINKDIRECT and Template:infobox person, birth/death place indicates city, state, then country. No need to spell out \"United States; 'U.S.' is fine.-->\n| other_names        = Solange Knowles-Smith<!--Had one credit as Solange Knowles-Smith. Not necessary to list Solange Knowles-Ferguson (which is not a name that Solange is professionally or legally known by. See: Template:Infobox person. -->\n| occupation         = {{flatlist|\n*Singer-songwriter\n*performance artist\n*record producer\n*actress}}\n| years_active       = 2001\u2013present\n| net_worth          =\n| spouse             = {{ubl|{{marriage|Daniel Smith|2004|2007|end=div}}|{{marriage|[[Alan Ferguson (director)|Alan Ferguson]]|2014|2019|end=sep.}}}}\n| children           = 1\n| parents            = {{ubl|[[Mathew Knowles]]|[[Tina Knowles]]}}\n| relatives          = [[Beyonc\u00e9]] (sister)\n| module             = {{Infobox musical artist\n| embed = yes\n| background         = solo_singer\n| genre              = {{hlist|[[Contemporary R&B|R&B]]|[[pop music|pop]]|[[hip hop music|hip hop]]|[[funk]]|[[soul music|soul]]}}\n| instrument         = {{hlist|Vocals|keyboards}}\n| label              = {{hlist|[[Mathew Knowles|Music World]]|[[Columbia Records|Columbia]]|{{nowrap|[[Interscope Geffen A&M]]}}|[[Terrible Records|Terrible]]|[[Saint Records|Saint]]}}\n| associated_acts    = {{hlist|[[Destiny's Child]]|[[Kindness (musician)|Adam Banbridge]]|[[Chromeo]]|[[Dev Hynes]]|[[Kelela]]|John Carroll Kirby|[[David Longstreth]]|[[Master P]]|[[Lil Wayne]]|\n[[Janelle Mon\u00e1e]]|[[Panda Bear (musician)|Panda Bear]]|[[Raphael Saadiq]]|[[Sampha]]|[[Standing on the Corner (band)|Standing on the Corner]]|[[Tyler, the Creator]]|[[Pharrell Williams]]|[[Patrick Wimberly]]}}\n}}\n| website            = {{URL|www.solangemusic.com}}\n}}\n\n'''Solange Piaget Knowles''' ({{IPAc-en|s|o\u028a|\u02c8|l|\u0251\u02d0|n|\u0292}}; born June 24, 1986),<ref name=biographychannel>{{cite web| url = http://www.biography.com/people/solange-21265489#awesm=~oE4Tpn1dO6DMDk | title= Solange Biography | publisher= [[The Biography Channel]] | accessdate= May 12, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.familysearch.org/ark:/61903/1:1:VDV5-1SC|title=Solange Piaget Knowles - Texas Birth Index|date=June 24, 1986|website=[[FamilySearch]]|access-date=August 19, 2019}}</ref> also known [[mononymous person|mononymously]] as '''Solange''', is an American singer, songwriter, record producer, performance artist<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.surfacemag.com/articles/solange-knowles-is-not-a-pop-star/|title=Solange Knowles Is Not a Pop Star|date=January 11, 2018|website=SURFACE|language=en-US|access-date=November 17, 2019}}</ref>, and actress. Expressing an interest in music from an early age, Knowles had several temporary stints as a backup dancer for [[Destiny's Child]], which featured her elder sister, [[Beyonc\u00e9]], among its members, before signing with her father [[Mathew Knowles]]'s [[Music World Entertainment]] label. At age 16, Knowles released her first studio album ''[[Solo Star]]'' (2002). Between 2005 and 2007, Knowles had several minor acting roles, including the direct-to-video ''[[Bring It On: All or Nothing]]'' (2006) and continued writing music for Beyonc\u00e9 and for former Destiny's Child group members [[Kelly Rowland]] and [[Michelle Williams (singer)|Michelle Williams]].\n\nIn 2007, Knowles began to record music again. Her second studio album ''[[Sol-Angel and the Hadley St. Dreams]]'' (2008) deviated from the pop-oriented music of her debut to the Motown Sound of the 1960s and 1970s. It peaked at number nine on [[Billboard 200|US ''Billboard'' 200]] and received positive reviews from critics. She followed this up with the [[1980s music|1980s]] pop and [[Contemporary R&B|R&B]]\u2013inspired extended play ''[[True (EP)|True]]'' (2012) on [[Terrible Records]] and her imprint [[Saint Records]]. Her third studio album, ''[[A Seat at the Table]]'' (2016) was released to widespread critical acclaim and became her first number-one album in the United States. The album's lead single, \"[[Cranes in the Sky]]\" won the Grammy for [[Grammy Award for Best R&B Performance|Best R&B Performance]]. Her fourth studio album, ''[[When I Get Home (album)|When I Get Home]]'', was released in 2019.\n\nKnowles was heavily influenced by [[Motown]] [[girl group]]s and says that her first passion is songwriting. She is frequently compared by the media to her sister, Beyonc\u00e9, but Solange insists they have different aspirations and are musically different. She has been ranked by ''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]'' as the 100th most successful dance artist of all-time,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.billboard.com/charts/greatest-top-dance-club-artists|title=Greatest of All Time Top Dance Club Artists : Page 1|publisher=|accessdate=May 23, 2017}}</ref> and in 2017 was honored with the \"Impact Award\" at [[Billboard Women in Music|''Billboard'' Women in Music]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/biz/articles/8053968/solange-honored-as-billboard-impact-award-winner-for-2017-women-in-music-ciara|title=Solange Honored As Billboard Impact Award Winner for 2017 Women In Music|work=billboard.com}}</ref> Her other ventures include an endorsement deal with [[Rimmel|Rimmel London]] and a line of hip-hop-oriented merchandise for young children. On November 16, 2014, Knowles married music video director [[Alan Ferguson (director)|Alan Ferguson]] in [[New Orleans]], Louisiana.<ref name=\"people\">{{cite magazine| url = http://www.people.com/article/solange-knowles-marries-alan-ferguson | title= Solange Knowles Marries Alan Ferguson| magazine= [[People Magazine]] | accessdate= November 16, 2014}}</ref>\n\n==Early life==\nKnowles was born in [[Houston]], Texas, to [[Mathew Knowles]] and [[Tina Knowles]]. Solange's older sister is singer and performer [[Beyonc\u00e9]]. Her father, originally from Alabama, is [[African American]], and her mother, originally from [[Texas]], is [[Louisiana Creole people|Creole]] (with Cameroonian, Native American, and French ancestry).<ref name=\"FOX\">{{cite news |url=http://www.foxnews.com/story/0,2933,204978,00.html?sPage=fnc/entertainment/beyonce |title=Beyonc\u00e9 Knowles' Biography |publisher=[[Fox News Channel]] |date=April 15, 2008 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111225022759/http://www.foxnews.com/story/0,2933,204978,00.html?sPage=fnc%2Fentertainment%2Fbeyonce |archivedate=December 25, 2011 |url-status=dead  |access-date=July 28, 2019 }}</ref><ref name=smol1>{{cite news|last=Smolenyak|first=Megan|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/megan-smolenyak-smolenyak/a-peek-into-blue-ivy-cart_b_1200346.html |title=A Peek into Blue Ivy Carter's Past |work=The Huffington Post|date=January 12, 2012 |accessdate=January 30, 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|url=https://archive.org/details/impoliteconversa0000dani |url-access=registration |quote=beyonce native american african french l'oreal. |title=Impolite Conversations: On Race, Politics, Sex, Money, and Religion |publisher=Simon and Schuster |author1=Daniels, Cora |author2=Jackson, John L. |page=[https://archive.org/details/impoliteconversa0000dani/page/198 198] |year= 2014 |isbn=9781476739113 |accessdate=June 10, 2015}}</ref> Her maternal grandparents are Lumis Beyinc\u00e9 and [[Agn\u00e9z Der\u00e9on]], (a [[sewing|seamstress]]). She is also a descendant of [[Acadia]]n leader [[Joseph Broussard]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/megan-smolenyak-smolenyak/a-peek-into-blue-ivy-cart_b_1200346.html |title=A Peek into Blue Ivy Carter's Past |first= |last= |work=[[The Huffington Post]] |publisher=[[AOL]] |date=January 12, 2012 |accessdate=January 14, 2012}}</ref> As a child, Knowles studied dance and theater. At the age of five, she made her singing debut at an amusement park. She began writing songs at the age of nine.<ref name=\"CosmoQ&A\">{{cite web|url=http://www.cosmogirl.com/blog/solange-knowles-qa|title=Solange Knowles Q&A|date=August 25, 2008|work=[[Cosmo Girl]]|accessdate=December 10, 2008|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090810190126/http://www.cosmogirl.com/blog/solange-knowles-qa|archivedate=August 10, 2009}}</ref> At 13, she decided to pursue recording, but her parents initially advised her to wait. At the age of 15 Knowles replaced a departed dancer and performed with her sister's group [[Destiny's Child]] on tour.{{cn|date=April 2020}} During the group's opening stint for American pop singer [[Christina Aguilera]]'s tour, Knowles temporarily replaced Destiny's Child member [[Kelly Rowland]] after she broke her toes backstage during a costume change.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1428039/20001009/destinys_child.jhtml|title=Destiny's Child Has Tough Backstage Break|last=Manning|first=Kara|date=October 9, 2000|publisher=MTV|accessdate=November 4, 2008}}</ref>\n\n==Career==\n\n===2001\u20132003: Early career and ''Solo Star''===\nManaged by her father Mathew, Knowles first ventured into the music business in 2001 as the lead singer, backed by Destiny's Child, on the title theme song for the animated television series ''[[The Proud Family]]''.<ref name=\"rs080602\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.teenvogue.com/story/solange-knowles-the-proud-family-theme-song|title=Solange Knowles Sang 'The Proud Family' Theme Song Onstage Because Nostalgia Is REAL|first=Cond\u00e9|last=Nast|website=Teen Vogue|accessdate=February 23, 2019}}</ref> She also was a featured performer on \"Hey Goldmember\" for the soundtrack to the 2002 film ''[[Austin Powers in Goldmember]]'',<ref name=\"rs080602\"/> as well as a backup singer on the track \"Little Drummer Boy\" on Destiny's Child's 2001 holiday album ''[[8 Days of Christmas]]''.<ref name=\"MossNo\">{{cite news|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1452941/20020315/knowles_solange.jhtml|title=Solange, Beyonc\u00e9's Lil' Sis, Says She's No Destiny's Child|last=Moss|first=Corey|date=March 18, 2002|publisher=MTV|accessdate=November 4, 2008}}</ref> In 2002, she was featured on [[Lil Romeo]]'s second studio album ''[[Game Time]]'', singing portions of [[Luther Vandross]]-penned \"So Amazing\" on the single \"True Love\", and on Kelly Rowland's debut solo album ''[[Simply Deep]]'', for which she also wrote the title track, \"Beyond Imagination\" and \"Obsession\". In 2001 she appeared as [[Bow Wow (rapper)|Lil' Bow Wow's]] date in the music video for his single \"[[Puppy Love (Bow Wow song)|Puppy Love]]\".<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1457156/20020822/rowland_kelly.jhtml|title=Kelly Rowland Moves Into 'Leave It To Beaver' House|last=Corey|first=Moss|date=August 23, 2002|publisher=MTV|accessdate=November 4, 2008}}</ref> She also made an appearance on ''[[The Master of Disguise]]'' soundtrack and made cameos in [[Play (Swedish band)|Play]]'s video for \"M.A.S.T.E.R. (Part II)\" featuring [[Lil' Fizz]].\n\nIn 2002, she lent her voice for the character Chanel, the cousin of the protagonist [[Penny Proud]], in the episode \"Behind Family Lines\" to the animated television series ''The Proud Family''.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1458489/20021104/ashanti.jhtml|title=Ashanti, Keys, Solange 'Proud' Participants in Animated Series|last=D'Angelo|first=Joe|date=November 4, 2002|publisher=MTV|accessdate=February 3, 2009}}</ref>\nIn June 2003, Mathew Knowles excitedly announced that he was considering adding Solange to Destiny's Child when the group reunited in 2004, thus turning them into a quartet for the first time since short-lived member [[Farrah Franklin]] left in 2000. Mathew Knowles said he was testing the reactions, and, judging by what he had heard, \"it seems like a good idea\".<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1473417/20030626/destinys_child.jhtml|title=Destiny's Child May Get A New Member Next Year|last=Moss|first=Corey|date=June 26, 2003|publisher=MTV|accessdate=November 4, 2008}}</ref> Later in August, however, Beyonc\u00e9 said it was only a rumor and Destiny's Child would remain a trio. Rowland added, \"She's a solo star,\" [[name-dropping]] Knowles' debut album.<ref name=\"MossTrio\">{{cite news|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1477173/20030825/destinys_child.jhtml|title=Destiny's Child To Remain A Trio, Says Beyonc\u00e9|last=Corey|first=Moss|date=August 25, 2003|publisher=MTV|accessdate=November 4, 2008}}</ref>\n\nAt the age of 14, Solange Knowles started working on her debut album ''[[Solo Star]]'',<ref name=\"RamaswamySoul\">{{cite web|url=http://scotlandonsunday.scotsman.com/entertainment/Solange-Knowles-interview--Soul.4650388.jp|title=Solange Knowles interview \u2013 Soul sister|last=Ramaswamy|first=Chitra|date=November 2, 2008|work=[[Scotland on Sunday]]|accessdate=November 3, 2008}}</ref> which involved American producers such as [[Jermaine Dupri]], [[The Neptunes]], [[Linda Perry]] and [[Timbaland]] among others. She then recorded the album under her father's [[Music World Entertainment]] label with [[Columbia Records]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nydailynews.com/entertainment/music-arts/solange-knowles-article-1.1790851|title=Who is Solange Knowles? Everything you need to know about Beyonce's little sister|work=New York Daily News|date=May 13, 2014|last=Pesce|first=Nicole Lyn}}</ref> The album is primarily uptempo [[Contemporary R&B|R&B]], although Knowles said there are pop, rock, [[reggae]] and [[Hip hop music|hip hop]] influences.<ref name=\"rs080602\">{{cite news|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/news/story/5933946/solange_knowles_has_star_power|title=Solange Knowles Has \"Star\" Power |last=Bliss|first=Karen|date=August 6, 2002|work=[[Rolling Stone]]|accessdate=January 31, 2009}}</ref><ref name=\"MossNo\"/> Knowles co-wrote and co-produced some of the 15 tracks in the album,<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1458534/20021105/knowles_solange.jhtml|title=Solange 'Feeling' It With Beyonc\u00e9, N.O.R.E., Others|last=Wiederhorn|first=Jon|date=November 6, 2002|publisher=MTV|accessdate=November 4, 2008}}</ref> including its [[lead single]], \"[[Feelin' You (Part II)]]\". The song failed to enter the [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]], but reached number three on both the [[Hot R&B/Hip-Hop Singles Sales]] and [[Dance/Electronic Singles Sales|Hot Dance Music/Maxi-Singles Sales]] chart.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.billboard.biz/bbbiz/charts/search/detailed_chart_display.jsp?g=s&cd=Jan-25-2003&f=Hot_R&B/Hip-Hop_Singles_Sales&model.chartId=3048275|title=Hot R&B/Hip-Hop Singles Sales|work=[[Billboard magazine|Billboard]]|publisher=[[Nielsen Business Media]]|date=January 25, 2003|accessdate=July 21, 2008}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Billboard \u2013 Maxi Single Sales|url=https://books.google.com/?id=0Q0EAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA25&lpg=PA25&dq=%22Hot+Dance+Music/Maxi-Singles+Sales+solange#v=onepage&q=solange&f=false|publisher=Nielsen Business Media, Inc.|accessdate=November 7, 2016|language=en|date=January 11, 2003}}</ref> ''Solo Star'' was released on January 21, 2003 in the United States, where it debuted at number 49 on the [[Billboard 200|''Billboard'' 200]] and reached number 23 on the [[Top R&B/Hip-Hop Albums]] chart.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.billboard.com/charts/2003-02-08/billboard-200 |title=The Billboard 200: Solo Star |date=February 2008 |work=Billboard |publisher=Nielsen Business Media |accessdate=November 4, 2008 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140101103147/http://www.billboard.com/charts/2003-02-08/billboard-200 |archivedate=January 1, 2014 }}</ref><ref name=\"ConcepcionTop\">{{cite web|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/news/1045367/solange-not-out-to-top-sister-beyonce-on-new-album|last=Concepcion|first=Mariel|date=May 16, 2008|title=Solange Not Out To Top Sister Beyonc\u00e9 On New Album|work=[[Billboard magazine|Billboard]]|publisher=Nielsen Business Media|accessdate=July 21, 2008}}</ref> ''Solo Star'' had a mixed critical reception: William Ruhlmann of [[AllMusic]] called it a \"state-of-the-art contemporary R&B album\", but deemed Knowles \"lost somewhere in the mix\".<ref>{{cite web|url={{Allmusic|class=album|id=r625601|pure_url=yes}}|title=Solo Star: Solange Knowles|last=Ruhlmann|first=William|website=AllMusic|accessdate=January 31, 2009}}</ref> By mid-2008, the album had sold 112,000 copies domestically according to [[Nielsen SoundScan]].<ref name=\"ConcepcionTop\"/>\n\n===2003\u20132008: Films and ''Sol-Angel and the Hadley St. Dreams''===\n[[File:Solange Knowles @ The Ruby Lounge, Manchester, (14 11 08) (3041189101).jpg|thumb|Knowles performing at the Ruby Lounge in [[Manchester]] in 2008]]\nIn 2004, she guest starred in the episode \"The Catch\" of the sitcom ''[[One on One (TV series)|One on One]]''.\nKnowles appeared as a teenager in the 2004 [[comedy film]] ''[[Johnson Family Vacation]]'', starring alongside American actors [[Cedric the Entertainer]], [[Vanessa L. Williams|Vanessa Williams]] and Bow Wow.<ref name=\"MossTrio\"/> She provided a song for its soundtrack\u2014\"[[Freedom (Solange Knowles song)|Freedom]]\", a collaboration with the Houston-based funk-jazz band [[Drop Trio]]. Although the reviews were generally negative, Knowles earned praise from ''[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]'' magazine: \"Solange Knowles is nearly as dazzling as big sister Beyonc\u00e9 and does little more than smile winningly in her first bigscreen outing.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.variety.com/review/VE1117923532.html?categoryid=31&cs=1|title=Johnson Family Vacation|last=Lowry|first=Brian|date=April 7, 2004|work=Variety|accessdate=February 3, 2009}}</ref>\nIn 2006, she starred as a cheerleading captain in the film ''[[Bring It On: All or Nothing]]'', the third installment of the ''Bring It On'' series, alongside American actress and singer [[Hayden Panettiere]]. What little critical reaction the low-budget, [[Direct-to-video|direct-to-DVD]] movie got was negative,<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/bring_it_on_all_or_nothing/ | title=Bring It On: All or Nothing (2006) | website=[[Rotten Tomatoes]] | accessdate=February 3, 2009}}</ref> and Knowles was described as an \"affordable young starlet\".<ref>{{cite news | url=http://efilmcritic.com/review.php?movie=14815&reviewer=392 | title=Bring It On: All or Nothing | author=Cornelius, David | publisher=Efilmcritic.com | date=August 10, 2006 | accessdate=February 3, 2009}}</ref> Knowles uses her full name for her acting, rather than just the first name she uses when singing; for ''Bring It On: All or Nothing'', she was billed as Solange Knowles-Smith,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://abcfamily.go.com/abcfamily/path/section_Movies+BringItOnAllOrNothing/page_Detail |title=Bring It On: All Or Nothing |publisher=[[ABC Family]] |accessdate=January 1, 2009 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080822211011/http://abcfamily.go.com/abcfamily/path/section_Movies%2BBringItOnAllOrNothing/page_Detail |archivedate=August 22, 2008 |url-status=dead }}</ref> reflecting her married state at the time.\n\nAfter the release of her debut album, Knowles started acting in films followed by a career break.<ref name=\"BreakingSolange\">{{cite web|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/blogs/breaking/2008/09/breaking-solange.php|title=Breaking: Solange|date=September 23, 2008|work=Rolling Stone|accessdate=January 31, 2009}}</ref> While she was married, her family moved to [[Idaho]], and, while staying there, resumed writing songs including the singles \"[[Get Me Bodied]]\" and \"[[Upgrade U]]\" from her sister's second solo album, ''[[B'Day (Beyonc\u00e9 album)|B'Day]]''.<ref name=\"BreakingSolange\"/><ref name=\"Co-Publishing Deal\">{{cite web|url=http://www.marketwire.com/mw/release.do?id=762009|date=August 20, 2007|title=Solange Knowles Signs a Worldwide Co-Publishing Deal With EMI Music Publishing}}</ref> Knowles earned the R&B and Hip-Hop Song accolade for \"Get Me Bodied\" at the 2008 [[ASCAP Awards]].<ref name=\"ascap\">{{cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/pressRelease/idUS28916+23-Jul-2008+PRN20080723|title=Solange Knowles Enjoys the #1 Spot Again|date=July 22, 2008|publisher=[[PR Newswire]]|agency=[[Reuters]]|accessdate=November 5, 2008|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090109183332/http://www.reuters.com/article/pressRelease/idUS28916+23-Jul-2008+PRN20080723|archivedate=January 9, 2009}}</ref> She had also written songs for Destiny's Child, and members Kelly Rowland and [[Michelle Williams (singer)|Michelle Williams]].{{cn|date=April 2020}} In 2004, while pregnant with her son Daniel, she made a [[cameo appearance]] in Destiny's Child's music video for \"[[Soldier (Destiny's Child song)|Soldier]]\".<ref>{{cite video|people=[[Ray Kay|Kay, Ray]] (Director)|date=2005|title=Soldier|medium=Music video|publisher=[[Sony BMG]]|location=United States}}</ref>\n\nAfter the divorce, Knowles returned to Houston to begin working on her second album. Knowles renewed her management, signing a record deal with [[Geffen Records|Geffen]] and a publishing deal with [[EMI]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/news/1047083/solange-knowles-inks-with-geffen|title=Solange Knowles Inks With Geffen|last=Crosley|first=Hillary|date=December 11, 2007|work=Billboard|publisher=Nielsen Business Media|accessdate=November 6, 2008}}</ref><ref name=\"EdwardsFlying\">{{cite web|url=http://www.essence.com/2007/10/05/solange-knowles-flying-solo/|title=Solange Knowles Flying Solo|last=Edwards|first=Jeanine|work=[[Essence (magazine)|Essence]]|accessdate=November 3, 2008}}</ref> Knowles finished working on her second studio album in 2008 and titled the project ''[[Sol-Angel and the Hadley St. Dreams]]''. It includes production by [[CeeLo Green]], [[Soulshock & Karlin]] and [[Mark Ronson]] as well as an appearance by [[Bilal (musician)|Bilal]]. A collection of 1960s and 1970s influenced songs,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://clutchmagonline.com/lifeculture/feature/destinys-child-solange-comes-of-age/|title=Destiny's Child: Solange Comes of Age|last=Arthur|first=Sylvia|date=July 1, 2008|work=Clutch|accessdate=November 6, 2008|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101225004726/http://clutchmagonline.com/lifeculture/feature/destinys-child-solange-comes-of-age/|archive-date=December 25, 2010|url-status=dead}}</ref> it is seen as a departure from her pop-oriented debut,<ref name=\"BarkerDecided\">{{cite web|url=http://www.teenhollywood.com/printerversion.asp?r=175424 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180919165210/http://www.teenhollywood.com/printerversion.asp?r=175424 |url-status=dead |archive-date=September 19, 2018 |title=Solange Knowles: She's \"Decided\"! |last=Barker |first=Lynn |date=May 14, 2008 |publisher=Teen Hollywood |accessdate=February 1, 2009 }}</ref><ref name=\"KennedyChannels\">{{cite news|url=http://www.fox59.com/pages/landing_american_dad/?Solange-Knowles-little-sister-to-Beyonce=1&blockID=47623&feedID=13|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180919165204/https://fox59.com/pages/landing_american_dad/?Solange-Knowles-little-sister-to-Beyonce=1&blockID=47623&feedID=13|url-status=dead|archive-date=September 19, 2018|title=Solange Knowles, little sister to Beyonce, channels her inner soul with her sophomore CD|last=Kennedy|first=Mark|date=September 3, 2008|publisher=[[WXIN (TV)|WXIN-TV]]|accessdate=February 1, 2009}}</ref> with what ''Billboard'' magazine called \"more of a modern twist on hip-hop and R&B flecked with tinges of blues and jazz\".<ref name=\"ConcepcionTop\"/> The album was released on August 26, 2008 in the United States. By December 2008, the album had sold over 114,000 copies according to Nielsen SoundScan.<ref name=\"CaulfieldSolange\">{{cite web|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/ask-billboard/266071/ask-billboard-perez-hilton-solange-grace-jones |title=Ask Billboard: Sol-Angel doesn't get wings |last=Caulfield |first=Keith |work=Billboard |publisher=Nielsen Business Media |accessdate=January 31, 2009 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130924162657/http://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/ask-billboard/266071/ask-billboard-perez-hilton-solange-grace-jones |archivedate=September 24, 2013 }}</ref> The album was positively received by critics,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.metacritic.com/music/artists/solange/solangelandthehadleystdreams|title=''Sol-Angel and the Hadley St. Dreams'' by Solange|website=[[Metacritic]]|accessdate=August 16, 2008}}</ref> some of whom considered it far better than her debut.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/2008/nov/10/popandrock|title=Solange|last=Gittins|first=Ian|date=November 10, 2008|work=[[The Guardian]]|accessdate=January 31, 2009 | location=London}}</ref> The album's lead single, \"[[I Decided (song)|I Decided]]\", was released in April 2008, and reached the top of the ''Billboard'' [[Dance Club Songs|Hot Dance Club Play]] chart;<ref name=\"CaulfieldSolange\"/> ''[[Rolling Stone]]'' magazine labelled it her breakthrough single.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/rockdaily/index.php/2008/09/24/on-the-breaking-blog-solange/ |title=On the Breaking Blog: Solange |date=September 24, 2008 |work=[[Rolling Stone]] |accessdate=January 31, 2009 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080927171441/http://www.rollingstone.com/rockdaily/index.php/2008/09/24/on-the-breaking-blog-solange/ |archivedate=September 27, 2008 }}</ref> In support of the album, Knowles began the Solange Presents Sol-Angel and the Hadley St. Dreams Tour in Britain in November 2008.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.polydor.co.uk/topstories.php?story=50|title=Solange Announces UK Dates|date=October 3, 2008|publisher=[[Polydor Records]]|accessdate=November 9, 2008|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://archive.today/20120910201857/http://www.polydor.co.uk/topstories.php?story=50|archivedate=September 10, 2012}}</ref> Knowles also co-wrote \"Scared of Lonely\" and \n\"[[Why Don't You Love Me (Beyonc\u00e9 song)|Why Don't You Love Me]]\" for her sister's third studio album ''[[I Am... Sasha Fierce]]''.\n\nKnowles announced, via her blog HadleyStreetJournal.com, that she would be releasing a series of [[mixtape]]s to coincide with the album. The first mixtape, ''I Can't Get Clearance...'', includes the leaked track \"[[Fuck the Industry|Fuck the Industry (Signed Sincerely)]]\". On this record, Knowles expressed her views on the current state of the music industry. The lyrics to the song name check some major artists such as [[Mary J. Blige]], [[Ashanti (entertainer)|Ashanti]], [[Keyshia Cole]], and Beyonc\u00e9, although she made a point of stating that it does not have \"a negative light to any of [them]\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.solangel.typepad.com/|title=Awwwwwhhhh Dammmmnnn........|date=August 1, 2008|publisher=Solangel.typepad.com|accessdate=November 3, 2008}}</ref> The mixtape was never released, but Solange released \"Fuck the Industry (Signed Sincerely)\" as a single in 2010.\n\n===2008\u20132014: ''True'' EP and Saint Records===\n[[File:Solange Knowles SXSW 2009.jpg|thumb|Knowles performing at [[SXSW]] 2009]]\nIn an interview with MTV in 2009, Knowles revealed that she was determining the type of sound for the follow-up to ''Sol-Angel and the Hadley St. Dreams''.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1609288/20090415/knowles_solange.jhtml|title=Will New Solange Album Have A Duet With Sister Beyonc\u00e9?|last=Vena|first=Jocelyn|date=April 15, 2009|publisher=MTV|accessdate=April 17, 2009}}</ref> Knowles also parted ways with the [[Interscope-Geffen-A&M]] record label group. She would now release her third studio album independently.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rap-up.com/2009/10/31/solange-exits-interscope-records|accessdate=December 2, 2009|title=Solange Exits Interscope Records|date=October 31, 2009|publisher=Rap-Up.com}}</ref> Early in 2010, Knowles traveled to Australia to work with Australian rock band, [[Midnight Juggernauts]] on her third studio album.{{citation needed|date=January 2018}} Knowles had planned to release the album in summer as revealed on her official Twitter account in 2009.<ref>[http://blog.singersroom.com/celebs/index.php/2009/10/09/solange-at-work-on-2010-album/ Solange At Work on 2010 Album]{{webarchive|url=https://archive.today/20120714025506/http://blog.singersroom.com/celebs/index.php/2009/10/09/solange-at-work-on-2010-album/ |date=July 14, 2012 }} Singersroom Celebs \u2013 Retrieved June 16, 2010</ref> She also revealed on her Twitter account that she rented a house in [[Santa Barbara, California]] to get into a certain state of mind while writing and making music.<ref>[http://theybf.com/2010/05/06/solange-readies-next-albumrihannas-te-amo-cover Solange Readies Next Album] The Young, Black & Fabulous \u2013 Retrieved June 16, 2010</ref> On May 7, 2010, Knowles made a guest appearance on the popular children show, ''[[Yo Gabba Gabba!]]'' for a \"Mothers Day Special\" where she performed an original song called \"Momma Loves Baby\".<ref>[http://www.bvnewswire.com/2010/04/29/solange-knowles-yo-gabba-gabba-mothers-day/ Solange Knowles Does Yo Gabba Gabba' for Mothers Day] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100604102245/http://www.bvnewswire.com/2010/04/29/solange-knowles-yo-gabba-gabba-mothers-day |date=June 4, 2010 }} Entertainment News \u2013 Retrieved June 16, 2010</ref><ref>[http://hiphop.popcrunch.com/solange-knowles-yo-gabba-gabba-guest-appearance-may-7/ Solange Knowles \"Yo Gabba Gabba\" Guest Appearance May 7] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100712011206/http://hiphop.popcrunch.com/solange-knowles-yo-gabba-gabba-guest-appearance-may-7/ |date=July 12, 2010 }} Retrieved June 16, 2010</ref><ref>[http://www.monstersandcritics.com/smallscreen/news/article_1552088.php/Solange-Knowles-on-Yo-Gabba-Gabba-for-Mother-s-day-marathon-on-Nick Solange on Yo Gabba Gabba for Mothers Day] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100503094326/http://www.monstersandcritics.com/smallscreen/news/article_1552088.php/Solange-Knowles-on-Yo-Gabba-Gabba-for-Mother-s-day-marathon-on-Nick |date=May 3, 2010 }} Retrieved June 16, 2010</ref>\n\nIn an interview with ''[[Vibe (magazine)|Vibe]]'' on July 7, 2010, Knowles said she suffered \"a little bit of a [[Mental breakdown|breakdown]]\" while recording her new album: \"I literally gave up my sanity for a while to do this record. [...] We literally were waking up in the morning and just making music all day and all night. [...] It just started to wear on me in so many different ways. I started having these crazy [[panic attack]]s.\" Knowles explained how she made sacrifices \"mentally, emotionally and financially\", and continued, \"It's more than an album to me. It's a transitional time in my life.\" Regarding the musical direction of the album, she said the inspiration came from [[New wave music|new wave]] and stated, \"This is a dance record, but the lyrics can get pretty dark at times.\"<ref name=\"Murphy\"/>\nThe singer has also worked on songs with [[Chromeo]] and long-time collaborator [[Pharrell Williams]].\n\nIn September 2012, Solange released a teaser video for \"[[Losing You (Solange Knowles song)|Losing You]]\", which was announced as the lead single from her third studio album. This release marked Solange's first release as a signee of the independent label [[Terrible Records]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.solange-k.net/wordpress/2012/09/02/solange-shoots-video-for-losing-you-in-south-africa/|title=solange-k.net|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120905012829/http://www.solange-k.net/wordpress/2012/09/02/solange-shoots-video-for-losing-you-in-south-africa/|archivedate=September 5, 2012}}</ref> The video was shot in Cape Town, South Africa in early September 2012. Knowles revealed in an interview that her mother Tina Knowles had paid for Solange and her friends to fly out and record the video as her birthday gift. On October 24, 2012, Knowles held a listening party in New York City for her EP ''[[True (EP)|True]]'', released for digital download on iTunes November 27, 2012.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rap-up.com/2012/10/25/solange-previews-true-ep-at-new-york-listening-party/ |title=Solange Previews 'True' EP at New York Listening Party |publisher=Rap-Up.com |date=October 25, 2012 |accessdate=May 14, 2014}}</ref> The CD and vinyl was made available January 8, 2013. Following the EP's release, Solange appeared on the cover of ''[[The Fader]]'' magazine's 84th issue.<ref>{{cite web|title=Solange: Rise and Shine|url=http://www.thefader.com/2013/02/12/solange-rise-and-shine}}</ref>\n\nOn May 14, 2013, Knowles moved to Louisiana and announced that she had launched her own record label named Saint Records, which she will be using to release her third full-length album and future music projects distributed through [[Sony Music Entertainment|Sony]].<ref name=\"Solange Knowles Launches New Record Label, Releases Latest Track Featuring Kendrick Lamar\">{{cite news|last=Nessif|first=Bruna|title=Solange Knowles Launches New Record Label, Releases Latest Track Featuring Kendrick Lamar|url=http://uk.eonline.com/news/418855/solange-knowles-launches-new-record-label-releases-latest-track-featuring-kendrick-lamar|accessdate=May 14, 2013|newspaper=eonline.com|date=May 14, 2013}}</ref> Saint Records was established to focus on not-yet mainstream hip-hop and R&B artists. Solange also collaborated with [[The Lonely Island]] on the song \"Semicolon\" which was featured as part of YouTube's Comedy Week and is featured on The Lonely Island's album, ''[[The Wack Album]]''. On November 11, 2013, Knowles' record label released its first compilation album, ''[[Saint Heron]]''.\n\n===2014\u2013present: ''A Seat at the Table,'' ''When I Get Home,'' and performance art.===\n[[File:Solange - Coachella 2014 (12).jpg|thumb|left|Knowles performing at [[Coachella Valley Music and Arts Festival|Coachella]] in 2014]]\nOn May 15, 2015, Knowles performed \"Rise\" for the first time at an HBO-sponsored event, which was inspired by police killings in [[Ferguson, Missouri|Ferguson]] and [[Baltimore]] and the subsequent protests.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.idolator.com/7592955/solange-new-song-rise-ferguson-baltimore-protest|title=Solange Unveils New Song \"Rise,\" Inspired By Ferguson & Baltimore: Watch|work=Music News, Reviews, and Gossip on Idolator.com|date=May 15, 2015}}</ref> In July 2015, Knowles announced that her third studio album was nearly complete. On her thirtieth birthday, June 24, 2016, she stated that she had completed ''[[A Seat at the Table]]'' three days before her birthday, on June 21.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.fuse.tv/2016/06/solange-new-album-completed|title=Solange's New Album is Completed|date=June 24, 2016|work=[[Fuse.tv]]|accessdate=June 25, 2016}}</ref> The album was released on September 30, 2016, to widespread critical acclaim.<ref>Mary J. DiMeglio, [http://www.billboard.com/articles/news/7526464/solange-knowles-release-new-album-seat-at-table-listen \"Solange Drops New Album, 'A Seat at the Table': Listen,\"] ''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]'', September 30, 2016.</ref> It became her first number-one album in the United States. This made her and Beyonc\u00e9 the first sisters to have both had US number-one albums in a calendar year.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.etonline.com/music/199983_beyonce_and_solange_knowles_become_first_sisters_to_have_number_1_albums/ |title=Beyonce and Solange Knowles Become First Sisters to Land No. 1 Albums |publisher=Etonline.com |date= |accessdate=October 12, 2016}}</ref> On October 3, 2016, Knowles released two music videos from ''A Seat at the Table'': \"Don't Touch my Hair\" and \"Cranes in the Sky\", both co-directed by herself and husband, [[Alan Ferguson (director)|Alan Ferguson]].\n\nDuring the 2017 Roots Picnic Festival in Philadelphia, Pennsylvania, Knowles performed a rendition of the sing-along from ''The Proud Family'', the television series whose theme song she was featured on in 2001, and she participated at the [[Glastonbury Festival|2017 Glastonbury Festival]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.eonline.com/news/859111/solange-leads-the-proud-family-theme-song-sing-along-and-brings-us-back-to-2001 |title=Solange Leads The Proud Family Sing-Along and Kicks It to 2001|publisher=|date=June 5, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.glastonburyfestivals.co.uk/line-up/line-up-2017/|title=Glastonbury Festival - 2017|last=Digital|first=Pretty Good|website=Glastonbury Festival - June 21-25, 2017|language=en-US|access-date=January 7, 2019}}</ref> In December 2017, Solange directed the video of The Weekend by [[SZA (singer)]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/hip-hop/8078596/sza-ctrl-shares-new-solange-knowles-directed-video-for-the-weekend |title=Sza Ctrl Shares New Solange Directed Video For The Weekend|publisher=}}</ref>\n\nOn October 15, 2018, it was announced by Knowles that she would be releasing her fourth studio album in the Fall during an interview with [[New York Times Style Magazine]].<ref>{{cite web |last1=Monroe |first1=Jazz |title=Solange's New Album Coming This Fall |url=https://pitchfork.com/news/solanges-new-album-coming-this-fall/ |website=Pitch Fork |accessdate=October 15, 2018}}</ref> However, this did not come to fruition.\n\nOn January 3, 2019, the [[Coachella Valley Music and Arts Festival]] announced that Solange would co-headline the stage with [[Tame Impala]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.capitalfm.com/events/coachella/2019-line-up-dates-headliner-tickets/|title=Coachella 2019 \u2013 Line Up, Dates, Headliner And More\u2026 Ariana Grande, Childish Gambino Confirmed|website=Capital|language=en|access-date=January 7, 2019}}</ref> The Coachella performance was later canceled due to \u201cmajor production delays\u201d.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://pitchfork.com/news/solange-cancels-coachella-2019-set/|title=Solange Cancels Coachella 2019 Set|last=Nast|first=Cond\u00e9|website=Pitchfork|language=en|access-date=April 8, 2019}}</ref> On January 8, 2019, it was announced Solange would be performing at the [[Bonnaroo Music Festival]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://pitchfork.com/news/bonnaroo-2019-lineup-announced-childish-gambino-solange-phish-cardi-b-more/|title=Bonnaroo 2019 Lineup Announced: Childish Gambino, Solange, Phish, Cardi B, More|website=Pitchfork|language=en|access-date=February 7, 2019}}</ref> She was also confirmed to perform at the UK's [[Parklife (festival)|Parklife]] festival <ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.factmag.com/2019/01/30/cardi-b-solange-parklife-2019/|title=Cardi B, Solange and The Streets announced for Parklife Festival 2019|date=January 30, 2019|publisher=|accessdate=February 23, 2019}}</ref> and [[Lovebox Festival]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.highsnobiety.com/p/lovebox-festival-2019-lineup/|title=Lovebox 2019 Sets Solange, Chance the Rapper & BROCKHAMPTON|date=February 12, 2019|website=Highsnobiety|accessdate=February 23, 2019}}</ref>\n\nOn March 1, 2019, she released her fourth studio album, ''[[When I Get Home (album)|When I Get Home]]'', on all streaming platforms.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://pitchfork.com/news/solange-announces-new-album-when-i-get-home-out-tonight/|title=Solange Releases New Album When I Get Home: Listen|website=Pitchfork|language=en|access-date=March 1, 2019}}</ref> She previously teased the album by posting two video snippets on her Instagram and Twitter, and a personal web page on the African-American social networking site, [[BlackPlanet]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.elle.com/culture/a26575997/solange-black-planet-when-i-get-home-album-announcement/|title=Solange Teased Her New Album on the Social Network Black Planet, and It Means Everything|last=Hubbard|first=Shanita|date=February 28, 2019|website=ELLE|language=en-US|access-date=March 1, 2019}}</ref>\n\nOutside her work of being a singer-songwriter, Solange has also ventured into performance art. In an interview with Surface magazine, she said \"I'm not at all interested in entertainment. I\u2019m really interested in energy exchange between the viewer and the performer. One way to do that is to make an inclusive experience through style, through energy, through space.\u201d<ref name=\":0\" /> She has put on subsequent performance art pieces throughout the world, including Witness! at the [[Elbphilharmonie]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://pitchfork.com/news/solange-announces-witness-performance-piece/|title=Solange Announces \"Witness!\" Performance Piece|website=Pitchfork|language=en|access-date=November 17, 2019}}</ref>, and Bridge-s at the [[J. Paul Getty Museum|Getty Museum]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.latimes.com/entertainment-arts/story/2019-11-15/solange-performance-art-bridges-getty-museum|title=Solange brings her new performance art to the Getty this weekend. Here's a sneak peek|date=November 15, 2019|website=Los Angeles Times|language=en-US|access-date=November 17, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.getty.edu/visit/cal/events/solange.html|title=Bridge-s {{!}} Getty360 Calendar|website=The J. Paul Getty in Los Angeles|language=en|access-date=November 17, 2019}}</ref>.\n\n==Artistry==\n\n===Music and influences===\n{{Listen|pos = right\n |filename     = Solange Dancing in the Dark.ogg\n |title        = \"Dancing in the Dark\"\n |description  = The song features a 1970s [[funk]] sound and contains a thick horn sample from [[Heinz Kiessling]]'s 1960s recording \"Feeling Young\".<ref>ILIKEIT (August 31, 2008). [http://www.singersroom.com/reviews/artist-media-64.asp Music Review \u2013 Solange Knowles: Sol-Angel and the Hadley St. Dreams] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110929125456/http://www.singersroom.com/reviews/artist-media-64.asp |date=September 29, 2011 }}. Singersroom. Retrieved on July 5, 2011.</ref><ref>Godfrey, Sarah (September 13, 2008). [http://www.washingtoncitypaper.com/articles/36159/sloppy-seconds Sloppy Seconds: The Game and Solange have a hard time avoiding the shadow of bigger names]. ''[[Washington City Paper]]''. Retrieved on July 5, 2011.</ref>\n}}\n\nOn her debut album, Knowles had no control over which kinds of music to produce, because \"when you're 14, everyone else is older and more seasoned and you trust their decisions\".<ref name=\"RamaswamySoul\"/> Knowles was more concerned with pleasing her record label by submitting to their desires.<ref name=\"EdwardsFlying\"/>\n\nHer musical influences were better expressed on ''Sol-Angel and the Hadley St. Dreams'', when she considered herself mature and was able to write and produce songs as she wished, without worrying about the expectations of others.<ref name=\"RamaswamySoul\"/> Knowles' lyrics tackle relationships, world issues, and deceased friends,<ref name=\"EdwardsFlying\"/><ref name=\"S2SSolMMD\"/> with her second album focusing on events in her life, such as marriage, divorce, and parenthood.<ref name=\"EdwardsFlying\"/> The album touched upon a variety of genres including [[pop-soul]],<ref name=\"Kellman\">Kellman, Andy. [{{Allmusic|class=album|id=r1412903|pure_url=yes}} Review: ''Sol-Angel and the Hadley St. Dreams'']. [[AllMusic]]. Retrieved on July 22, 2009.</ref> [[psychedelic soul]],<ref>{{cite news|last=Wood|first=Mikael|date=August 28, 2008|url=http://www.latimes.com/entertainment/la-et-solange28-2008aug28,0,6574389.story|title=No little-sister act for Solange Knowles|newspaper=Los Angeles|accessdate=November 18, 2012}}</ref> [[electronica]],<ref name=\"Cinquemani\">Cinquemani, Sal. [http://www.slantmagazine.com/music/music_review.asp?ID=1476 Review: ''Sol-Angel and the Hadley St. Dreams''] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140201173951/http://www.slantmagazine.com/music/music_review.asp?ID=1476 |date=February 1, 2014 }}. [[Slant Magazine]]. Retrieved on July 22, 2009.</ref> and R&B.<ref name=\"Sullivan\">Sullivan, Caroline. [https://www.theguardian.com/music/2008/aug/15/urban1 Review: ''Sol-Angel and the Hadley St. Dreams'']. ''[[The Guardian]]''. Retrieved on July 22, 2009.</ref>\n\nKnowles' debut extended play ''True'' is a new wave album with Knowles stating, \"This is a dance record, but the lyrics can get pretty dark at times.\"<ref name=\"Murphy\">{{cite magazine|first=Keith|last=Murphy|title= A Long Convo With... Solange |url=http://www.vibe.com/content/long-convo-withsolange|date=July 7, 2010|magazine=[[Vibe (magazine)|Vibe]]|accessdate=July 7, 2010}}</ref> Knowles described the EP as \"eclectic with 1980s references and African percussion influences.\" Sonically the extended play is influenced by the keyboard sounds and beats of early 1980s pop and R&B music.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/music/reviews/w3d3 |title=Music \u2013 Review of Solange Knowles \u2013 True |publisher=BBC |date=January 1, 1970 |accessdate=May 14, 2014}}</ref> The EP was recorded in five cities including Santa Barbara, Los Angeles, Houston, New York, and on the German autobahn.<ref>{{cite magazine|url=http://www.elle.com/news/culture/solange-knowles-album-true |title=Solange Knowles New Album True \u2013 Solange Knowles Interview About Music |magazine=Elle |date=April 3, 2014 |accessdate=May 14, 2014}}</ref>\n\nAside from recording, Knowles occasionally paints as her hobby: \"I think that painting, for me, is such an affirmative expression in that sometimes you don't know what the outcome is gonna be and each stroke and each brush for me is an emotion and, in the end, it comes out as a piece which is the most amazing thing.&nbsp;... It definitely provides a different outlet.\"<ref name=\"BarkerDecided\"/>\n\n===Public image===\n[[File:Solange Knowles Cannes 2013.jpg|thumbnail|upright|Knowles at the [[2013 Cannes Film Festival]]]]\nKnowles has always been compared by the media to her sister, Beyonc\u00e9, whom she considers one of her role models. She has expressed her opinion of the comparison in the lyrics to \"God Given Name\": \"I'm not her and never will be\"<ref name=\"RamaswamySoul\"/><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.vibe.com/news/online_exclusives/2008/10/solange_volume_now/ |title=VOLUME NOW: Solange Knowles |last=Murphy |first=Keith |date=October 29, 2008 |work=[[Vibe (magazine)|Vibe]] |accessdate=December 11, 2008 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081223010940/http://www.vibe.com/news/online_exclusives/2008/10/solange_volume_now/ |archivedate=December 23, 2008 }}</ref> \u2013 which was purposely set as the opening track of ''Sol-Angel and the Hadley St. Dreams'' to show their differences.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/news/1044257/solange-steps-out-on-sophomore-solo-disc |title=Solange Steps Out on Sophomore Solo Disc |date=September 5, 2008 |work=Billboard |publisher=Nielsen Business Media |accessdate=January 31, 2009 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130704214635/http://www.billboard.com/articles/news/1044257/solange-steps-out-on-sophomore-solo-disc |archivedate=July 4, 2013 }}</ref> In his review for the album, Jody Rosen of ''Rolling Stone'' magazine referred to the lyrics as a declaration of independence.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/reviews/album/22684278/review/22712701/solangel__the_hadley_st_dreams|title=Solange Knowles: Sol-Angel & The Hadley St. Dreams |last=Rosen|first=Jody|date=September 4, 2008|work=Rolling Stone|accessdate=January 31, 2009}}</ref> Beyonc\u00e9 was unwilling to bring her sister into the recording industry, reasoning that it \"involves a lot of pressure\". Knowles countered by saying, \"It's good to have her advice, but we really have different goals\".<ref name=\"RamaswamySoul\"/> In her sister's self-titled album, Beyonc\u00e9 credits Knowles with the lyric \"my sister taught me I should speak my mind\", as she acknowledges the impact her family has made on her life.\n\nIn recent years, Knowles has also garnered considerable attention as a fashion icon. Her knack for bold colors, mixed prints and [[retro]] styles, as well as her knack for glamorous, fashion-forward looks in her music videography and public appearances, has become integral to her current image. She has been photographed wearing [[Alexander Wang (designer)|Alexander Wang]], [[Alexander McQueen]] and [[Chanel]]. The music video for her 2012 single \"Losing You\" featured a heavy demonstration of the contemporary sartorial movement throughout Africa, [[La Sape]].\n\nSimilarly, her decision to grow her [[Afro-textured hair|natural hair]] initially generated strong reactions from the public. In a cover interview with [[Toyin Ojih Odutola]] for Cultured Magazine, Knowles addressed her shift to minimalist fashion and the response she received from the public, \u201cThis idea that black women could not be minimalist, we could not be subtle\u2014 we have to be big, we have to be loud, we have to be an explosive presence.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.culturedmag.com/solange-knowles-toyin-ojih-odutola/|title=Solange Knowles and Toyin Ojih Odutola Talk Sound, Art and Architecture|date=February 19, 2018|website=Cultured Magazine|language=en-US|access-date=March 8, 2019}}</ref>\n\nAt the 2017 Glamour Women of the Year awards, Knowles wore a yellow [[Jean-Paul Gaultier]] couture gown and was named a Woman of the Year.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.vogue.com/article/solange-knowles-glamour-magazine-women-woman-of-the-year-awards |title=Only Solange Could Pull Off This Bright Yellow Jean Paul Gaultier Gown |author=Rachel Hahn |website=www.vogue.com |date=November 15, 2017|access-date=November 14, 2017}}</ref>\n\nKnowles is an activist for the Black Lives Matter movement and has openly made many statements in opposition to police brutality against African Americans.  On the day of the mass shooting at the Emanuel AME church in Charleston, South Carolina, Solange released a statement posing the following questions: \"Where can we be safe? Where can we be free? Where can we be black?\" Knowles has stated on several occasions that as a black woman, she is \"not really allowed to be mad\" without enforcing racial stereotypes, however, she has \"a lot to be mad about\".\n\nIn July 2016, she took to Twitter to critique police who were present at a peaceful protest in Baton Rouge, saying \"Protesters/marchers have been nothing but peaceful today in Baton Rouge. Police are here pulling out tear gas while children are around\" and  \"Most of the march/protest speakers in Baton Rouge were all under 17 years old... We all left feeling uplifted...Yet as I walked back to my car I personally saw @BRPD pulling huge assault rifles out on peaceful protesters....\"\n\nHer 2016 album, ''A Seat at The Table'', acknowledges the inequalities that black women face in America.  With songs like \"Mad\", \"Don't Touch My Hair\", and \"F.U.B.U\", Knowles addresses stereotypes of young, black Americans, such as criminality or the fixation people have on black women's natural hair, saying she's \"got the right to be mad\".\n\n==Other ventures==\nIn 2001, Knowles collaborated with Destiny's Child to sing the theme song for the Disney Channel show ''The Proud Family''.\n\nIn 2007, Knowles began promoting Baby Jamz, a [[hip hop]]-styled toy line for pre-schoolers.<ref name=\"Co-Publishing Deal\" /><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.nydailynews.com/entertainment/music/2008/06/17/2008-06-17_sister_act_solange_knowles_beyonces_youn.html|title=Sister act: Solange Knowles, Beyonce's younger sibling, comes into her own|last=Smith|first=Olivia|date=June 17, 2008|work=[[New York Daily News]]|accessdate=December 11, 2008}}</ref> It was inspired by her son, Julez, who is fond of hip hop music.<ref name=\"EdwardsFlying\" /> She is the executive producer of the CD, composed of updated hip hop inspired nursery rhymes, which is featured in all of the toys.<ref name=\"Co-Publishing Deal\" />\n\nIn 2008, Knowles was named as ambassador for [[Giorgio Armani]]'s younger diffusion line, Armani Jeans. Armani said Knowles epitomizes the style, which is a \"vision of a young, independent, casual lifestyle with a strong and cool, fashion sensibility\".<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.vogue.co.uk/news/daily/080731-solange-knowles-for-armani-jeans.aspx|title=Armani Says Solange|last=Barnett|first=Leisa|date=July 31, 2008|work=[[Vogue (magazine)|Vogue]]|accessdate=February 1, 2009|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080828232738/http://www.vogue.co.uk/news/daily/080731-solange-knowles-for-armani-jeans.aspx|archivedate=August 28, 2008}}</ref>\n\nKnowles has worked on the award-winning children's television series ''Yo Gabba Gabba!''. She performed \"Momma Loves Baby\" during the live performance when it toured the [[Dallas\u2013Fort Worth metroplex|Dallas\u2013Fort Worth]] area. She also performed \"Momma Loves Baby\" during a 2010 episode called \"Baby\".\n\nIn 2011, Knowles, along with Alejandra Ramos Munoz and [[Zooey Deschanel]], were announced as the new faces of [[Rimmel|Rimmel London]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.rimmellondon.com/us/en/ourfaces/ourmodels/solange-knowles |title=Solange Knowles |publisher=Rimmel London |accessdate=November 25, 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111128131449/http://www.rimmellondon.com/us/en/ourfaces/ourmodels/solange-knowles |archivedate=November 28, 2011  }}</ref>\n\nIn February 2012, Knowles became Vogue.com's \"Today I'm Wearing\" guest blogger, sharing a photograph of her outfits daily for a month.\n\nIn 2016 Knowles became [[Michael Kors]]' new face for his fashion works.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.google.it/search?ie=UTF-8&source=android-browser&q=michael/kors%20solange&gfe_rd=cr&ei=RrXFWMXaJ4zA8getjYGgAQ#gfe_rd=cr|title=michael/kors solange \u2013 Google Search|website=www.google.it|language=en|access-date=March 12, 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn 2017, Knowles became the face of a new [[Calvin Klein]] campaign.<ref>{{cite web |url= https://fashionista.com/2017/11/solange-calvin-klein-campaign |title= Solange Basically Casts Her Own Calvin Klein Campaign|publisher=}}</ref>\n\nIn 2018, Knowles received the artist of the year award from the Harvard Foundation.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://news.harvard.edu/gazette/story/2018/03/harvard-foundation-honors-solange-as-artist-of-the-year/|title=Solange visits as Harvard Foundation's artist of year|date=March 5, 2018|publisher=|accessdate=May 4, 2018}}</ref> \nShe became the face of [[Mercedes-Benz]]'s new campaign ''#WEWONDER''<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.essentialhommemag.com/mercedes-benz-presents-the-wewonder-campaign-with-solange/|title=MERCEDES-BENZ WITH SOLANGE|date=February 12, 2018|publisher=essentialhommemag.com|accessdate=August 9, 2018}}</ref> and [[Helmut Lang (fashion brand)|Helmut Lang]] fashion campaign.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.vogue.com/article/kanye-west-solange-helmut-lang-photos|title=Kanye West, Solange, and More Helmut Lang Collectors Star in the Label's New Project|date=January 4, 2018|publisher=vogue.com|accessdate=August 9, 2018}}</ref>\nShe has started a collaboration for interior design with [[IKEA]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/2018/jul/06/solange-collaboration-with-ikea|title=Swede dreams: what to expect from Solange's Saint Heron collaboration with Ikea|date=July 6, 2018|work=theguardian.com|accessdate=August 9, 2018}}</ref>\n\n===House of Der\u00e9on===\nKnowles and sister Beyonc\u00e9 modeled for their family's clothing line, [[House of Der\u00e9on]], named after their grandmother, Agn\u00e9z Der\u00e9on. She also helped launch Der\u00e9on, a junior apparel collection and a sister line to House of Der\u00e9on.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.ctv.ca/servlet/ArticleNews/story/CTVNews/20070816/Beyonce_Canada_070816/20070816?hub=CanadaAM|title=Beyonc\u00e9 launches her clothing line in Toronto|date=August 16, 2007|publisher=[[CTV News]]|accessdate=April 5, 2008}}</ref> Both sisters modeled for Der\u00e9on, and were featured in most of Der\u00e9on's marketing campaigns. Together they were featured in a \"[[Got Milk?]]\" campaign ad, wearing House of Der\u00e9on.\n\n==Personal life==\n\nKnowles married Daniel Smith on February 27, 2004 (a day after Alison Hinds February 26th) when she was 17 and he was 19.<ref name=\"EdwardsFlying\" /><ref>[http://www.people.com/people/archive/article/0,,20149623,00.html \"Crazy in Love\"]. ''People''. March 22, 2004.</ref> On October 18, 2004, Knowles gave birth to their son, Daniel Julez J. Smith Jr.<ref>{{cite web|last=Grossman|first=Wendy|author2=Peterson, Todd |date=October 26, 2004|title=Solange Knowles Gives Birth to a Boy|work=[[People (magazine)|People]]|publisher=[[Time Inc.|Time]]|url=http://www.people.com/people/article/0,,734570,00.html|accessdate=December 6, 2008}}</ref> Knowles calls her son the greatest unplanned blessing, but has partly expressed regret that she bore a child at an early age. A song she wrote for her baby, \"6 O'Clock Blues\", was included on ''Sol-Angel and the Hadley St. Dreams''.<ref name=\"S2SSolMMD\">{{cite web|url=http://www.s2smagazine.com/content/content.asp?issueid=200805&listid=03|title=Beyonc\u00e9's little sister Solange manages motherhood, music and a divorce|date=May 2008|work=[[Sister 2 Sister]]|accessdate=December 11, 2008 |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20080805015953/http://www.s2smagazine.com/content/content.asp?issueid=200805&listid=03 |archivedate = August 5, 2008}}</ref> After Julez's birth, the family moved to [[Moscow, Idaho]], where Knowles' husband continued studying in college.<ref name=\"KennedyChannels\" /> In October 2007, Knowles confirmed that she and Smith had divorced in an interview with ''[[Essence (magazine)|Essence]]'' magazine.<ref name=\"EdwardsFlying\" /> After the divorce, Knowles and her son moved to Los Angeles.<ref name=\"BarkerDecided\" /> In August 2013, Knowles announced that she and her son were moving to [[New Orleans]], Louisiana.\n\nOn May 12, 2014, [[TMZ]] released security video footage of Knowles physically assaulting brother-in-law, [[Jay-Z]] and being restrained by a security guard in an elevator at [[The Standard, High Line]], in Manhattan, following the 2014 [[Met Gala]]. Jay-Z remained passive and did not retaliate while her sister Beyonc\u00e9, who was also present, did not react to either party throughout the altercation.<ref name=\"tmz 20140512\">{{cite web|url=http://www.tmz.com/2014/05/12/jay-z-solange-fight-elevator-video-beyonce-met-gala/ |title=Jay Z Attacked By Solange Knowles \u2013 Beyonce's Sister's Physical Attack |publisher=TMZ.com |accessdate=May 14, 2014}}</ref> The footage and story went [[Viral video|viral]], but the reason for the altercation remains unknown.<ref>\n*{{cite web|url=http://globalnews.ca/news/1326108/watch-beyonces-sister-solange-attacks-jay-z-in-elevator/|title=Beyonce's sister Solange attacks Jay Z in elevator|work=Global News|first=John|last=Kennedy|date=May 12, 2014|accessdate=May 12, 2014}}\n*{{cite web|url=http://www.nme.com/news/solange/77262|title=Beyonce's sister Solange allegedly filmed attacking Jay Z in lift \u2013 watch|work=[[NME]]|date=May 12, 2014|accessdate=May 12, 2014}}\n*{{cite news|url=http://www.nydailynews.com/entertainment/gossip/solange-knowles-kicks-punches-claws-jay-z-met-gala-after-party-article-1.1789023 |title=Solange Knowles kicks, punches, claws Jay Z in elevator video at Met Gala after-party |newspaper=NY Daily News |accessdate=May 14, 2014}}</ref>\nMatthew Knowles, however, has hinted that the incident may have been faked for attention, saying: \"So you sometimes have to ignite that tour. It's called a Jedi mind trick. The Jedi mind trick fools you a lot...all I know is the Jedi mind trick. Everyone's talking about it. Ticket sales went up. Solange's album sales went up 200%!\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.designntrend.com/articles/18596/20140828/matthew-knowles-hints-jay-z-beyonce-faked-solange-gate-elevator.htm|title=Matthew Knowles Hints That Jay Z And Beyonce Fake'd The 'Solange Gate' Elevator Incident To Sale 'On The Run' Tour Tickets|last=Design&Trend|date=August 28, 2014|accessdate=May 23, 2017|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170326222623/http://www.designntrend.com/articles/18596/20140828/matthew-knowles-hints-jay-z-beyonce-faked-solange-gate-elevator.htm|archivedate=March 26, 2017}}</ref> The cause is rumored to be Jay-Z's infidelity, which the couple would address on their respective albums ''[[Lemonade (Beyonc\u00e9 album)|Lemonade]]'', ''[[4:44 (album)|4:44]]'', and their joint album ''[[Everything Is Love]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bustle.com/articles/158174-how-beyonces-lemonade-changes-the-way-we-look-at-the-2014-met-gala-elevator-incident|title=How Beyonce's 'Lemonade' Changes The Way We Look at the 2014 Met Gala Elevator Incident|first=Nicole|last=Pomarico|publisher=|accessdate=May 23, 2017}}</ref>\n\nOn November 16, 2014, Knowles married music video director Alan Ferguson at the [[Marigny Opera House]] in New Orleans, Louisiana.<ref name=\"people\" /><ref>{{cite news|last1=Ethan|first1=Sacks|title=Solange Knowles marries longtime boyfriend Alan Ferguson in New Orleans wedding|url=http://www.nydailynews.com/entertainment/gossip/solange-knowles-set-marry-longtime-boyfriend-article-1.2012891|newspaper=New York Daily News|accessdate=November 17, 2014}}</ref> On November 1, 2019, Knowles revealed on her Instagram account that she and Ferguson had separated earlier that year.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.vibe.com/2019/11/solange-separates-from-alan-ferguson|title=Solange Knowles Posts Optimistic Message In Midst Of Separation From Alan Ferguson|work=Vibe|language=en|access-date=December 10, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://madamenoire.com/1110766/solange-confirms-her-divorce-after-months-of-speculation-early-this-year-we-separated-and-parted-ways/|title=Solange Confirms Her Separation From Alan Ferguson After Months Of Speculation: \"Early This Year We Separated And Parted Ways\"|last=Kelly|first=Keyaira|date=November 1, 2019|website=MadameNoire|access-date=November 1, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Discography==\n{{main|Solange Knowles discography}}\n* ''[[Solo Star]]'' (2002)\n* ''[[Sol-Angel and the Hadley St. Dreams]]'' (2008)\n* ''[[A Seat at the Table]]'' (2016)\n* ''[[When I Get Home (album)|When I Get Home]]'' (2019)\n\n==Tours==\n'''Headlining'''\n*Solo Star Tour (2003)\n*The Art of Love Tour (2008)\n*Solange Presents Sol-Angel and the Hadley St. Dreams Tour (2008)\n*[[True EP|True Promo Tour]] (2012)\n*Orion's Rise (2017)\n'''Supporting'''\n*[[Simply Deeper Tour]] (2003)\n*[[The Justified World Tour]] (2003-2004)\n\n==Filmography==\n===Film===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|- style=\"background:#ccc; text-align:center;\"\n!Year\n!Title\n!Role\n!Notes\n|-\n| 2004 || ''[[Johnson Family Vacation]]'' || Nikki Johnson ||\n|-\n| 2006 || ''[[Bring It On: All or Nothing]]'' || Camille || Credited as Solange Knowles-Smith\n|-\n| 2019 || ''[[Homecoming (2019 film)| Homecoming]]'' || Herself || Cameo\n|}\n\n===Television===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|- style=\"background:#ccc; text-align:center;\"\n!Year\n!Title\n!Role\n!Notes\n|-\n| 2001 || ''[[Intimate Portrait]]'' || Herself || rowspan=\"3\"|1 episode\n|-\n|rowspan=3| 2002 || ''[[The Proud Family]]'' || Chanel\n|-\n| ''[[Taina (TV series)|Taina]]'' || Rachel\n|-\n| ''[[Taff (TV series)|Taff]]'' ||rowspan=5|Herself || 2 episodes\n|-\n|rowspan=4 | 2003 || ''[[Soul Train]]'' || 1 episode\n|-\n| ''[[American Music Awards of 2003 (January)|The 30th Annual American Music Awards]]''\n| Award show\n|-\n| ''[[The Today Show]]'' || rowspan=\"8\"| 1 episode\n|-\n| ''[[The Brothers Garcia]]''\n|-\n| 2004 || ''[[One on One (TV series)|One on One]]'' || Charlotte\n|-\n| 2005 || ''[[Listen Up! (TV series)|Listen Up!]]'' || Erika\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\"|2008 || ''[[Ghost Whisperer]]'' || Singer\n|-\n|'' [[Lincoln Heights (TV series)|Lincoln Heights]]'' || rowspan=\"3\"|Herself\n|-\n| 2010 || ''[[Yo Gabba Gabba!]]''\n|-\n| 2018 || ''[[Random Acts of Flyness]]''\n|}\n\n==Honors and awards==\n{{Main|List of awards and nominations received by Solange Knowles}}\nAt the [[59th Annual Grammy Awards]] (2017), Knowles won her first [[Grammy Award]], for [[Best R&B Performance]] for her song \"[[Cranes in the Sky]]\", the lead and only single from her debut studio album ''A Seat at the Table'' (2016), which was Knowles' first Grammy Award nomination. Knowles has also won a [[BET Award]], a [[Soul Train Music Award]], a [[Webby Award]], and more. In 2017, she also won [[Glamour Awards|''Glamour'' Award]] for Woman of the Year, and became the first winner of [[Billboard Women in Music|''Billboard'' Women in Music Impact Award]].\n\n== See also ==\n* {{Books-inline|Solange Knowles}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons}}\n* {{Official website|www.solangemusic.com}}\n* {{IMDb name|1090271}}\n\n{{Solange Knowles}}\n{{Beyonc\u00e9}}\n{{Roc Nation}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Knowles, Solange}}\n[[Category:Solange Knowles| ]]\n[[Category:1986 births]]\n[[Category:21st-century American women singers]]\n[[Category:Actresses from Houston]]\n[[Category:African-American female singers]]\n[[Category:African-American actresses]]\n[[Category:African-American businesspeople]]\n[[Category:African-American choreographers]]\n[[Category:American choreographers]]\n[[Category:African-American fashion designers]]\n[[Category:American fashion designers]]\n[[Category:African-American female dancers]]\n[[Category:African-American female models]]\n[[Category:American female models]]\n[[Category:African-American female singer-songwriters]]\n[[Category:African-American singer-songwriters]]\n[[Category:American female singer-songwriters]]\n[[Category:African-American record producers]]\n[[Category:American bloggers]]\n[[Category:American businesspeople in retailing]]\n[[Category:American contemporary R&B singers]]\n[[Category:American cosmetics businesspeople]]\n[[Category:American fashion businesspeople]]\n[[Category:American female dancers]]\n[[Category:American film actresses]]\n[[Category:American funk singers]]\n[[Category:American hip hop record producers]]\n[[Category:American hip hop singers]]\n[[Category:American music video directors]]\n[[Category:American people of Creole descent]]\n[[Category:American people who self-identify as being of Native American descent]]\n[[Category:American rhythm and blues singer-songwriters]]\n[[Category:American soul singers]]\n[[Category:American toy industry businesspeople]]\n[[Category:American women in business]]\n[[Category:Beyonc\u00e9]]\n[[Category:Businesspeople from Texas]]\n[[Category:Columbia Records artists]]\n[[Category:Destiny's Child]]\n[[Category:Geffen Records artists]]\n[[Category:Interscope Records artists]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Music video codirectors]]\n[[Category:Musicians from Houston]]\n[[Category:Neo soul singers]]\n[[Category:Roc Nation artists|Solange Knowles]]\n[[Category:Singers from Texas]]\n[[Category:Songwriters from Texas]]\n[[Category:Sony BMG artists]]\n[[Category:American female hip hop musicians]]\n[[Category:Record producers from Texas]]\n[[Category:Record producers from Louisiana]]\n[[Category:American women bloggers]]\n[[Category:21st-century American singers]]\n[[Category:American women record producers]]\n[[Category:Women hip hop record producers]]\n[[Category:American women in electronic music]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|American performance artist and musician}}\n{{good article}}{{Use mdy dates|date=March 2020}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name               = Solange\n| image              = Solange (220707).jpg\n| caption            = Knowles on stage in [[Oslo]] in 2017\n| birth_name         = Solange Piaget Knowles\n| birth_date         = {{Birth date and age|1986|6|24}}<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2012/06/22/solange-knowles-birthday-_n_1619787.html|title=Solange' Birthday: As Star Turns 26, A Look At Fabulous Celebrity Sisters (PHOTOS)|work=The Huffington Post|date=June 24, 2012}}</ref>\n| birth_place        = [[Houston]], [[Texas]], U.S.<!--As per WP:LINKDIRECT and Template:infobox person, birth/death place indicates city, state, then country. No need to spell out \"United States; 'U.S.' is fine.-->\n| other_names        = Solange Knowles-Smith<!--Had one credit as Solange Knowles-Smith. Not necessary to list Solange Knowles-Ferguson (which is not a name that Solange is professionally or legally known by. See: Template:Infobox person. -->\n| occupation         = {{flatlist|\n*Singer-songwriter\n*performance artist\n*record producer\n*actress}}\n| years_active       = 2001\u2013present\n| net_worth          =\n| spouse             = {{ubl|{{marriage|Daniel Smith|2004|2007|end=div}}|{{marriage|[[Alan Ferguson (director)|Alan Ferguson]]|2014|2019|end=sep.}}}}\n| children           = 1\n| parents            = {{ubl|[[Mathew Knowles]]|[[Tina Knowles]]}}\n| relatives          = [[Beyonc\u00e9]] (sister)\n| module             = {{Infobox musical artist\n| embed = yes\n| background         = solo_singer\n| genre              = {{hlist|[[Contemporary R&B|R&B]]|[[pop music|pop]]|[[hip hop music|hip hop]]|[[funk]]|[[soul music|soul]]}}\n| instrument         = {{hlist|Vocals|keyboards}}\n| label              = {{hlist|[[Mathew Knowles|Music World]]|[[Columbia Records|Columbia]]|{{nowrap|[[Interscope Geffen A&M]]}}|[[Terrible Records|Terrible]]|[[Saint Records|Saint]]}}\n| associated_acts    = {{hlist|[[Destiny's Child]]|[[Kindness (musician)|Adam Banbridge]]|[[Chromeo]]|[[Dev Hynes]]|[[Kelela]]|John Carroll Kirby|[[David Longstreth]]|[[Master P]]|[[Lil Wayne]]|\n[[Janelle Mon\u00e1e]]|[[Panda Bear (musician)|Panda Bear]]|[[Raphael Saadiq]]|[[Sampha]]|[[Standing on the Corner (band)|Standing on the Corner]]|[[Tyler, the Creator]]|[[Pharrell Williams]]|[[Patrick Wimberly]]}}\n}}\n| website            = {{URL|www.solangemusic.com}}\n}}\n\n'''Solange Piaget Knowles''' ({{IPAc-en|s|o\u028a|\u02c8|l|\u0251\u02d0|n|\u0292}}; born June 24, 1986),<ref name=biographychannel>{{cite web| url = http://www.biography.com/people/solange-21265489#awesm=~oE4Tpn1dO6DMDk | title= Solange Biography | publisher= [[The Biography Channel]] | accessdate= May 12, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.familysearch.org/ark:/61903/1:1:VDV5-1SC|title=Solange Piaget Knowles - Texas Birth Index|date=June 24, 1986|website=[[FamilySearch]]|access-date=August 19, 2019}}</ref> also known [[mononymous person|mononymously]] as '''Solange''', is an American singer, songwriter, record producer, performance artist<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.surfacemag.com/articles/solange-knowles-is-not-a-pop-star/|title=Solange Knowles Is Not a Pop Star|date=January 11, 2018|website=SURFACE|language=en-US|access-date=November 17, 2019}}</ref>, and actress. Expressing an interest in music from an early age, Knowles had several temporary stints as a backup dancer for [[Destiny's Child]], which featured her elder sister, [[Beyonc\u00e9]], among its members, before signing with her father [[Mathew Knowles]]'s [[Music World Entertainment]] label. At age 16, Knowles released her first studio album ''[[Solo Star]]'' (2002). Between 2005 and 2007, Knowles had several minor acting roles, including the direct-to-video ''[[Bring It On: All or Nothing]]'' (2006) and continued writing music for Beyonc\u00e9 and for former Destiny's Child group members [[Kelly Rowland]] and [[Michelle Williams (singer)|Michelle Williams]].\n\nIn 2007, Knowles began to record music again. Her second studio album ''[[Sol-Angel and the Hadley St. Dreams]]'' (2008) deviated from the pop-oriented music of her debut to the Motown Sound of the 1960s and 1970s. It peaked at number nine on [[Billboard 200|US ''Billboard'' 200]] and received positive reviews from critics. She followed this up with the [[1980s music|1980s]] pop and [[Contemporary R&B|R&B]]\u2013inspired extended play ''[[True (EP)|True]]'' (2012) on [[Terrible Records]] and her imprint [[Saint Records]]. Her third studio album, ''[[A Seat at the Table]]'' (2016) was released to widespread critical acclaim and became her first number-one album in the United States. The album's lead single, \"[[Cranes in the Sky]]\" won the Grammy for [[Grammy Award for Best R&B Performance|Best R&B Performance]]. Her fourth studio album, ''[[When I Get Home (album)|When I Get Home]]'', was released in 2019.\n\nKnowles was heavily influenced by [[Motown]] [[girl group]]s and says that her first passion is songwriting. She is frequently compared by the media to her sister, Beyonc\u00e9, but Solange insists they have different aspirations and are musically different. She has been ranked by ''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]'' as the 100th most successful dance artist of all-time,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.billboard.com/charts/greatest-top-dance-club-artists|title=Greatest of All Time Top Dance Club Artists : Page 1|publisher=|accessdate=May 23, 2017}}</ref> and in 2017 was honored with the \"Impact Award\" at [[Billboard Women in Music|''Billboard'' Women in Music]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/biz/articles/8053968/solange-honored-as-billboard-impact-award-winner-for-2017-women-in-music-ciara|title=Solange Honored As Billboard Impact Award Winner for 2017 Women In Music|work=billboard.com}}</ref> Her other ventures include an endorsement deal with [[Rimmel|Rimmel London]] and a line of hip-hop-oriented merchandise for young children. On November 16, 2014, Knowles married music video director [[Alan Ferguson (director)|Alan Ferguson]] in [[New Orleans]], Louisiana.<ref name=\"people\">{{cite magazine| url = http://www.people.com/article/solange-knowles-marries-alan-ferguson | title= Solange Knowles Marries Alan Ferguson| magazine= [[People Magazine]] | accessdate= November 16, 2014}}</ref>\n\n==Early life==\nKnowles was born in [[Houston]], Texas, to [[Mathew Knowles]] and [[Tina Knowles]]. Solange's older sister is singer and performer [[Beyonc\u00e9]]. Her father, originally from Alabama, is [[African American]], and her mother, originally from [[Texas]], is [[Louisiana Creole people|Creole]] (with Cameroonian, Native American, and French ancestry).<ref name=\"FOX\">{{cite news |url=http://www.foxnews.com/story/0,2933,204978,00.html?sPage=fnc/entertainment/beyonce |title=Beyonc\u00e9 Knowles' Biography |publisher=[[Fox News Channel]] |date=April 15, 2008 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111225022759/http://www.foxnews.com/story/0,2933,204978,00.html?sPage=fnc%2Fentertainment%2Fbeyonce |archivedate=December 25, 2011 |url-status=dead  |access-date=July 28, 2019 }}</ref><ref name=smol1>{{cite news|last=Smolenyak|first=Megan|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/megan-smolenyak-smolenyak/a-peek-into-blue-ivy-cart_b_1200346.html |title=A Peek into Blue Ivy Carter's Past |work=The Huffington Post|date=January 12, 2012 |accessdate=January 30, 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|url=https://archive.org/details/impoliteconversa0000dani |url-access=registration |quote=beyonce native american african french l'oreal. |title=Impolite Conversations: On Race, Politics, Sex, Money, and Religion |publisher=Simon and Schuster |author1=Daniels, Cora |author2=Jackson, John L. |page=[https://archive.org/details/impoliteconversa0000dani/page/198 198] |year= 2014 |isbn=9781476739113 |accessdate=June 10, 2015}}</ref> Her maternal grandparents are Lumis Beyinc\u00e9 and [[Agn\u00e9z Der\u00e9on]], (a [[sewing|seamstress]]). She is also a descendant of [[Acadia]]n leader [[Joseph Broussard]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/megan-smolenyak-smolenyak/a-peek-into-blue-ivy-cart_b_1200346.html |title=A Peek into Blue Ivy Carter's Past |first= |last= |work=[[The Huffington Post]] |publisher=[[AOL]] |date=January 12, 2012 |accessdate=January 14, 2012}}</ref> As a child, Knowles studied dance and theater. At the age of five, she made her singing debut at an amusement park. She began writing songs at the age of nine.<ref name=\"CosmoQ&A\">{{cite web|url=http://www.cosmogirl.com/blog/solange-knowles-qa|title=Solange Knowles Q&A|date=August 25, 2008|work=[[Cosmo Girl]]|accessdate=December 10, 2008|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090810190126/http://www.cosmogirl.com/blog/solange-knowles-qa|archivedate=August 10, 2009}}</ref> At 13, she decided to pursue recording, but her parents initially advised her to wait. At the age of 15 Knowles replaced a departed dancer and performed with her sister's group [[Destiny's Child]] on tour.{{cn|date=April 2020}} During the group's opening stint for American pop singer [[Christina Aguilera]]'s tour, Knowles temporarily replaced Destiny's Child member [[Kelly Rowland]] after she broke her toes backstage during a costume change.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1428039/20001009/destinys_child.jhtml|title=Destiny's Child Has Tough Backstage Break|last=Manning|first=Kara|date=October 9, 2000|publisher=MTV|accessdate=November 4, 2008}}</ref>\n\n==Career==\n\n===2001\u20132003: Early career and ''Solo Star''===\nManaged by her father Mathew, Knowles first ventured into the music business in 2001 as the lead singer, backed by Destiny's Child, on the title theme song for the animated television series ''[[The Proud Family]]''.<ref name=\"rs080602\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.teenvogue.com/story/solange-knowles-the-proud-family-theme-song|title=Solange Knowles Sang 'The Proud Family' Theme Song Onstage Because Nostalgia Is REAL|first=Cond\u00e9|last=Nast|website=Teen Vogue|accessdate=February 23, 2019}}</ref> She also was a featured performer on \"Hey Goldmember\" for the soundtrack to the 2002 film ''[[Austin Powers in Goldmember]]'',<ref name=\"rs080602\"/> as well as a backup singer on the track \"Little Drummer Boy\" on Destiny's Child's 2001 holiday album ''[[8 Days of Christmas]]''.<ref name=\"MossNo\">{{cite news|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1452941/20020315/knowles_solange.jhtml|title=Solange, Beyonc\u00e9's Lil' Sis, Says She's No Destiny's Child|last=Moss|first=Corey|date=March 18, 2002|publisher=MTV|accessdate=November 4, 2008}}</ref> In 2002, she was featured on [[Lil Romeo]]'s second studio album ''[[Game Time]]'', singing portions of [[Luther Vandross]]-penned \"So Amazing\" on the single \"True Love\", and on Kelly Rowland's debut solo album ''[[Simply Deep]]'', for which she also wrote the title track, \"Beyond Imagination\" and \"Obsession\". In 2001 she appeared as [[Bow Wow (rapper)|Lil' Bow Wow's]] date in the music video for his single \"[[Puppy Love (Bow Wow song)|Puppy Love]]\".<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1457156/20020822/rowland_kelly.jhtml|title=Kelly Rowland Moves Into 'Leave It To Beaver' House|last=Corey|first=Moss|date=August 23, 2002|publisher=MTV|accessdate=November 4, 2008}}</ref> She also made an appearance on ''[[The Master of Disguise]]'' soundtrack and made cameos in [[Play (Swedish band)|Play]]'s video for \"M.A.S.T.E.R. (Part II)\" featuring [[Lil' Fizz]].\n\nIn 2002, she lent her voice for the character Chanel, the cousin of the protagonist [[Penny Proud]], in the episode \"Behind Family Lines\" to the animated television series ''The Proud Family''.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1458489/20021104/ashanti.jhtml|title=Ashanti, Keys, Solange 'Proud' Participants in Animated Series|last=D'Angelo|first=Joe|date=November 4, 2002|publisher=MTV|accessdate=February 3, 2009}}</ref>\nIn June 2003, Mathew Knowles excitedly announced that he was considering adding Solange to Destiny's Child when the group reunited in 2004, thus turning them into a quartet for the first time since short-lived member [[Farrah Franklin]] left in 2000. Mathew Knowles said he was testing the reactions, and, judging by what he had heard, \"it seems like a good idea\".<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1473417/20030626/destinys_child.jhtml|title=Destiny's Child May Get A New Member Next Year|last=Moss|first=Corey|date=June 26, 2003|publisher=MTV|accessdate=November 4, 2008}}</ref> Later in August, however, Beyonc\u00e9 said it was only a rumor and Destiny's Child would remain a trio. Rowland added, \"She's a solo star,\" [[name-dropping]] Knowles' debut album.<ref name=\"MossTrio\">{{cite news|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1477173/20030825/destinys_child.jhtml|title=Destiny's Child To Remain A Trio, Says Beyonc\u00e9|last=Corey|first=Moss|date=August 25, 2003|publisher=MTV|accessdate=November 4, 2008}}</ref>\n\nAt the age of 14, Solange Knowles started working on her debut album ''[[Solo Star]]'',<ref name=\"RamaswamySoul\">{{cite web|url=http://scotlandonsunday.scotsman.com/entertainment/Solange-Knowles-interview--Soul.4650388.jp|title=Solange Knowles interview \u2013 Soul sister|last=Ramaswamy|first=Chitra|date=November 2, 2008|work=[[Scotland on Sunday]]|accessdate=November 3, 2008}}</ref> which involved American producers such as [[Jermaine Dupri]], [[The Neptunes]], [[Linda Perry]] and [[Timbaland]] among others. She then recorded the album under her father's [[Music World Entertainment]] label with [[Columbia Records]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nydailynews.com/entertainment/music-arts/solange-knowles-article-1.1790851|title=Who is Solange Knowles? Everything you need to know about Beyonce's little sister|work=New York Daily News|date=May 13, 2014|last=Pesce|first=Nicole Lyn}}</ref> The album is primarily uptempo [[Contemporary R&B|R&B]], although Knowles said there are pop, rock, [[reggae]] and [[Hip hop music|hip hop]] influences.<ref name=\"rs080602\">{{cite news|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/news/story/5933946/solange_knowles_has_star_power|title=Solange Knowles Has \"Star\" Power |last=Bliss|first=Karen|date=August 6, 2002|work=[[Rolling Stone]]|accessdate=January 31, 2009}}</ref><ref name=\"MossNo\"/> Knowles co-wrote and co-produced some of the 15 tracks in the album,<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1458534/20021105/knowles_solange.jhtml|title=Solange 'Feeling' It With Beyonc\u00e9, N.O.R.E., Others|last=Wiederhorn|first=Jon|date=November 6, 2002|publisher=MTV|accessdate=November 4, 2008}}</ref> including its [[lead single]], \"[[Feelin' You (Part II)]]\". The song failed to enter the [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]], but reached number three on both the [[Hot R&B/Hip-Hop Singles Sales]] and [[Dance/Electronic Singles Sales|Hot Dance Music/Maxi-Singles Sales]] chart.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.billboard.biz/bbbiz/charts/search/detailed_chart_display.jsp?g=s&cd=Jan-25-2003&f=Hot_R&B/Hip-Hop_Singles_Sales&model.chartId=3048275|title=Hot R&B/Hip-Hop Singles Sales|work=[[Billboard magazine|Billboard]]|publisher=[[Nielsen Business Media]]|date=January 25, 2003|accessdate=July 21, 2008}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Billboard \u2013 Maxi Single Sales|url=https://books.google.com/?id=0Q0EAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA25&lpg=PA25&dq=%22Hot+Dance+Music/Maxi-Singles+Sales+solange#v=onepage&q=solange&f=false|publisher=Nielsen Business Media, Inc.|accessdate=November 7, 2016|language=en|date=January 11, 2003}}</ref> ''Solo Star'' was released on January 21, 2003 in the United States, where it debuted at number 49 on the [[Billboard 200|''Billboard'' 200]] and reached number 23 on the [[Top R&B/Hip-Hop Albums]] chart.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.billboard.com/charts/2003-02-08/billboard-200 |title=The Billboard 200: Solo Star |date=February 2008 |work=Billboard |publisher=Nielsen Business Media |accessdate=November 4, 2008 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140101103147/http://www.billboard.com/charts/2003-02-08/billboard-200 |archivedate=January 1, 2014 }}</ref><ref name=\"ConcepcionTop\">{{cite web|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/news/1045367/solange-not-out-to-top-sister-beyonce-on-new-album|last=Concepcion|first=Mariel|date=May 16, 2008|title=Solange Not Out To Top Sister Beyonc\u00e9 On New Album|work=[[Billboard magazine|Billboard]]|publisher=Nielsen Business Media|accessdate=July 21, 2008}}</ref> ''Solo Star'' had a mixed critical reception: William Ruhlmann of [[AllMusic]] called it a \"state-of-the-art contemporary R&B album\", but deemed Knowles \"lost somewhere in the mix\".<ref>{{cite web|url={{Allmusic|class=album|id=r625601|pure_url=yes}}|title=Solo Star: Solange Knowles|last=Ruhlmann|first=William|website=AllMusic|accessdate=January 31, 2009}}</ref> By mid-2008, the album had sold 112,000 copies domestically according to [[Nielsen SoundScan]].<ref name=\"ConcepcionTop\"/>\n\n===2003\u20132008: Films and ''Sol-Angel and the Hadley St. Dreams''===\n[[File:Solange Knowles @ The Ruby Lounge, Manchester, (14 11 08) (3041189101).jpg|thumb|Knowles performing at the Ruby Lounge in [[Manchester]] in 2008]]\nIn 2004, she guest starred in the episode \"The Catch\" of the sitcom ''[[One on One (TV series)|One on One]]''.\nKnowles appeared as a teenager in the 2004 [[comedy film]] ''[[Johnson Family Vacation]]'', starring alongside American actors [[Cedric the Entertainer]], [[Vanessa L. Williams|Vanessa Williams]] and Bow Wow.<ref name=\"MossTrio\"/> She provided a song for its soundtrack\u2014\"[[Freedom (Solange Knowles song)|Freedom]]\", a collaboration with the Houston-based funk-jazz band [[Drop Trio]]. Although the reviews were generally negative, Knowles earned praise from ''[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]'' magazine: \"Solange Knowles is nearly as dazzling as big sister Beyonc\u00e9 and does little more than smile winningly in her first bigscreen outing.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.variety.com/review/VE1117923532.html?categoryid=31&cs=1|title=Johnson Family Vacation|last=Lowry|first=Brian|date=April 7, 2004|work=Variety|accessdate=February 3, 2009}}</ref>\nIn 2006, she starred as a cheerleading captain in the film ''[[Bring It On: All or Nothing]]'', the third installment of the ''Bring It On'' series, alongside American actress and singer [[Hayden Panettiere]]. What little critical reaction the low-budget, [[Direct-to-video|direct-to-DVD]] movie got was negative,<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/bring_it_on_all_or_nothing/ | title=Bring It On: All or Nothing (2006) | website=[[Rotten Tomatoes]] | accessdate=February 3, 2009}}</ref> and Knowles was described as an \"affordable young starlet\".<ref>{{cite news | url=http://efilmcritic.com/review.php?movie=14815&reviewer=392 | title=Bring It On: All or Nothing | author=Cornelius, David | publisher=Efilmcritic.com | date=August 10, 2006 | accessdate=February 3, 2009}}</ref> Knowles uses her full name for her acting, rather than just the first name she uses when singing; for ''Bring It On: All or Nothing'', she was billed as Solange Knowles-Smith,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://abcfamily.go.com/abcfamily/path/section_Movies+BringItOnAllOrNothing/page_Detail |title=Bring It On: All Or Nothing |publisher=[[ABC Family]] |accessdate=January 1, 2009 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080822211011/http://abcfamily.go.com/abcfamily/path/section_Movies%2BBringItOnAllOrNothing/page_Detail |archivedate=August 22, 2008 |url-status=dead }}</ref> reflecting her married state at the time.\n\nAfter the release of her debut album, Knowles started acting in films followed by a career break.<ref name=\"BreakingSolange\">{{cite web|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/blogs/breaking/2008/09/breaking-solange.php|title=Breaking: Solange|date=September 23, 2008|work=Rolling Stone|accessdate=January 31, 2009}}</ref> While she was married, her family moved to [[Idaho]], and, while staying there, resumed writing songs including the singles \"[[Get Me Bodied]]\" and \"[[Upgrade U]]\" from her sister's second solo album, ''[[B'Day (Beyonc\u00e9 album)|B'Day]]''.<ref name=\"BreakingSolange\"/><ref name=\"Co-Publishing Deal\">{{cite web|url=http://www.marketwire.com/mw/release.do?id=762009|date=August 20, 2007|title=Solange Knowles Signs a Worldwide Co-Publishing Deal With EMI Music Publishing}}</ref> Knowles earned the R&B and Hip-Hop Song accolade for \"Get Me Bodied\" at the 2008 [[ASCAP Awards]].<ref name=\"ascap\">{{cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/pressRelease/idUS28916+23-Jul-2008+PRN20080723|title=Solange Knowles Enjoys the #1 Spot Again|date=July 22, 2008|publisher=[[PR Newswire]]|agency=[[Reuters]]|accessdate=November 5, 2008|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090109183332/http://www.reuters.com/article/pressRelease/idUS28916+23-Jul-2008+PRN20080723|archivedate=January 9, 2009}}</ref> She had also written songs for Destiny's Child, and members Kelly Rowland and [[Michelle Williams (singer)|Michelle Williams]].{{cn|date=April 2020}} In 2004, while pregnant with her son Daniel, she made a [[cameo appearance]] in Destiny's Child's music video for \"[[Soldier (Destiny's Child song)|Soldier]]\".<ref>{{cite video|people=[[Ray Kay|Kay, Ray]] (Director)|date=2005|title=Soldier|medium=Music video|publisher=[[Sony BMG]]|location=United States}}</ref>\n\nAfter the divorce, Knowles returned to Houston to begin working on her second album. Knowles renewed her management, signing a record deal with [[Geffen Records|Geffen]] and a publishing deal with [[EMI]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/news/1047083/solange-knowles-inks-with-geffen|title=Solange Knowles Inks With Geffen|last=Crosley|first=Hillary|date=December 11, 2007|work=Billboard|publisher=Nielsen Business Media|accessdate=November 6, 2008}}</ref><ref name=\"EdwardsFlying\">{{cite web|url=http://www.essence.com/2007/10/05/solange-knowles-flying-solo/|title=Solange Knowles Flying Solo|last=Edwards|first=Jeanine|work=[[Essence (magazine)|Essence]]|accessdate=November 3, 2008}}</ref> Knowles finished working on her second studio album in 2008 and titled the project ''[[Sol-Angel and the Hadley St. Dreams]]''. It includes production by [[CeeLo Green]], [[Soulshock & Karlin]] and [[Mark Ronson]] as well as an appearance by [[Bilal (musician)|Bilal]]. A collection of 1960s and 1970s influenced songs,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://clutchmagonline.com/lifeculture/feature/destinys-child-solange-comes-of-age/|title=Destiny's Child: Solange Comes of Age|last=Arthur|first=Sylvia|date=July 1, 2008|work=Clutch|accessdate=November 6, 2008|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101225004726/http://clutchmagonline.com/lifeculture/feature/destinys-child-solange-comes-of-age/|archive-date=December 25, 2010|url-status=dead}}</ref> it is seen as a departure from her pop-oriented debut,<ref name=\"BarkerDecided\">{{cite web|url=http://www.teenhollywood.com/printerversion.asp?r=175424 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180919165210/http://www.teenhollywood.com/printerversion.asp?r=175424 |url-status=dead |archive-date=September 19, 2018 |title=Solange Knowles: She's \"Decided\"! |last=Barker |first=Lynn |date=May 14, 2008 |publisher=Teen Hollywood |accessdate=February 1, 2009 }}</ref><ref name=\"KennedyChannels\">{{cite news|url=http://www.fox59.com/pages/landing_american_dad/?Solange-Knowles-little-sister-to-Beyonce=1&blockID=47623&feedID=13|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180919165204/https://fox59.com/pages/landing_american_dad/?Solange-Knowles-little-sister-to-Beyonce=1&blockID=47623&feedID=13|url-status=dead|archive-date=September 19, 2018|title=Solange Knowles, little sister to Beyonce, channels her inner soul with her sophomore CD|last=Kennedy|first=Mark|date=September 3, 2008|publisher=[[WXIN (TV)|WXIN-TV]]|accessdate=February 1, 2009}}</ref> with what ''Billboard'' magazine called \"more of a modern twist on hip-hop and R&B flecked with tinges of blues and jazz\".<ref name=\"ConcepcionTop\"/> The album was released on August 26, 2008 in the United States. By December 2008, the album had sold over 114,000 copies according to Nielsen SoundScan.<ref name=\"CaulfieldSolange\">{{cite web|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/ask-billboard/266071/ask-billboard-perez-hilton-solange-grace-jones |title=Ask Billboard: Sol-Angel doesn't get wings |last=Caulfield |first=Keith |work=Billboard |publisher=Nielsen Business Media |accessdate=January 31, 2009 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130924162657/http://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/ask-billboard/266071/ask-billboard-perez-hilton-solange-grace-jones |archivedate=September 24, 2013 }}</ref> The album was positively received by critics,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.metacritic.com/music/artists/solange/solangelandthehadleystdreams|title=''Sol-Angel and the Hadley St. Dreams'' by Solange|website=[[Metacritic]]|accessdate=August 16, 2008}}</ref> some of whom considered it far better than her debut.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/2008/nov/10/popandrock|title=Solange|last=Gittins|first=Ian|date=November 10, 2008|work=[[The Guardian]]|accessdate=January 31, 2009 | location=London}}</ref> The album's lead single, \"[[I Decided (song)|I Decided]]\", was released in April 2008, and reached the top of the ''Billboard'' [[Dance Club Songs|Hot Dance Club Play]] chart;<ref name=\"CaulfieldSolange\"/> ''[[Rolling Stone]]'' magazine labelled it her breakthrough single.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/rockdaily/index.php/2008/09/24/on-the-breaking-blog-solange/ |title=On the Breaking Blog: Solange |date=September 24, 2008 |work=[[Rolling Stone]] |accessdate=January 31, 2009 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080927171441/http://www.rollingstone.com/rockdaily/index.php/2008/09/24/on-the-breaking-blog-solange/ |archivedate=September 27, 2008 }}</ref> In support of the album, Knowles began the Solange Presents Sol-Angel and the Hadley St. Dreams Tour in Britain in November 2008.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.polydor.co.uk/topstories.php?story=50|title=Solange Announces UK Dates|date=October 3, 2008|publisher=[[Polydor Records]]|accessdate=November 9, 2008|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://archive.today/20120910201857/http://www.polydor.co.uk/topstories.php?story=50|archivedate=September 10, 2012}}</ref> Knowles also co-wrote \"Scared of Lonely\" and \n\"[[Why Don't You Love Me (Beyonc\u00e9 song)|Why Don't You Love Me]]\" for her sister's third studio album ''[[I Am... Sasha Fierce]]''.\n\nKnowles announced, via her blog HadleyStreetJournal.com, that she would be releasing a series of [[mixtape]]s to coincide with the album. The first mixtape, ''I Can't Get Clearance...'', includes the leaked track \"[[Fuck the Industry|Fuck the Industry (Signed Sincerely)]]\". On this record, Knowles expressed her views on the current state of the music industry. The lyrics to the song name check some major artists such as [[Mary J. Blige]], [[Ashanti (entertainer)|Ashanti]], [[Keyshia Cole]], and Beyonc\u00e9, although she made a point of stating that it does not have \"a negative light to any of [them]\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.solangel.typepad.com/|title=Awwwwwhhhh Dammmmnnn........|date=August 1, 2008|publisher=Solangel.typepad.com|accessdate=November 3, 2008}}</ref> The mixtape was never released, but Solange released \"Fuck the Industry (Signed Sincerely)\" as a single in 2010.\n\n===2008\u20132014: ''True'' EP and Saint Records===\n[[File:Solange Knowles SXSW 2009.jpg|thumb|Knowles performing at [[SXSW]] 2009]]\nIn an interview with MTV in 2009, Knowles revealed that she was determining the type of sound for the follow-up to ''Sol-Angel and the Hadley St. Dreams''.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1609288/20090415/knowles_solange.jhtml|title=Will New Solange Album Have A Duet With Sister Beyonc\u00e9?|last=Vena|first=Jocelyn|date=April 15, 2009|publisher=MTV|accessdate=April 17, 2009}}</ref> Knowles also parted ways with the [[Interscope-Geffen-A&M]] record label group. She would now release her third studio album independently.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rap-up.com/2009/10/31/solange-exits-interscope-records|accessdate=December 2, 2009|title=Solange Exits Interscope Records|date=October 31, 2009|publisher=Rap-Up.com}}</ref> Early in 2010, Knowles traveled to Australia to work with Australian rock band, [[Midnight Juggernauts]] on her third studio album.{{citation needed|date=January 2018}} Knowles had planned to release the album in summer as revealed on her official Twitter account in 2009.<ref>[http://blog.singersroom.com/celebs/index.php/2009/10/09/solange-at-work-on-2010-album/ Solange At Work on 2010 Album]{{webarchive|url=https://archive.today/20120714025506/http://blog.singersroom.com/celebs/index.php/2009/10/09/solange-at-work-on-2010-album/ |date=July 14, 2012 }} Singersroom Celebs \u2013 Retrieved June 16, 2010</ref> She also revealed on her Twitter account that she rented a house in [[Santa Barbara, California]] to get into a certain state of mind while writing and making music.<ref>[http://theybf.com/2010/05/06/solange-readies-next-albumrihannas-te-amo-cover Solange Readies Next Album] The Young, Black & Fabulous \u2013 Retrieved June 16, 2010</ref> On May 7, 2010, Knowles made a guest appearance on the popular children show, ''[[Yo Gabba Gabba!]]'' for a \"Mothers Day Special\" where she performed an original song called \"Momma Loves Baby\".<ref>[http://www.bvnewswire.com/2010/04/29/solange-knowles-yo-gabba-gabba-mothers-day/ Solange Knowles Does Yo Gabba Gabba' for Mothers Day] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100604102245/http://www.bvnewswire.com/2010/04/29/solange-knowles-yo-gabba-gabba-mothers-day |date=June 4, 2010 }} Entertainment News \u2013 Retrieved June 16, 2010</ref><ref>[http://hiphop.popcrunch.com/solange-knowles-yo-gabba-gabba-guest-appearance-may-7/ Solange Knowles \"Yo Gabba Gabba\" Guest Appearance May 7] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100712011206/http://hiphop.popcrunch.com/solange-knowles-yo-gabba-gabba-guest-appearance-may-7/ |date=July 12, 2010 }} Retrieved June 16, 2010</ref><ref>[http://www.monstersandcritics.com/smallscreen/news/article_1552088.php/Solange-Knowles-on-Yo-Gabba-Gabba-for-Mother-s-day-marathon-on-Nick Solange on Yo Gabba Gabba for Mothers Day] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100503094326/http://www.monstersandcritics.com/smallscreen/news/article_1552088.php/Solange-Knowles-on-Yo-Gabba-Gabba-for-Mother-s-day-marathon-on-Nick |date=May 3, 2010 }} Retrieved June 16, 2010</ref>\n\nIn an interview with ''[[Vibe (magazine)|Vibe]]'' on July 7, 2010, Knowles said she suffered \"a little bit of a [[Mental breakdown|breakdown]]\" while recording her new album: \"I literally gave up my sanity for a while to do this record. [...] We literally were waking up in the morning and just making music all day and all night. [...] It just started to wear on me in so many different ways. I started having these crazy [[panic attack]]s.\" Knowles explained how she made sacrifices \"mentally, emotionally and financially\", and continued, \"It's more than an album to me. It's a transitional time in my life.\" Regarding the musical direction of the album, she said the inspiration came from [[New wave music|new wave]] and stated, \"This is a dance record, but the lyrics can get pretty dark at times.\"<ref name=\"Murphy\"/>\nThe singer has also worked on songs with [[Chromeo]] and long-time collaborator [[Pharrell Williams]].\n\nIn September 2012, Solange released a teaser video for \"[[Losing You (Solange Knowles song)|Losing You]]\", which was announced as the lead single from her third studio album. This release marked Solange's first release as a signee of the independent label [[Terrible Records]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.solange-k.net/wordpress/2012/09/02/solange-shoots-video-for-losing-you-in-south-africa/|title=solange-k.net|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120905012829/http://www.solange-k.net/wordpress/2012/09/02/solange-shoots-video-for-losing-you-in-south-africa/|archivedate=September 5, 2012}}</ref> The video was shot in Cape Town, South Africa in early September 2012. Knowles revealed in an interview that her mother Tina Knowles had paid for Solange and her friends to fly out and record the video as her birthday gift. On October 24, 2012, Knowles held a listening party in New York City for her EP ''[[True (EP)|True]]'', released for digital download on iTunes November 27, 2012.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rap-up.com/2012/10/25/solange-previews-true-ep-at-new-york-listening-party/ |title=Solange Previews 'True' EP at New York Listening Party |publisher=Rap-Up.com |date=October 25, 2012 |accessdate=May 14, 2014}}</ref> The CD and vinyl was made available January 8, 2013. Following the EP's release, Solange appeared on the cover of ''[[The Fader]]'' magazine's 84th issue.<ref>{{cite web|title=Solange: Rise and Shine|url=http://www.thefader.com/2013/02/12/solange-rise-and-shine}}</ref>\n\nOn May 14, 2013, Knowles moved to Louisiana and announced that she had launched her own record label named Saint Records, which she will be using to release her third full-length album and future music projects distributed through [[Sony Music Entertainment|Sony]].<ref name=\"Solange Knowles Launches New Record Label, Releases Latest Track Featuring Kendrick Lamar\">{{cite news|last=Nessif|first=Bruna|title=Solange Knowles Launches New Record Label, Releases Latest Track Featuring Kendrick Lamar|url=http://uk.eonline.com/news/418855/solange-knowles-launches-new-record-label-releases-latest-track-featuring-kendrick-lamar|accessdate=May 14, 2013|newspaper=eonline.com|date=May 14, 2013}}</ref> Saint Records was established to focus on not-yet mainstream hip-hop and R&B artists. Solange also collaborated with [[The Lonely Island]] on the song \"Semicolon\" which was featured as part of YouTube's Comedy Week and is featured on The Lonely Island's album, ''[[The Wack Album]]''. On November 11, 2013, Knowles' record label released its first compilation album, ''[[Saint Heron]]''.\n\n===2014\u2013present: ''A Seat at the Table,'' ''When I Get Home,'' and performance art.===\n[[File:Solange - Coachella 2014 (12).jpg|thumb|left|Knowles performing at [[Coachella Valley Music and Arts Festival|Coachella]] in 2014]]\nOn May 15, 2015, Knowles performed \"Rise\" for the first time at an HBO-sponsored event, which was inspired by police killings in [[Ferguson, Missouri|Ferguson]] and [[Baltimore]] and the subsequent protests.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.idolator.com/7592955/solange-new-song-rise-ferguson-baltimore-protest|title=Solange Unveils New Song \"Rise,\" Inspired By Ferguson & Baltimore: Watch|work=Music News, Reviews, and Gossip on Idolator.com|date=May 15, 2015}}</ref> In July 2015, Knowles announced that her third studio album was nearly complete. On her thirtieth birthday, June 24, 2016, she stated that she had completed ''[[A Seat at the Table]]'' three days before her birthday, on June 21.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.fuse.tv/2016/06/solange-new-album-completed|title=Solange's New Album is Completed|date=June 24, 2016|work=[[Fuse.tv]]|accessdate=June 25, 2016}}</ref> The album was released on September 30, 2016, to widespread critical acclaim.<ref>Mary J. DiMeglio, [http://www.billboard.com/articles/news/7526464/solange-knowles-release-new-album-seat-at-table-listen \"Solange Drops New Album, 'A Seat at the Table': Listen,\"] ''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]'', September 30, 2016.</ref> It became her first number-one album in the United States. This made her and Beyonc\u00e9 the first sisters to have both had US number-one albums in a calendar year.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.etonline.com/music/199983_beyonce_and_solange_knowles_become_first_sisters_to_have_number_1_albums/ |title=Beyonce and Solange Knowles Become First Sisters to Land No. 1 Albums |publisher=Etonline.com |date= |accessdate=October 12, 2016}}</ref> On October 3, 2016, Knowles released two music videos from ''A Seat at the Table'': \"Don't Touch my Hair\" and \"Cranes in the Sky\", both co-directed by herself and husband, [[Alan Ferguson (director)|Alan Ferguson]].\n\nDuring the 2017 Roots Picnic Festival in Philadelphia, Pennsylvania, Knowles performed a rendition of the sing-along from ''The Proud Family'', the television series whose theme song she was featured on in 2001, and she participated at the [[Glastonbury Festival|2017 Glastonbury Festival]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.eonline.com/news/859111/solange-leads-the-proud-family-theme-song-sing-along-and-brings-us-back-to-2001 |title=Solange Leads The Proud Family Sing-Along and Kicks It to 2001|publisher=|date=June 5, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.glastonburyfestivals.co.uk/line-up/line-up-2017/|title=Glastonbury Festival - 2017|last=Digital|first=Pretty Good|website=Glastonbury Festival - June 21-25, 2017|language=en-US|access-date=January 7, 2019}}</ref> In December 2017, Solange directed the video of The Weekend by [[SZA (singer)]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/hip-hop/8078596/sza-ctrl-shares-new-solange-knowles-directed-video-for-the-weekend |title=Sza Ctrl Shares New Solange Directed Video For The Weekend|publisher=}}</ref>\n\nOn October 15, 2018, it was announced by Knowles that she would be releasing her fourth studio album in the Fall during an interview with [[New York Times Style Magazine]].<ref>{{cite web |last1=Monroe |first1=Jazz |title=Solange's New Album Coming This Fall |url=https://pitchfork.com/news/solanges-new-album-coming-this-fall/ |website=Pitch Fork |accessdate=October 15, 2018}}</ref> However, this did not come to fruition.\n\nOn January 3, 2019, the [[Coachella Valley Music and Arts Festival]] announced that Solange would co-headline the stage with [[Tame Impala]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.capitalfm.com/events/coachella/2019-line-up-dates-headliner-tickets/|title=Coachella 2019 \u2013 Line Up, Dates, Headliner And More\u2026 Ariana Grande, Childish Gambino Confirmed|website=Capital|language=en|access-date=January 7, 2019}}</ref> The Coachella performance was later canceled due to \u201cmajor production delays\u201d.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://pitchfork.com/news/solange-cancels-coachella-2019-set/|title=Solange Cancels Coachella 2019 Set|last=Nast|first=Cond\u00e9|website=Pitchfork|language=en|access-date=April 8, 2019}}</ref> On January 8, 2019, it was announced Solange would be performing at the [[Bonnaroo Music Festival]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://pitchfork.com/news/bonnaroo-2019-lineup-announced-childish-gambino-solange-phish-cardi-b-more/|title=Bonnaroo 2019 Lineup Announced: Childish Gambino, Solange, Phish, Cardi B, More|website=Pitchfork|language=en|access-date=February 7, 2019}}</ref> She was also confirmed to perform at the UK's [[Parklife (festival)|Parklife]] festival <ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.factmag.com/2019/01/30/cardi-b-solange-parklife-2019/|title=Cardi B, Solange and The Streets announced for Parklife Festival 2019|date=January 30, 2019|publisher=|accessdate=February 23, 2019}}</ref> and [[Lovebox Festival]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.highsnobiety.com/p/lovebox-festival-2019-lineup/|title=Lovebox 2019 Sets Solange, Chance the Rapper & BROCKHAMPTON|date=February 12, 2019|website=Highsnobiety|accessdate=February 23, 2019}}</ref>\n\nOn March 1, 2019, she released her fourth studio album, ''[[When I Get Home (album)|When I Get Home]]'', on all streaming platforms.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://pitchfork.com/news/solange-announces-new-album-when-i-get-home-out-tonight/|title=Solange Releases New Album When I Get Home: Listen|website=Pitchfork|language=en|access-date=March 1, 2019}}</ref> She previously teased the album by posting two video snippets on her Instagram and Twitter, and a personal web page on the African-American social networking site, [[BlackPlanet]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.elle.com/culture/a26575997/solange-black-planet-when-i-get-home-album-announcement/|title=Solange Teased Her New Album on the Social Network Black Planet, and It Means Everything|last=Hubbard|first=Shanita|date=February 28, 2019|website=ELLE|language=en-US|access-date=March 1, 2019}}</ref>\n\nOutside her work of being a singer-songwriter, Solange has also ventured into performance art. In an interview with Surface magazine, she said \"I'm not at all interested in entertainment. I\u2019m really interested in energy exchange between the viewer and the performer. One way to do that is to make an inclusive experience through style, through energy, through space.\u201d<ref name=\":0\" /> She has put on subsequent performance art pieces throughout the world, including Witness! at the [[Elbphilharmonie]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://pitchfork.com/news/solange-announces-witness-performance-piece/|title=Solange Announces \"Witness!\" Performance Piece|website=Pitchfork|language=en|access-date=November 17, 2019}}</ref>, and Bridge-s at the [[J. Paul Getty Museum|Getty Museum]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.latimes.com/entertainment-arts/story/2019-11-15/solange-performance-art-bridges-getty-museum|title=Solange brings her new performance art to the Getty this weekend. Here's a sneak peek|date=November 15, 2019|website=Los Angeles Times|language=en-US|access-date=November 17, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.getty.edu/visit/cal/events/solange.html|title=Bridge-s {{!}} Getty360 Calendar|website=The J. Paul Getty in Los Angeles|language=en|access-date=November 17, 2019}}</ref>.\n\n==Artistry==\n\n===Music and influences===\n{{Listen|pos = right\n |filename     = Solange Dancing in the Dark.ogg\n |title        = \"Dancing in the Dark\"\n |description  = The song features a 1970s [[funk]] sound and contains a thick horn sample from [[Heinz Kiessling]]'s 1960s recording \"Feeling Young\".<ref>ILIKEIT (August 31, 2008). [http://www.singersroom.com/reviews/artist-media-64.asp Music Review \u2013 Solange Knowles: Sol-Angel and the Hadley St. Dreams] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110929125456/http://www.singersroom.com/reviews/artist-media-64.asp |date=September 29, 2011 }}. Singersroom. Retrieved on July 5, 2011.</ref><ref>Godfrey, Sarah (September 13, 2008). [http://www.washingtoncitypaper.com/articles/36159/sloppy-seconds Sloppy Seconds: The Game and Solange have a hard time avoiding the shadow of bigger names]. ''[[Washington City Paper]]''. Retrieved on July 5, 2011.</ref>\n}}\n\nOn her debut album, Knowles had no control over which kinds of music to produce, because \"when you're 14, everyone else is older and more seasoned and you trust their decisions\".<ref name=\"RamaswamySoul\"/> Knowles was more concerned with pleasing her record label by submitting to their desires.<ref name=\"EdwardsFlying\"/>\n\nHer musical influences were better expressed on ''Sol-Angel and the Hadley St. Dreams'', when she considered herself mature and was able to write and produce songs as she wished, without worrying about the expectations of others.<ref name=\"RamaswamySoul\"/> Knowles' lyrics tackle relationships, world issues, and deceased friends,<ref name=\"EdwardsFlying\"/><ref name=\"S2SSolMMD\"/> with her second album focusing on events in her life, such as marriage, divorce, and parenthood.<ref name=\"EdwardsFlying\"/> The album touched upon a variety of genres including [[pop-soul]],<ref name=\"Kellman\">Kellman, Andy. [{{Allmusic|class=album|id=r1412903|pure_url=yes}} Review: ''Sol-Angel and the Hadley St. Dreams'']. [[AllMusic]]. Retrieved on July 22, 2009.</ref> [[psychedelic soul]],<ref>{{cite news|last=Wood|first=Mikael|date=August 28, 2008|url=http://www.latimes.com/entertainment/la-et-solange28-2008aug28,0,6574389.story|title=No little-sister act for Solange Knowles|newspaper=Los Angeles|accessdate=November 18, 2012}}</ref> [[electronica]],<ref name=\"Cinquemani\">Cinquemani, Sal. [http://www.slantmagazine.com/music/music_review.asp?ID=1476 Review: ''Sol-Angel and the Hadley St. Dreams''] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140201173951/http://www.slantmagazine.com/music/music_review.asp?ID=1476 |date=February 1, 2014 }}. [[Slant Magazine]]. Retrieved on July 22, 2009.</ref> and R&B.<ref name=\"Sullivan\">Sullivan, Caroline. [https://www.theguardian.com/music/2008/aug/15/urban1 Review: ''Sol-Angel and the Hadley St. Dreams'']. ''[[The Guardian]]''. Retrieved on July 22, 2009.</ref>\n\nKnowles' debut extended play ''True'' is a new wave album with Knowles stating, \"This is a dance record, but the lyrics can get pretty dark at times.\"<ref name=\"Murphy\">{{cite magazine|first=Keith|last=Murphy|title= A Long Convo With... Solange |url=http://www.vibe.com/content/long-convo-withsolange|date=July 7, 2010|magazine=[[Vibe (magazine)|Vibe]]|accessdate=July 7, 2010}}</ref> Knowles described the EP as \"eclectic with 1980s references and African percussion influences.\" Sonically the extended play is influenced by the keyboard sounds and beats of early 1980s pop and R&B music.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/music/reviews/w3d3 |title=Music \u2013 Review of Solange Knowles \u2013 True |publisher=BBC |date=January 1, 1970 |accessdate=May 14, 2014}}</ref> The EP was recorded in five cities including Santa Barbara, Los Angeles, Houston, New York, and on the German autobahn.<ref>{{cite magazine|url=http://www.elle.com/news/culture/solange-knowles-album-true |title=Solange Knowles New Album True \u2013 Solange Knowles Interview About Music |magazine=Elle |date=April 3, 2014 |accessdate=May 14, 2014}}</ref>\n\nAside from recording, Knowles occasionally paints as her hobby: \"I think that painting, for me, is such an affirmative expression in that sometimes you don't know what the outcome is gonna be and each stroke and each brush for me is an emotion and, in the end, it comes out as a piece which is the most amazing thing.&nbsp;... It definitely provides a different outlet.\"<ref name=\"BarkerDecided\"/>\n\n===Public image===\n[[File:Solange Knowles Cannes 2013.jpg|thumbnail|upright|Knowles at the [[2013 Cannes Film Festival]]]]\nKnowles has always been compared by the media to her sister, Beyonc\u00e9, whom she considers one of her role models. She has expressed her opinion of the comparison in the lyrics to \"God Given Name\": \"I'm not her and never will be\"<ref name=\"RamaswamySoul\"/><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.vibe.com/news/online_exclusives/2008/10/solange_volume_now/ |title=VOLUME NOW: Solange Knowles |last=Murphy |first=Keith |date=October 29, 2008 |work=[[Vibe (magazine)|Vibe]] |accessdate=December 11, 2008 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081223010940/http://www.vibe.com/news/online_exclusives/2008/10/solange_volume_now/ |archivedate=December 23, 2008 }}</ref> \u2013 which was purposely set as the opening track of ''Sol-Angel and the Hadley St. Dreams'' to show their differences.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/news/1044257/solange-steps-out-on-sophomore-solo-disc |title=Solange Steps Out on Sophomore Solo Disc |date=September 5, 2008 |work=Billboard |publisher=Nielsen Business Media |accessdate=January 31, 2009 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130704214635/http://www.billboard.com/articles/news/1044257/solange-steps-out-on-sophomore-solo-disc |archivedate=July 4, 2013 }}</ref> In his review for the album, Jody Rosen of ''Rolling Stone'' magazine referred to the lyrics as a declaration of independence.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/reviews/album/22684278/review/22712701/solangel__the_hadley_st_dreams|title=Solange Knowles: Sol-Angel & The Hadley St. Dreams |last=Rosen|first=Jody|date=September 4, 2008|work=Rolling Stone|accessdate=January 31, 2009}}</ref> Beyonc\u00e9 was unwilling to bring her sister into the recording industry, reasoning that it \"involves a lot of pressure\". Knowles countered by saying, \"It's good to have her advice, but we really have different goals\".<ref name=\"RamaswamySoul\"/> In her sister's self-titled album, Beyonc\u00e9 credits Knowles with the lyric \"my sister taught me I should speak my mind\", as she acknowledges the impact her family has made on her life.\n\nIn recent years, Knowles has also garnered considerable attention as a fashion icon. Her knack for bold colors, mixed prints and [[retro]] styles, as well as her knack for glamorous, fashion-forward looks in her music videography and public appearances, has become integral to her current image. She has been photographed wearing [[Alexander Wang (designer)|Alexander Wang]], [[Alexander McQueen]] and [[Chanel]]. The music video for her 2012 single \"Losing You\" featured a heavy demonstration of the contemporary sartorial movement throughout Africa, [[La Sape]].\n\nSimilarly, her decision to grow her [[Afro-textured hair|natural hair]] initially generated strong reactions from the public. In a cover interview with [[Toyin Ojih Odutola]] for Cultured Magazine, Knowles addressed her shift to minimalist fashion and the response she received from the public, \u201cThis idea that black women could not be minimalist, we could not be subtle\u2014 we have to be big, we have to be loud, we have to be an explosive presence.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.culturedmag.com/solange-knowles-toyin-ojih-odutola/|title=Solange Knowles and Toyin Ojih Odutola Talk Sound, Art and Architecture|date=February 19, 2018|website=Cultured Magazine|language=en-US|access-date=March 8, 2019}}</ref>\n\nAt the 2017 Glamour Women of the Year awards, Knowles wore a yellow [[Jean-Paul Gaultier]] couture gown and was named a Woman of the Year.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.vogue.com/article/solange-knowles-glamour-magazine-women-woman-of-the-year-awards |title=Only Solange Could Pull Off This Bright Yellow Jean Paul Gaultier Gown |author=Rachel Hahn |website=www.vogue.com |date=November 15, 2017|access-date=November 14, 2017}}</ref>\n\nKnowles is an activist for the Black Lives Matter movement and has openly made many statements in opposition to police brutality against African Americans.  On the day of the mass shooting at the Emanuel AME church in Charleston, South Carolina, Solange released a statement posing the following questions: \"Where can we be safe? Where can we be free? Where can we be black?\" Knowles has stated on several occasions that as a black woman, she is \"not really allowed to be mad\" without enforcing racial stereotypes, however, she has \"a lot to be mad about\".\n\nIn July 2016, she took to Twitter to critique police who were present at a peaceful protest in Baton Rouge, saying \"Protesters/marchers have been nothing but peaceful today in Baton Rouge. Police are here pulling out tear gas while children are around\" and  \"Most of the march/protest speakers in Baton Rouge were all under 17 years old... We all left feeling uplifted...Yet as I walked back to my car I personally saw @BRPD pulling huge assault rifles out on peaceful protesters....\"\n\nHer 2016 album, ''A Seat at The Table'', acknowledges the inequalities that black women face in America.  With songs like \"Mad\", \"Don't Touch My Hair\", and \"F.U.B.U\", Knowles addresses stereotypes of young, black Americans, such as criminality or the fixation people have on black women's natural hair, saying she's \"got the right to be mad\".\n\n==Other ventures==\nIn 2001, Knowles collaborated with Destiny's Child to sing the theme song for the Disney Channel show ''The Proud Family''.\n\nIn 2007, Knowles began promoting Baby Jamz, a [[hip hop]]-styled toy line for pre-schoolers.<ref name=\"Co-Publishing Deal\" /><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.nydailynews.com/entertainment/music/2008/06/17/2008-06-17_sister_act_solange_knowles_beyonces_youn.html|title=Sister act: Solange Knowles, Beyonce's younger sibling, comes into her own|last=Smith|first=Olivia|date=June 17, 2008|work=[[New York Daily News]]|accessdate=December 11, 2008}}</ref> It was inspired by her son, Julez, who is fond of hip hop music.<ref name=\"EdwardsFlying\" /> She is the executive producer of the CD, composed of updated hip hop inspired nursery rhymes, which is featured in all of the toys.<ref name=\"Co-Publishing Deal\" />\n\nIn 2008, Knowles was named as ambassador for [[Giorgio Armani]]'s younger diffusion line, Armani Jeans. Armani said Knowles epitomizes the style, which is a \"vision of a young, independent, casual lifestyle with a strong and cool, fashion sensibility\".<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.vogue.co.uk/news/daily/080731-solange-knowles-for-armani-jeans.aspx|title=Armani Says Solange|last=Barnett|first=Leisa|date=July 31, 2008|work=[[Vogue (magazine)|Vogue]]|accessdate=February 1, 2009|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080828232738/http://www.vogue.co.uk/news/daily/080731-solange-knowles-for-armani-jeans.aspx|archivedate=August 28, 2008}}</ref>\n\nKnowles has worked on the award-winning children's television series ''Yo Gabba Gabba!''. She performed \"Momma Loves Baby\" during the live performance when it toured the [[Dallas\u2013Fort Worth metroplex|Dallas\u2013Fort Worth]] area. She also performed \"Momma Loves Baby\" during a 2010 episode called \"Baby\".\n\nIn 2011, Knowles, along with Alejandra Ramos Munoz and [[Zooey Deschanel]], were announced as the new faces of [[Rimmel|Rimmel London]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.rimmellondon.com/us/en/ourfaces/ourmodels/solange-knowles |title=Solange Knowles |publisher=Rimmel London |accessdate=November 25, 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111128131449/http://www.rimmellondon.com/us/en/ourfaces/ourmodels/solange-knowles |archivedate=November 28, 2011  }}</ref>\n\nIn February 2012, Knowles became Vogue.com's \"Today I'm Wearing\" guest blogger, sharing a photograph of her outfits daily for a month.\n\nIn 2016 Knowles became [[Michael Kors]]' new face for his fashion works.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.google.it/search?ie=UTF-8&source=android-browser&q=michael/kors%20solange&gfe_rd=cr&ei=RrXFWMXaJ4zA8getjYGgAQ#gfe_rd=cr|title=michael/kors solange \u2013 Google Search|website=www.google.it|language=en|access-date=March 12, 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn 2017, Knowles became the face of a new [[Calvin Klein]] campaign.<ref>{{cite web |url= https://fashionista.com/2017/11/solange-calvin-klein-campaign |title= Solange Basically Casts Her Own Calvin Klein Campaign|publisher=}}</ref>\n\nIn 2018, Knowles received the artist of the year award from the Harvard Foundation.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://news.harvard.edu/gazette/story/2018/03/harvard-foundation-honors-solange-as-artist-of-the-year/|title=Solange visits as Harvard Foundation's artist of year|date=March 5, 2018|publisher=|accessdate=May 4, 2018}}</ref> \nShe became the face of [[Mercedes-Benz]]'s new campaign ''#WEWONDER''<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.essentialhommemag.com/mercedes-benz-presents-the-wewonder-campaign-with-solange/|title=MERCEDES-BENZ WITH SOLANGE|date=February 12, 2018|publisher=essentialhommemag.com|accessdate=August 9, 2018}}</ref> and [[Helmut Lang (fashion brand)|Helmut Lang]] fashion campaign.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.vogue.com/article/kanye-west-solange-helmut-lang-photos|title=Kanye West, Solange, and More Helmut Lang Collectors Star in the Label's New Project|date=January 4, 2018|publisher=vogue.com|accessdate=August 9, 2018}}</ref>\nShe has started a collaboration for interior design with [[IKEA]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/2018/jul/06/solange-collaboration-with-ikea|title=Swede dreams: what to expect from Solange's Saint Heron collaboration with Ikea|date=July 6, 2018|work=theguardian.com|accessdate=August 9, 2018}}</ref>\n\n===House of Der\u00e9on===\nKnowles and sister Beyonc\u00e9 modeled for their family's clothing line, [[House of Der\u00e9on]], named after their grandmother, Agn\u00e9z Der\u00e9on. She also helped launch Der\u00e9on, a junior apparel collection and a sister line to House of Der\u00e9on.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.ctv.ca/servlet/ArticleNews/story/CTVNews/20070816/Beyonce_Canada_070816/20070816?hub=CanadaAM|title=Beyonc\u00e9 launches her clothing line in Toronto|date=August 16, 2007|publisher=[[CTV News]]|accessdate=April 5, 2008}}</ref> Both sisters modeled for Der\u00e9on, and were featured in most of Der\u00e9on's marketing campaigns. Together they were featured in a \"[[Got Milk?]]\" campaign ad, wearing House of Der\u00e9on.\n\n==Personal life==\n\nKnowles married Daniel Smith on February 27, 2004 when she was 17 and he was 19.<ref name=\"EdwardsFlying\" /><ref>[http://www.people.com/people/archive/article/0,,20149623,00.html \"Crazy in Love\"]. ''People''. March 22, 2004.</ref> On October 18, 2004, Knowles gave birth to their son, Daniel Julez J. Smith Jr.<ref>{{cite web|last=Grossman|first=Wendy|author2=Peterson, Todd |date=October 26, 2004|title=Solange Knowles Gives Birth to a Boy|work=[[People (magazine)|People]]|publisher=[[Time Inc.|Time]]|url=http://www.people.com/people/article/0,,734570,00.html|accessdate=December 6, 2008}}</ref> Knowles calls her son the greatest unplanned blessing, but has partly expressed regret that she bore a child at an early age. A song she wrote for her baby, \"6 O'Clock Blues\", was included on ''Sol-Angel and the Hadley St. Dreams''.<ref name=\"S2SSolMMD\">{{cite web|url=http://www.s2smagazine.com/content/content.asp?issueid=200805&listid=03|title=Beyonc\u00e9's little sister Solange manages motherhood, music and a divorce|date=May 2008|work=[[Sister 2 Sister]]|accessdate=December 11, 2008 |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20080805015953/http://www.s2smagazine.com/content/content.asp?issueid=200805&listid=03 |archivedate = August 5, 2008}}</ref> After Julez's birth, the family moved to [[Moscow, Idaho]], where Knowles' husband continued studying in college.<ref name=\"KennedyChannels\" /> In October 2007, Knowles confirmed that she and Smith had divorced in an interview with ''[[Essence (magazine)|Essence]]'' magazine.<ref name=\"EdwardsFlying\" /> After the divorce, Knowles and her son moved to Los Angeles.<ref name=\"BarkerDecided\" /> In August 2013, Knowles announced that she and her son were moving to [[New Orleans]], Louisiana.\n\nOn May 12, 2014, [[TMZ]] released security video footage of Knowles physically assaulting brother-in-law, [[Jay-Z]] and being restrained by a security guard in an elevator at [[The Standard, High Line]], in Manhattan, following the 2014 [[Met Gala]]. Jay-Z remained passive and did not retaliate while her sister Beyonc\u00e9, who was also present, did not react to either party throughout the altercation.<ref name=\"tmz 20140512\">{{cite web|url=http://www.tmz.com/2014/05/12/jay-z-solange-fight-elevator-video-beyonce-met-gala/ |title=Jay Z Attacked By Solange Knowles \u2013 Beyonce's Sister's Physical Attack |publisher=TMZ.com |accessdate=May 14, 2014}}</ref> The footage and story went [[Viral video|viral]], but the reason for the altercation remains unknown.<ref>\n*{{cite web|url=http://globalnews.ca/news/1326108/watch-beyonces-sister-solange-attacks-jay-z-in-elevator/|title=Beyonce's sister Solange attacks Jay Z in elevator|work=Global News|first=John|last=Kennedy|date=May 12, 2014|accessdate=May 12, 2014}}\n*{{cite web|url=http://www.nme.com/news/solange/77262|title=Beyonce's sister Solange allegedly filmed attacking Jay Z in lift \u2013 watch|work=[[NME]]|date=May 12, 2014|accessdate=May 12, 2014}}\n*{{cite news|url=http://www.nydailynews.com/entertainment/gossip/solange-knowles-kicks-punches-claws-jay-z-met-gala-after-party-article-1.1789023 |title=Solange Knowles kicks, punches, claws Jay Z in elevator video at Met Gala after-party |newspaper=NY Daily News |accessdate=May 14, 2014}}</ref>\nMatthew Knowles, however, has hinted that the incident may have been faked for attention, saying: \"So you sometimes have to ignite that tour. It's called a Jedi mind trick. The Jedi mind trick fools you a lot...all I know is the Jedi mind trick. Everyone's talking about it. Ticket sales went up. Solange's album sales went up 200%!\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.designntrend.com/articles/18596/20140828/matthew-knowles-hints-jay-z-beyonce-faked-solange-gate-elevator.htm|title=Matthew Knowles Hints That Jay Z And Beyonce Fake'd The 'Solange Gate' Elevator Incident To Sale 'On The Run' Tour Tickets|last=Design&Trend|date=August 28, 2014|accessdate=May 23, 2017|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170326222623/http://www.designntrend.com/articles/18596/20140828/matthew-knowles-hints-jay-z-beyonce-faked-solange-gate-elevator.htm|archivedate=March 26, 2017}}</ref> The cause is rumored to be Jay-Z's infidelity, which the couple would address on their respective albums ''[[Lemonade (Beyonc\u00e9 album)|Lemonade]]'', ''[[4:44 (album)|4:44]]'', and their joint album ''[[Everything Is Love]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bustle.com/articles/158174-how-beyonces-lemonade-changes-the-way-we-look-at-the-2014-met-gala-elevator-incident|title=How Beyonce's 'Lemonade' Changes The Way We Look at the 2014 Met Gala Elevator Incident|first=Nicole|last=Pomarico|publisher=|accessdate=May 23, 2017}}</ref>\n\nOn November 16, 2014, Knowles married music video director Alan Ferguson at the [[Marigny Opera House]] in New Orleans, Louisiana.<ref name=\"people\" /><ref>{{cite news|last1=Ethan|first1=Sacks|title=Solange Knowles marries longtime boyfriend Alan Ferguson in New Orleans wedding|url=http://www.nydailynews.com/entertainment/gossip/solange-knowles-set-marry-longtime-boyfriend-article-1.2012891|newspaper=New York Daily News|accessdate=November 17, 2014}}</ref> On November 1, 2019, Knowles revealed on her Instagram account that she and Ferguson had separated earlier that year.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.vibe.com/2019/11/solange-separates-from-alan-ferguson|title=Solange Knowles Posts Optimistic Message In Midst Of Separation From Alan Ferguson|work=Vibe|language=en|access-date=December 10, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://madamenoire.com/1110766/solange-confirms-her-divorce-after-months-of-speculation-early-this-year-we-separated-and-parted-ways/|title=Solange Confirms Her Separation From Alan Ferguson After Months Of Speculation: \"Early This Year We Separated And Parted Ways\"|last=Kelly|first=Keyaira|date=November 1, 2019|website=MadameNoire|access-date=November 1, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Discography==\n{{main|Solange Knowles discography}}\n* ''[[Solo Star]]'' (2002)\n* ''[[Sol-Angel and the Hadley St. Dreams]]'' (2008)\n* ''[[A Seat at the Table]]'' (2016)\n* ''[[When I Get Home (album)|When I Get Home]]'' (2019)\n\n==Tours==\n'''Headlining'''\n*Solo Star Tour (2003)\n*The Art of Love Tour (2008)\n*Solange Presents Sol-Angel and the Hadley St. Dreams Tour (2008)\n*[[True EP|True Promo Tour]] (2012)\n*Orion's Rise (2017)\n'''Supporting'''\n*[[Simply Deeper Tour]] (2003)\n*[[The Justified World Tour]] (2003-2004)\n\n==Filmography==\n===Film===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|- style=\"background:#ccc; text-align:center;\"\n!Year\n!Title\n!Role\n!Notes\n|-\n| 2004 || ''[[Johnson Family Vacation]]'' || Nikki Johnson ||\n|-\n| 2006 || ''[[Bring It On: All or Nothing]]'' || Camille || Credited as Solange Knowles-Smith\n|-\n| 2019 || ''[[Homecoming (2019 film)| Homecoming]]'' || Herself || Cameo\n|}\n\n===Television===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|- style=\"background:#ccc; text-align:cen